                        <outline text="A novel multi-criteria dual simplex method based on matrix pencils. #MPS #h #slide #novel:algorithm #novel:slow" _note="Paper section: https://dynalist.io/d/F6qJJul5x4JWwZ4KTrIffFqu#z=nk1d_NXdPnoKq3ID5pQQCvIY" colorLabel="1">
                            <outline text="The Method #h ">
<outline text="Background and Context #slide ">
    <outline text="The Dual Simplex Method " _note="https://dynalist.io/d/gcskC8EanDTKsGE-U8yP7HPC#z=04vhTiIdMmr5II6NPB3ax6LB"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Intro #slide ">
    <outline text="The algorithm views the linear system of equations used in the dual simplex method as a bilinear linear matrix pencil equation. "/>
    <outline text="This can be written using non-basic and basic variables as">
        <outline text="$$x^\top(A-vD)y+\hat{x}\hat{y}=0$$">
            <outline text="$$x^\top(A-vD)y+\hat{x}^\top(I-\hat{v}{D})\hat{y}=0$$ #wfe-ignore-item "/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="where $$x\ge 0,\hat{x}\ge 0,y\ge 0,\hat{y}\ge 0$$."/>
</outline>
<outline text="View as Linear Matrix Pencil Equation #slide ">
    <outline text="Setting #simplex:augmented ">
        <outline text="Canonical form can be written as">
            <outline text="$$x^\top(A-vbc^\top)y+\hat{x}^\top(\alpha I-{\beta}{bc^\top})\hat{y}=0$$"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="where $$x\ge 0,\hat{x}\ge 0,\hat{y}\ge 0$$."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Assumptions">
        <outline text="The matrix pencil $$A-\lambda {bc^\top}$$ is regular."/>
        <outline text="The unique finite eigenvalue of this regular matrix pencil is positive. "/>
        <outline text="Note: this excludes the case where $$bc^\top$$ is nilpotent."/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Relationships and Assumptions #slide ">
    <outline text="$$A$$ is invertible"/>
    <outline text="$$D=BC^\top$$ rank-factorisation"/>
    <outline text="$$A-\lambda D$$ is a regular matrix pencil"/>
    <outline text="Assumption: $$D$$ is not nilpotent "/>
    <outline text="$$V=C^\top A^{-1}B$$"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Tableau Notation #slide ">
    <outline text="We extend the classical compact tableau notation as follows:">
        <outline text="$$\begin{array}{|c|c|} \hline A &amp; B\\ \hline C^\top &amp; V\\ \hline \end{array}$$"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="The expanded tableau is:">
        <outline text="$$\begin{array}{|c|c|c|} \hline A &amp; I &amp; B\\ \hline I &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\ \hline C^\top &amp; 0 &amp; V\\ \hline \end{array}$$"/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Initialisation #slide #simplex:init ">
    <outline text="We start with $$x=y=0$$, $$v=0$$ and a basic solution that may be infeasible, given as follows:">
        <outline text="Let $$\lambda\neq 0$$ be an eigenvalue of $$D$$ with corresponding eigenvectors $$\hat{x}^\top, \hat{y}$$ and define $$\hat{v}=1/\lambda$$. "/>
        <outline text="Then $$(\hat{v},\hat{x}^\top, \hat{y})$$ is a generalised eigensystem of $$I-\lambda{D}$$. "/>
        <outline text="Subject to the substitution $$A\leftarrow A+aD$$ for a suitable real number $$a$$ we can assume $$\hat{v}&gt;0$$. "/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Reduction Step (I) #slide #simplex:pivot ">
    <outline text="We partition the matrix $$A$$ into $$rs$$ blocks ($$1\le r \le m$$, $$1\le s \le n$$), with matching row and column dimensions:">
        <outline text="$$A=\begin{pmatrix} A_{11} &amp; \cdots &amp; A_{1j} &amp; \cdots &amp; A_{1s} \\ \vdots &amp;  &amp; \vdots &amp;  &amp; \vdots \\ A_{i1} &amp; \cdots &amp; A_{ij} &amp; \cdots &amp; A_{is} \\ \vdots &amp;  &amp; \vdots &amp;  &amp; \vdots \\A_{r1} &amp; \cdots &amp; A_{rj} &amp; \cdots &amp; A_{rs} \\ \end{pmatrix}$$"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Let $$B$$ and $$C^\top$$ be partitioned accordingly"/>
    <outline text="We can pick a block-index pair $$(i,j)$$ as block-pivot, if $$A_{ij}$$ is square and $$A_{ij}-\lambda B_{ij}C_{ij}^\top$$ is a regular matrix pencil with at least one real, positive eigenvalue $$\mu$$ and corresponding eigenvectors $$x^\top_\mu, y_\mu$$ that are not both nonnegative"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Reduction Step (II) #slide #simplex:pivot ">
    <outline text="Primal (Row/Left-Multiplication)">
        <outline text="The new matrices $$\tilde{A}$$ and $$\tilde{B}$$ are obtained through left-multiplication of a suitable matrix $$P$$ and swapping basic and non-basic variables"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Dual (Column/Row-Multiplication)">
        <outline text="The new matrices $$\tilde{A}$$ and $$\tilde{C}$$ are obtained through right-multiplication of a suitable matrix $$Q$$ and swapping basic and non-basic variables"/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Reduction Step (III) #slide #simplex:pivot ">
    <outline text="One has">
        <outline text="$$\tilde{A}_{ij}=$$"/>
        <outline text="$$\tilde{R}_i=$$"/>
        <outline text="$$\tilde{C}^\top_j=$$"/>
        <outline text="$$\tilde{V}=V-Q^\top A^{-1}P$$"/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Normalisation Step #slide ">
    <outline text=""/>
</outline>
<outline text="Termination #slide ">
    <outline text="$$D=LR^\top$$, $$L,R^\top\ge 0, A^{-1}L\ge 0, R^\top A^{-1}\ge 0 \Rightarrow A-vD$$ has a nonnegative eigenvalue and semipositive eigenvector. "/>
</outline>
<outline text="Theorem."/>
<outline text="The following statements are equivalent:">
    <outline text="$$A_{11}-\lambda B_{11}$$ is an active / Thompson-Weil sub-pencil"/>
    <outline text="algebraic formulation"/>
    <outline text="The block-pivot"/>
</outline>
