                            <outline text="Pseudo-Linear Algebra #h">
<outline text="Introduction #slide ">
    <outline text="Introduced by Jacobson (1937) as a unifying framework for linear differential and difference equations/systems "/>
    <outline text="Computer Algebra use by e.g. Bronstein \&amp; Petkovsek (1996), Bronstein (2000), Barkatou (2006) and Barkatou, Broughton \&amp; Pfluegel (2008, 2010)"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Concepts #slide ">
    <outline text="We need some notations:">
        <outline text="$$F$$ a field"/>
        <outline text="$$\phi$$ a $$K$$-automorphism of $$F$$"/>
        <outline text="$$\delta$$ a pseudo-derivation w.r.t. $$\phi$$, i.e.">
            <outline text="$$\delta(fg) = \delta f \phi g + f\delta g$$"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="One can show: if $$\phi \neq \text{id}$$, then $$\exists \gamma \in F: \delta = \gamma(\phi - \text{id})$$.">
        <outline text=""/>
    </outline>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Systems of Pseudo-Linear Equations #h ">
<outline text="Introduction #slide ">
    <outline text="System of Pseudo-Linear Equations:">
        <outline text="$$\delta Y(\tau) = A(\tau) \phi Y(\tau)$$"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="with $$A \in F^{n \times n}$$. This unifies common types of linear functional equations."/>
    <outline text="If $$\phi \neq \text{id}$$, the system can be represented in different formats:">
        <outline text="$$\phi Y(\tau) = A(\tau) Y(\tau)$$"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="or">
        <outline text="$$\delta Y(\tau) = A(\tau) Y(\tau)$$."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Conversions between formats can be done efficiently."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Local Solutions #h ">
    <outline text="Aims and Objectives #slide ">
        <outline text="Ultimate aim: efficiently compute symbolic solutions of systems of linear functional equations."/>
        <outline text="Objectives:">
            <outline text="To give a unifying theoretical framework for defining irregular parts of formal solutions."/>
            <outline text="To provide a generic algorithm that can compute irregular parts efficiently."/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="This is joint work with M. Barkatou and G. Broughton."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Formal Solutions of Pseudo-Linear Equations #h ">
        <outline text="Irregular Parts #h ">
            <outline text="Singular Systems of Pseudo-Linear Equations #slide ">
                <outline text="Additional notations:">
                    <outline text="$$F = K((\tau))$$"/>
                    <outline text="$$v: F\longrightarrow \Z\cup\{\infty\}$$ a valuation defined by">
                        <outline text="$$v(f) = \left \{\begin{array}{lcl} m &amp; \mbox{if }&amp; f=\tau^{m}(f_{0}+f_{1}\tau + \ldots), f_{0} \neq 0, \\ \infty &amp; \mbox{if }&amp; f = 0. \end{array}\right.$$"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="$$\omega \in \Z$$ defined by $$\omega(\D) =v(\delta(\tau)) - v(\tau)$$."/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Also assume $$v(\phi(f)) = v(f) \;\;\;\forall f \in F$$. "/>
                <outline text="A singular system of pseudo-linear equations is:">
                    <outline text="$$\tau^{r-\omega}\delta Y(\tau) = A(\tau) \phi Y(\tau)$$"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="with $$r \in \N$$ (the \emph{Poincar\'{e}-rank}) and $$A \in K[[\tau]]^{n \times n}$$."/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Local Characteristics #slide ">
                <outline text="We define the quantities $$c, q \in K^{\ast}$$ from the definition of $$\phi$$ and $$\delta$$:">
                    <outline text="$$\phi(\tau) = q\tau + O(\tau^{2})$$"/>
                    <outline text="$$\tau^{-\omega}\delta(\tau) = c\tau + O(\tau^{2})$$"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="We then have inductively for $$h \in \N^{+}$$">
                    <outline text="$$\phi(\tau^{h})  =  q^{h}\tau^{h} + O(\tau^{h+1})$$,"/>
                    <outline text="$$\tau^{-\omega}\delta(\tau^{h}) = c [h]_{q}\tau^{h} + O(\tau^{h+1})$$"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="where">
                    <outline text="$$[\lambda]_q = \left \{\begin{array}{lcr} \frac{1-q^{\lambda}}{1-q} &amp; \text{if}&amp; q \neq 1, \\ \lambda &amp; \text{if}&amp; q = 1. \end{array}\right.$$"/>
                </outline>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Examples #slide ">
                <outline text="Linear Differential Systems:">
                    <outline text="$$\phi = \text{id}, \; \delta = \frac{d}{d\tau}, \; \omega = -1, \; q=1, \; c=1$$"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Linear Difference Systems:">
                    <outline text="$$\phi(\tau) = \frac{\tau}{\tau+1}, \; \delta = \phi - \text{id}, \; \omega = 1, \; q=1, \; c=-1$$"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Linear $$q$$-Difference Systems:">
                    <outline text="$$\phi(\tau) = q\tau, \; \delta = \phi - \text{id}, \; \omega = 0, \; q \neq 1, \; c=q-1$$"/>
                </outline>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Classification of Singularities #slide">
                <outline text="%\begin{definition}"/>
                <outline text="%\label{first_kind} A local system of the form"/>
                <outline text="%(\ref{pseudo_lin_sys}) is said to be of the \emph{first kind}"/>
                <outline text="%if for its Poincar\'{e}-rank $$r$$, we have $$r=0$$."/>
                <outline text="%\end{definition}"/>
                <outline text="Let $$ T \in \GLn{\F}$$. Change of variable">
                    <outline text="$$Y=TZ$$"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="leads to"/>
                <outline text="\emph{equivalent} system $$\tau^{-\omega} \D Z = B \Aut Z$$"/>
                <outline text="where"/>
                <outline text="$$B = T^{-1} (A \Aut T -\tau^{-\omega} \D T) =:T_{\delta,\phi}[A]$$"/>
                <outline text="#definition">
                    <outline text="System (\ref{pseudo_lin_sys}) is called \emph{regular singular} if $$\exists$$ $$T_{\delta, \phi} $$ such that  $$T_{\delta , \phi}[A]$$ is of \emph{first kind}, i.e. $$r=0$$. Otherwise, it is called \emph{irregular singular}."/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Barkatou \&amp; Broughton \&amp; Pfluegel (2010): Regular Singular Case \&amp; Incomplete FMS in Irregular Singular Case\    "/>
                <outline text="New Goal: find complete FMS of irregular system."/>
            </outline>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Regular Solutions #h "/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Formal Reduction #h ">
        <outline text="Formal Reduction #slide " _note="&#xA;The formal reduction of linear systems of functional equations with meromorphic coefficients is a method used to simplify and solve such systems. &#xA;The method involves reducing the system of equations to a simpler form by making use of the analytic properties of the coefficients, such as their poles and residues. ">
            <outline text="Idea: transform into simpler system -- lower $$r$$, decrease $$n$$"/>
            <outline text="Originally established for differential systems"/>
            <outline text="Transformations:">
                <outline text="Changes of variable $$Y=TZ$$,"/>
                <outline text="Changes of variable $$Y = e_{r,\mu}Z$$ where $$e_{r,\mu}$$ is a suitable scalar function,"/>
                <outline text="Substituting $$\tau = \tilde{\tau}^{s}$$ with $$s\in \N$$, $$s&gt;1$$."/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Problems:">
                <outline text="How to compute $$T$$?"/>
                <outline text="How to define $$e_{r,\mu}$$?"/>
                <outline text="How to find ramifications?"/>
            </outline>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Approaches -- Overview #slide ">
            <outline text="Approaches in the literature: 2 schools">
                <outline text=" Traditional">
                    <outline text="Use of Shearing transformations"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Algorithmic">
                    <outline text="Use of Moser and/or super reduction"/>
                    <outline text="Care about introducing algebraic extensions of ground field "/>
                </outline>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Main differences:"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Basic Operations #h ">
            <outline text="Gauge-Transformation #slide">
                <outline text="Let $$T(x)$$ be invertible square matrix function. The change of variable">
                    <outline text="$$y = Tz$$"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="transforms system (\ref{system}) into">
                    <outline text="$$x^{r+1}\frac{dz}{dx} = \tilde{A}z $$"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="where">
                    <outline text="$$ \tilde{A} = T[A] :=  T^{-1}AT - x^{r+1}T^{-1}\frac{dT}{dx}$$."/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="We call (\ref{system}) and (\ref{tildesystem}) ($$A$$ and $$\tilde{A}$$ respectively) {\em equivalent}. "/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Exponential Shift #slide "/>
            <outline text="Splitting Lemma #slide ">
                <outline text="Consider (\ref{system}) and assume that $$A_0$$ is block-diagonal ">
                    <outline text="$$ A_0 = \left(\begin{array}{cc}  A_0^{11} &amp; 0 \\  0 &amp; A_0^{22} \\\end{array}\right)$$"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="such that $$\rho(A_0^{11})\cap\rho(A_0^{22})=\emptyset.$$"/>
                <outline text="Then there exists a formal analytical transformation of the form">
                    <outline text="$$T(x) = \sum_{j = 0}^{\infty}T_j x^{j}\quad (T_0 = I)$$"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="such that the transformed system is block-diagonal with the same block partition as in $$A_0$$."/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Shearing Transformation #slide ">
                <outline text="Gauge-Transformation using diagonal matrix ">
                    <outline text="$$S=\text{diag}(x^{s_1},\ldots,x^{s_n})$$ "/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="where $$s_i\in\mathbb{Q}$$. The transformed system is ">
                    <outline text="$$\delta(Y)=B\phi(Y)$$ "/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="where">
                    <outline text="$$B=S[A]=S^{-1}A\phi(S)-\delta(S)$$."/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="This means $$b_{ij}=a_{ij}x^{s_i-s_j}-\text{diag}(\delta(x^{s_i})/\theta(x^{s_i})$$ and">
                    <outline text="$$\text{val}(b_{ij})=$$"/>
                    <outline text="$$\text{lc}(b_{ij})=$$"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="In order to be useful for formal reduction, the new matrix needs to satisfy">
                    <outline text="$$\text{val}(B)&gt;\text{val}(A)$$. "/>
                </outline>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Ramification #slide ">
                <outline text="This could introduce __ramifications__. "/>
            </outline>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Advanced Operations #h ">
            <outline text="Moser-Reduction #h "/>
            <outline text="Super-Reduction #h "/>
            <outline text="Katz-Invariant #h"/>
            <outline text="Generalised Splitting Lemma #slide "/>
            <outline text="Rational (Root-free) Splitting Lemma #h ">
                <outline text="Splitting Lemma for $$ (\omega, P)$$-Commutative  Systems #slide ">
                    <outline text="#lemma:commutative_splitting ">
                        <outline text="Consider the system (\ref{qsystem}) and assume that $$\hat{A}$$ is $$(\omega, P)$$-commutative with $$\hat{A}_p$$ and $$P$$ block-diagonal with blocks of same dimension">
                            <outline text="$$\hat{A}_p = \left(\begin{array}{cc}\hat{A}_p^{11} &amp; 0 \\0 &amp; \hat{A}_p^{22} \\ \end{array}\right),\quad P =\left(\begin{array}{cc}P^{11} &amp; 0 \\0 &amp; P^{22}\\ \end{array}\right)$$"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="such that">
                            <outline text="$$\wpspec(\hat{A}_p^{11})\cap\wpspec(\hat{A}_p^{22})=\emptyset.$$"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Then there exists a $$(\omega, P)$$-commutative $$q $$-meromorphic transformation of the form">
                            <outline text="$$\hat{T}(x) =\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}T_jx^{j/q}\quad (T_0 = I)$$ #equation "/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="such that the transformed system is $$(\omega, P)$$-commutative and block-diagonal with the same block partition as in $$\hat{A}_p $$ and $$P $$."/>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Rational Splitting Lemma #slide ">
                    <outline text="#proposition">
                        <outline text="Consider a system as in ( #qsystem) with leading matrix $$\hat{A}_p$$ and let $$q\geq 2$$. The following statements are equivalent:">
                            <outline text="There exists a system as in ( #qsystem) and a generalised Shearing-transformation $$\tilde{S}$$ of ramifications index $$q$$ such that $$\tilde{S}[A]=\hat{A}$$."/>
                            <outline text="The system ( #qsystem) is $$(\omega, \tilde{P})$$-commutative, the matrix $$\tilde{P}$$ is similar to a diagonal matrix and $$\text{spec}(\tilde{P})\subseteq\{1,\omega,\omega^2,\ldots,\omega^{q-1}\} $$."/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Furthermore, if $$\lambda$$ is an eigenvalue of $$\hat{A}_{p}$$ with multiplicity $$s$$, the numbers $$\omega\lambda,\ldots,\omega^{(q-1)}\lambda$$ are all eigenvalues of the same multiplicity $$s$$."/>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
            </outline>
        </outline>
    </outline>
