    <outline text="Game Analysis #slide ">
        <outline text="The analysis of this presented security game is not difficult, it can be shown that there are no pure Nash equilibrium strategies as [..] and hence a closed-form expression exists \cite{} for determining the values $$p^{*} = \frac{c^{\mathcal{A}}}{l^{\mathcal{D}}} = 1 - \frac{c^{\mathcal{A}}}{l^{\mathcal{D}}}$$ and $$q^{*} = \frac{c^{\mathcal{D}}}{l^{\mathcal{D}}}$$ forming a mixed Nash equilibrium strategy $$(s_D^{*}, s_A^{*})$$ where $$p^*$$ and $$q^*$$ are the probability of defense and attack respectively. "/>
        <outline text="This will be the underlying method to compute our attack likelihood in this scenario, based on $$q^*$$."/>
        <outline text="One verifies that the expected utilities in this case are $$ u_D^{*} = -c^{\mathcal{D}} $$ and $$ u_A^{*} = 0 $$."/>
