<outline text="2. Add CVSS metrics to the utility functions #h">
    <outline text="Move to CVSS #slide ">
        <outline text="We  now use CVSS to specify the payoff functions of the single-target security game of the previous section.  "/>
        <outline text="To achieve this aim, we will use the CVSS impact and exploitability sub-scores. "/>
        <outline text="Our aim is only use this publicly available scoring data, as we are assuming a complete information game."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Approach #slide ">
        <outline text="The loss for the defender is due to the attack impact, which will be modelled as a function of the CVSS impact sub-score: $$l^{\mathcal{D}} =f({\mu}_{Imp})$$. "/>
        <outline text="Furthermore we assume that the defender applies the principle of adequate protection [@pfleeger] by investing an amount for defence that is proportional to the loss: $$c^{\mathcal{D}} \sim f({\mu}_{Imp})$$ where $$f$$ is linear. "/>
        <outline text="The attack cost depends on the CVSS exploitability subscore, taking into account that high score values indicate a vulnerability that is easy to exploit: $$c^{\mathcal{A}} = g({\mu_{Exp}})$$."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="CVSS Game #slide ">
        <outline text="We start with the following game:"/>
        <outline text="$$\begin{array}{ | c | c | c | } \mathcal{D} \downarrow \mathcal{A}\rightarrow &amp; a&amp; \overline{a} \\ d &amp;?,?&amp; ?, 0 \\ \overline{d} &amp;? ,?&amp; 0, 0 \end{array}$$ #normal" colorLabel="3"/>
    </outline>
</outline>
