<outline text="Example: Case Study 2 #slide ">
    <outline text="The analysis of the previous game can be used for the vulnerability patching scenario."/>
    <outline text="The goal is to find realistic values for the game payoff parameters $$l^D$$ and $$c^A$$."/>
    <outline text="This could be done for example using the __Common Vulnerability Scoring System__ (CVSS)."/>
    <outline text="Information about the severity of the vulnerability is publicly available online."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Case Study 2 (continued) #slide ">
    <outline text="The attacker's cost $$c^A$$ is proportional to the inverse of the CVSS __exploitability subscore__:">
        <outline text="$$c^A = \alpha \cdot {\mu_{E}}^{-1} $$."/>
        <outline text="Here, $$\alpha$$ is a constant that needs to be suitably defined."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="The loss of the defender $$l^D$$ is due to a threat event impact, exploiting the vulnerability and affecting the asset's CIA security requirements."/>
    <outline text="Using the CVSS impact subscore, a vector $$V$$ with numerical components is defined, depending on the security criticality of the asset. ">
        <outline text="This yields $$l^D =   \mu_{Imp, C} \cdot V_C + \mu_{Imp, I} \cdot V_I + \mu_{Imp, A} \cdot V_A$$."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Finally, by plugging this into the game solutions, a recommendation can be made for the decision to patch the vulnerability."/>
</outline>
