                            <outline text="GREY HAT HACKERS ARE PROBLEMATIC">
<outline text="Motivation #slide ">
    <outline text="Slide Title: Black Hat Hackers">
        <outline text="Black hat hackers are criminals who act with malicious intent."/>
        <outline text="Their motivation is often financial gain or revenge.">
            <outline text="They may also release malware that destroys files, holds computers hostage, or steals personal information."/>
            <outline text="Black hats spread havoc wherever they go, often causing serious damage to individuals and organizations alike."/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Sometimes they target people they strongly disagree with for ideological reasons."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Slide Title: Gray Hat Hackers">
        <outline text="Gray hat hackers engage in a mix of both black and white hat activities."/>
        <outline text="They may look for system vulnerabilities without permission or knowledge from the owner, and may report any issues found to the owner for a small fee."/>
        <outline text="Gray hats may sometimes violate laws or ethical standards but usually lack the malicious intent of black hat hackers."/>
        <outline text="They may believe they are doing good for companies by hacking into their systems, but owners rarely appreciate unauthorized access to their business information infrastructure."/>
        <outline text="Often, the real intention of gray hats is to showcase their skills and gain publicity and recognition for contributing to cybersecurity."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Slide Title: Definition of a White Hat Hacker">
        <outline text="A white hat hacker is a computer security expert who specializes in finding vulnerabilities in systems and networks."/>
        <outline text="Unlike black hat hackers, white hat hackers use their skills for ethical and lawful purposes, such as testing and improving the security of computer systems and networks."/>
        <outline text="White hat hackers may be hired by organizations to conduct penetration testing or vulnerability assessments to identify potential weaknesses in their systems."/>
        <outline text="They may also participate in bug bounty programs, where companies offer rewards to hackers who identify and report vulnerabilities in their systems."/>
        <outline text="White hat hackers may also develop and promote security best practices, and may work with law enforcement or other organizations to help combat cybercrime."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="__Black hat hacker definition__">
        <outline text="__Black hat hackers are criminals who break into computer networks with malicious intent. They may also release malware that destroys files, holds computers hostage, or steals passwords, credit card numbers, and other personal information.__"/>
        <outline text="__Black hats are motivated by self-serving reasons, such as financial gain, revenge, or simply to spread havoc. Sometimes their motivation might be ideological, by targeting people they strongly disagree with.__"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="__White hat hacker definition__">
        <outline text="__White hat hackers  sometimes also called ethical hackers or good hackers  are the antithesis of black hats. They exploit computer systems or networks to identify their security flaws so they can make recommendations for improvement__"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="__Gray hat hacker definition__">
        <outline text="__Somewhere between white and black are gray hat hackers. Gray hat hackers enact a blend of both black hat and white hat activities. Gray hat hackers often look for vulnerabilities in a system without the owner's permission or knowledge. If issues are found, they report them to the owner, sometimes requesting a small fee to fix the problem.__"/>
        <outline text="__A grey hat is a computer hacker or computer security expert who may sometimes violate laws or typical ethical standards, but usually does not have the malicious intent typical of a black hat hacker.__"/>
        <outline text="__Some gray hat hackers like to believe they are doing something good for companies by hacking their websites and invading their networks without permission. Still, company owners rarely appreciate unauthorized forays into their business information infrastructure.__"/>
        <outline text="__Often, a gray hat's real intention is to show off their skills and gain publicity  maybe even appreciation  for what they consider a contribution to cybersecurity.__"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="https://www.kaspersky.com/resource-center/definitions/hacker-hat-types"/>
</outline>
