                            <outline text="SIMPLE GAME #wfe-ignore-item ">
<outline text="Part I -- Designing The Game  #eyo-style:Section #wfe-ignore-item ">
    <outline text="HaaS Scenario #slide " complete="true">
        <outline text="Employees in an organisation are used as human sensors "/>
        <outline text="They report on cyber security incidents they encounter "/>
        <outline text="Organisation needs to decide whether they can trust an incoming report $$r$$ (or its absence)"/>
        <outline text="Reports have the following properties:">
            <outline text="Could report incidents only, or also their absence"/>
            <outline text="For the most general scenario: they could be externally attacked (modified, delayed or fabricated)"/>
            <outline text="Could be synchronous or asynchronous"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Reports -- Examples #slide" complete="true">
        <outline text="Alice reports:">
            <outline text="&quot;I have received a spam email at 8:10h, which was not detected by the spam filter&quot;"/>
            <outline text="&quot;While browsing the web for free tools that could be used for our project, I have discovered a freeware website that contains links to some malware&quot;"/>
            <outline text="&quot;Within the last seven days of the reporting period, there were three replies to the company's Twitter feed that appear to mislead potential customers&quot;"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Human Sensor System #slide " complete="true">
        <outline text="Human sensor has internal fault $$f$$ and/or external fault (vulnerability) $$v$$">
            <outline text="Faults = human lack of willingness to contribute to the security of the organisation "/>
            <outline text="Vulnerabilities = Weaknesses in personality traits leading to exploitation by social engineering attacks"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Here $$f$$ has fault mode: Byzantine rather than fault-stop #wfe-ignore-item "/>
        <outline text="Blurring traditional boundaries: fault can be deliberate"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Human-made Faults #slide " complete="true">
        <outline text="![](https://dynalist.io/u/YvZWuj6z_yyqithSACMX1tw_)( human-made-faults.png) #eyo-style:Normal "/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Assumptions #slide " complete="true">
        <outline text="Public information, known to all players:">
            <outline text="Specific game theoretic model, comprising of game type and payoff  functions, including solution algorithm "/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Private information:">
            <outline text="The human sensor knows his own type (based on previous experience, appraisal or self observation/reflection)."/>
            <outline text="The report receiver does not know the human sensor's type."/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="The reports are sent through a secure channel."/>
        <outline text="The users are competent in their non-security related job tasks"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="HaaS Sensor Types #slide " complete="true">
        <outline text="Human sensor is not necessarily competent in security. "/>
        <outline text="The human sensor could be cooperative or uncooperative."/>
        <outline text="Using formal terminology: human sensor might have faults and/or vulnerabilities">
            <outline text="have a vulnerability (unknowingly -- socially engineered)"/>
            <outline text="a fault (deliberately)"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Human sensor could also turn malicious. "/>
        <outline text="We obtain 3 different types. "/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Type 1: Cooperative Human Sensor #slide" complete="true">
        <outline text=" Is willing to help with security but potentially lacking in precision/reliability ">
            <outline text="Could be socially engineered (externally attacked)"/>
            <outline text="Could have insufficient cyber skills to recognise security anomalies"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Type 2 and 3: Uncooperative Human Sensor #slide " complete="true">
        <outline text="Type 2: Could be deliberately unreliable and apply minimal effort in contribution to overall security ">
            <outline text="lazy -- give it low priority"/>
            <outline text="distracted -- too focused on non-security job aspects"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Type 3: Could be malicious  (internal threat/attacker), wanting to create harm.">
            <outline text="disgruntled (seeking emotional reward), "/>
            <outline text="greedy (seeking financial reward)"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="GAME #wfe-ignore-item ">
        <outline text="Scenario -- Sensor #slide " complete="true">
            <outline text="Player: Human Sensor $$H$$ ($$S$$ in reference game)"/>
            <outline text="Strategies: Human sensor $$\mathcal{H}$$ has three pure strategies $$s^\mathcal{H}\in \{c, a, n\}$$:">
                <outline text="$$c$$ -- cooperate and to send the perceived correct report (and to benefit from increased esteem, or being paid a bounty)"/>
                <outline text="$$a$$ -- perform an attack by giving misleading reports(in order to get a psychological &quot;kick&quot; or some other financial reward from a cyber criminal)"/>
                <outline text="$$n$$ -- not sending a report at all (as too lazy and preferring to &quot;get on with the job&quot;)"/>
            </outline>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Scenario -- Report Receiver #slide " complete="true">
            <outline text="Player: Report Receiving Organisation $$R$$ ($$R$$ in reference game)"/>
            <outline text="Strategies: Report receiver $$\mathcal{R}$$ has two pure strategies $$s^\mathcal{R}\in \{t_r,\overline{t}_r\}$$ : ">
                <outline text="$$t_r$$ -- to trust the received report (and to benefit from its content to improve national security)"/>
                <outline text="$$\overline{t}_r$$ -- to not trust (to prevent damage, either by recognising the reporting node as malicious or as unreliable)"/>
            </outline>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Cost Benefit Model -- Human Sensor #slide " complete="true">
            <outline text="Benefit">
                <outline text="$$b_{rew}$$ -- reward (operational gain), threatened by operational punishment"/>
                <outline text="$$b_{est}$$ -- esteem (reputation), threatened by reputational punishment"/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Cost">
                <outline text="$$c_{op}$$ -- operational (data collection, message creation)"/>
                <outline text="$$c_{att}$$ -- Message attack (data modification, deletion or fabrication)"/>
                <outline text="$$c_{comm}$$ -- Message sending (communication cost)"/>
                <outline text="$$c_{pun}$$ -- Punishment: operational and reputational"/>
            </outline>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Cost Benefit Model -- Receiving Organisation #slide " complete="true">
            <outline text="Benefit">
                <outline text="$$b_{sec}$$ -- System security, threatened by direct costs"/>
                <outline text="$$b_{rep}$$ -- Good reputation, threatened by indirect costs"/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Cost">
                <outline text="$$c_{def}$$ -- Defence costs: verifying correctness of data"/>
                <outline text="$$c_{dir}$$ -- Direct costs: operational losses due to ">
                    <outline text="false positives/alarm (wrongly mistrust)"/>
                    <outline text="false negatives (missed alarm -- wrongly trust)"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="$$c_{ind}$$ -- Indirect costs: loss of reputation"/>
            </outline>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="INBOX #wfe-ignore-outline ">
        <outline text="Organisation can run training/tests to assess the types"/>
        <outline text="Employee Properties">
            <outline text="cyber-unwise">
                <outline text="deliberate/knowingly">
                    <outline text="uncommitted"/>
                    <outline text="lazy"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="unknowingly ">
                    <outline text="distracted"/>
                    <outline text="incompetent"/>
                    <outline text="irresponsible"/>
                    <outline text="negligent"/>
                    <outline text="? uncareful"/>
                    <outline text="unskilled"/>
                    <outline text="uncooperative"/>
                    <outline text="unprofessional"/>
                    <outline text="untrained"/>
                    <outline text="unreliable"/>
                </outline>
            </outline>
            <outline text="malicious">
                <outline text="disgruntled"/>
                <outline text="greedy"/>
            </outline>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Employee Properties">
            <outline text="cyber-unwise, cyber-wise"/>
            <outline text="disgruntled, loyal"/>
            <outline text="distracted, focused "/>
            <outline text="greedy, selfless ?"/>
            <outline text="incompetent, competent"/>
            <outline text="irresponsible, responsible"/>
            <outline text="lazy, hard-working"/>
            <outline text="malicious, honest"/>
            <outline text="negligent, thorough"/>
            <outline text="? uncareful, diligent"/>
            <outline text="uncommitted, committed"/>
            <outline text="uncooperative, cooperative"/>
            <outline text="unskilled, skilled"/>
            <outline text="unprofessional, professional"/>
            <outline text="untrained, trained"/>
            <outline text="unreliable, reliable"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="An honest human sensor does not know whether she is reliable or not, or socially engineered (stochastic element)"/>
        <outline text="HONEST">
            <outline text="The honest human sensor will always cooperate, so has no choice of actions per se"/>
            <outline text="But honesty does not always imply correctness "/>
            <outline text="We want to model the fact that they could unknowingly create false reports"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Malicious Human Sensor Game #slide ">
            <outline text="The malicious reporter sends a fake report"/>
            <outline text="She can also decide to deceive the recipient, by sending a correct report"/>
            <outline text="Generally, she will try to optimise the rewards from the attack or deception versus potential punishment such as loss of reputation or prosecution"/>
            <outline text="This can be modelled as an IDS game where the defence action of the report receiver is to not trust the report"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Cyber-Untrained Honest Human Sensor Game #slide "/>
        <outline text="Cyber-Trained Honest Human Sensor Game #slide "/>
        <outline text="INBOX">
            <outline text="Report receiver">
                <outline text="Can use statistics to">
                    <outline text="Estimate reliability of human sensor $$p_{\mathcal{R}}$$"/>
                    <outline text="Compute expected frequency of reportable cyber incidents $$p_{F}$$"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Unknown information ">
                    <outline text="Types -- whether human sensor is malicious $$p_{M}$$ or honest $$p_{H}$$"/>
                </outline>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Human sensor:">
                <outline text="Knows whether malicious or not"/>
                <outline text="Could get feedback to know whether reliable or not (useful for training purposes)"/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Likelihood of attack on reporting channel is not known by anyone "/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
