<outline text="Extended Game Equilibrium Analysis #slide ">
    <outline text="**Theorem 2**. The security game $$\mathcal{G}_r(A, B, \mathcal{D},\mathcal{A})$$ has no pure Nash Equilibrium. A mixed Nash Equilibrium strategy pair $$(x_\mathcal{D}^,y_\mathcal{A}^)$$ is obtained, where $$x_\mathcal{D}^=1 - \frac{r_{\mathcal{A}}+c_{\mathcal{A}}}{G+2r_{\mathcal{A}}}$$ and $$y_\mathcal{A}^=\frac{c_{\mathcal{D}}+r_{\mathcal{D}}}{2r_{\mathcal{D}}+I}$$ are the probability of defense and attack respectively. The resulting expected payoffs, in this case, are $$u_\mathcal{D}^=\frac{r_{\mathcal{D}}^2c_\mathcal{D}(I+r_{\mathcal{D}})}{I+2r_{\mathcal{D}}}$$ and $$u_\mathcal{A}^=\frac{r_{\mathcal{A}}^2+r_\mathcal{A}(G-c_{\mathcal{A}})}{G+2r_{\mathcal{A}}}$$. Furthermore, if $$r_{\mathcal{A}}&gt;0$$ then it holds $$u_\mathcal{A}^&gt;0$$."/>
