                            <outline text="Definition of Lambda-Matrix #slide #novel:definition " colorLabel="4">
<outline text="For a regular matrix pencil $$A-\lambda B$$ with a rank-factorisation $$B=LR^\top$$ we define the $$r\times r$$ matrix $$\Lambda:=R^\top \text{adj}(A)L$$. #definition "/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Well-Defined Lemma #novel:lemma " colorLabel="3">
<outline text="Lemma."/>
<outline text="The $$\Lambda$$-matrices obtained from different rank-factorisations of the same matrix $$B$$ are related to each other through application of suitable similarity transformations. "/>
<outline text="Proof."/>
<outline text="If $$B=L_1 R_1^\top =L_2 R_2^\top$$, then $$\Lambda_1\sim \Lambda_2$$.">
    <outline text="\cite{Piziak1999-iu}"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Lemma."/>
<outline text="Two equivalent regular matrix pencils have all their associated $$\Lambda$$-matrices being similar.  "/>
<outline text="Proof.">
    <outline text="If $$A-\lambda B \sim \tilde{A}-\lambda \tilde{B} $$, then $$\Lambda=\tilde{\Lambda}$$.">
        <outline text="$$\tilde{A}=SAT$$"/>
        <outline text="$$\tilde{B}=SBT=SLR^\top T=\tilde{L}\tilde{R}^\top$$"/>
        <outline text="$$\tilde{\Lambda}:=R^\top T \text{adj}(SAT)SL = R^\top T T^{-1}\text{adj}(A)S^{-1}SL=R^\top \text{adj}(A)L=\Lambda$$"/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="SCREENSHOT">
    <outline text="![Lambda-Mat.png](https://dynalist.io/u/8KZtLlw6t7Ml6N_uyxIQTMvE)"/>
</outline>
