                            <outline text="MP-Matrix Definition #slide #novel:definition add infinite EV">
<outline text="A square matrix $$A$$ admitting a splitting of the form $$A=sC-tB$$ where $$B,C&gt;0$$ is called an $$MP$$-Matrix, if it is an $$MP$$-Matrix of the finite type, or an $$MP$$-Matrix of the infinite type."/>
<outline text="$$A$$ is called an $$MP$$-Matrix of the finite type, if $$s\ge 0$$, $$t&gt;0$$ such that ">
    <outline text="$$B-\lambda C$$ is a regular matrix pencil which has the finite PF property,"/>
    <outline text="$$\frac{s}{t}\ge \rho_0(B-\lambda C)$$."/>
</outline>
<outline text="If $$\frac{s}{t}&gt; \rho(B-\lambda C)$$, then $$A$$ is called a non-singular $$MP$$-Matrix. Otherwise, it is referred to as a singular $$MP$$-Matrix."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Interpretation as Pencils #slide ">
<outline text="Interpret as matrix pencil">
    <outline text="$$(B-sI)-\lambda I=:P(\lambda)$$"/>
</outline>
<outline text="This can be defined for a general regular matrix pencil $$P(\lambda)=B-\lambda C$$ ">
    <outline text="Non-singular $$M$$-Pencil: $$(sC-tB)-\lambda C$$ where $${s}/{t}&gt;\rho(B-\lambda C)$$ ">
        <outline text="and $$B-\lambda C$$ has the strong Perron-Frobenius property."/>
    </outline>
</outline>
