                        <outline text="Matrix-based Space-Efficient Online Secret Sharing: A Contribution">
                            <outline text="Introduction #slide">
<outline text="Background:"/>
<outline text="Context:"/>
<outline text="Motivation:"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Contributions/Novelty #slide "/>
                            <outline text="Notations #slide "/>
                            <outline text="Background #slide ">
<outline text="The probabilistic algorithm for secret matrix share size reduction by \cite{Pfluegel2013-as}:">
    <outline text="Inspired by previous matrix-based work, but avoid Jordan normal form"/>
    <outline text="Propose a probabilistic algorithm, based on using companion form"/>
    <outline text="We achieve similarly short shares as Yang and Zhao, but are more efficient"/>
    <outline text="This yields a probabilistic online secret sharing scheme with small expected share size"/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Linear Algebra Concepts #slide ">
<outline text="Let us review some linear algebra concepts that will be used in the sequel."/>
<outline text="Let $$A \in \mathbbm{F}_p^{t \times t}$$. The matrix $$A$$ is \emph{cyclic} iff it is similar to matrix in {\em companion form}">
    <outline text="$$C =\left(\begin{array}{ccccc}0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 &amp; \ldots &amp; 0 \\0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; \ddots &amp; \vdots \\\vdots &amp; \vdots &amp; \ddots &amp; \ddots &amp; 0 \\0 &amp; 0 &amp; \ldots &amp; 0 &amp; 1 \\c_{0} &amp; c_{1} &amp; \ldots &amp; c_{t-2} &amp; c_{t-1} \\\end{array}\right)$$."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Here, we have that">
    <outline text="$$f (\lambda) = \lambda^{t} - c_{t-1} \lambda^{t-1} - \cdots- c_{1} \lambda - c_{0}$$"/>
</outline>
<outline text="is the characteristic polynomial of $$C$$. "/>
<outline text="For a cyclic matrix, we have that ">
    <outline text="$$f(\lambda) = \det(C- \lambda I) = \det(A- \lambda I) = m(\lambda)$$ "/>
</outline>
<outline text="where $$m(\lambda)$$ is the minimal polynomial of $$A$$."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Cyclic Vectors and a Probability Result #slide ">
<outline text="If $$A$$ is cyclic, we can use standard linear algebra techniques  to compute $$C$$"/>
<outline text="Algorithm Cyclic\_Vector($$A$$)">
    <outline text="[(1)] $$v_0:=$$ random vector"/>
    <outline text="[(2)] {\bf for} $$i=1$$ {\bf to} $$t-1$$: compute $$v_i:=v_{i-1}A$$"/>
    <outline text="[(3)] {\bf if} $$v_0, \ldots, v_{t-1}$$ are linearly independent {\bf then return} \emph{$$v_0$$} {\bf else return} {\em FAIL}"/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Research Question #slide ">
<outline text="Question: given a secret $$s$$, and a randomly chosen prime number $$p$$, we can convert $$s$$ to a matrix. How likely is this to induce a random cyclic matrix?"/>
<outline text="\begin{proposition}[Neumann et al., 1994]"/>
<outline text="If a matrix $$A$$ and a vector $$v$$ are chosen at random, then the probability that $$A$$ is cyclic and $$v$$ is a cyclic vector for $$A$$ is $$(1-p^{-1})(1-p^{-2})\cdots(1-p^{-t}) $$ ."/>
<outline text="\end{proposition}"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Matrix Share Size Reduction Algorithm #slide ">
<outline text="This probabilistic algorithm splits secret $$s$$ into public part $$P$$ and (short) secret part $$Q$$"/>
<outline text="We use repeated matrix conversion, with increasing prime numbers"/>
<outline text="Algorithm MSSR($$s$$)">
    <outline text="[(1)] $$p:=2$$"/>
    <outline text="[(2)] /* Conversion of secret */">
        <outline text="[(a)] $$p:=$$ next\_prime$$(p)$$"/>
        <outline text="[(b)] Compute the base-$$p$$ digits of $$s$$"/>
        <outline text="[(c)] Convert secret $$s$$ into a $$t \times t$$ matrix $$S$$ by using these digits (padding with 0 if necessary)"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="[(3)] /* Size reduction step */">
        <outline text="[(a)] Attempt to compute cyclic vector $$v$$"/>
        <outline text="[(b)] If not successful, go to Step (2)"/>
        <outline text="[(c)] Construct similarity transformation $$T$$ such that $$C := T^{-1}S T$$ is a companion matrix"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="[(4)] Put $$P := T$$ and $$Q := [c_0, c_1, \ldots, c_{t-1}, p]$$"/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="An Online Secret Sharing Scheme #slide ">
<outline text="We use the MSSR algorithm for an online secret sharing scheme with public and secret data"/>
<outline text="{Share creation}:">
    <outline text="Compute $$P$$ and $$Q$$ using MSSR algorithm"/>
    <outline text="Publish $$P$$"/>
    <outline text="Share $$Q$$, using any space efficient secret sharing scheme"/>
</outline>
<outline text="{Reconstruction of secret}:">
    <outline text="Reconstruct the characteristic polynomial $$f$$ and the value of $$p$$ by acquiring at least $$k$$ shares"/>
    <outline text="Build $$C$$ from the $$t$$ coefficients of $$f$$"/>
    <outline text="Compute $$S$$ from $$C$$, by using the public transformation $$T$$ as $$S = T C T ^{-1}$$"/>
    <outline text="Reconstruct $$s$$ from $$S$$ and $$p$$"/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
