                        <outline text="ARCHIVE">
                            <outline text="Introduction #slide #CI6280 ">
<outline text="The Common Vulnerability Scoring System (CVSS) is a specific vulnerability scoring technique."/>
<outline text="Developed by the Forum of Incident Response and Security Teams ([FIRST](https://www.first.org/))."/>
<outline text="Current version: v4.0, published in 2023. Still under active development!"/>
<outline text="CVSS provides an open framework for assessing the severity of software vulnerabilities, which is an industry-recognised standard"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="CVSS Version History #slide ">
<outline text="v1.0 (2005): The initial version focused on exploitability and impact, but lacked peer review and had limitations."/>
<outline text="v2.0 (2007): Introduced environmental and temporal metrics, along with a refined scoring system for better accuracy."/>
<outline text="v3.0 (2015): Major overhaul that incorporated exploitability, impact, and scope sub-scores, enabling more granular assessments."/>
<outline text="v3.1 (2019): Minor updates clarified scoring and addressed edge cases to enhance consistency and usability."/>
<outline text="v4.0 (2023): Significant changes include dynamic scoring based on attack patterns, improved environmental metrics, and a focus on attack surface reduction."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="CVSS Scores #slide #CI6280 ">
<outline text="A CVSS score is a quantity (numerical value), ranging from 0 to 10."/>
<outline text="One use $$\mu:v \rightarrow [0, \ldots, 10]$$, the vulnerability score/metric function. "/>
<outline text="An alternative qualitative representation consists of a vector, providing a compressed textual representation reflecting the values used to derive the score."/>
<outline text="A CVSS Score consists of a base score, which can be refined by additional scores/metrics (temporal, environmental)."/>
<outline text="Generally, the organisation specifies the Base and Temporal metrics, while the environmental metric depends on the end-users."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="CVSS Example: Heartbleed Bug #slide #CI6280 ">
<outline text="![Heartbleed-cvss.png](https://www.dropbox.com/s/o1o5ovl2zkk78te/Heartbleed-cvss.png?dl=1) #eyo-style:Normal "/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Metric Notations #slide #wfe-ignore-outline ">
<outline text="$$\mu:v \rightarrow [0, \ldots, 10]$$ -- vulnerability score/metric function #scoring #notation #cyber-SA-17"/>
<outline text="$$\mu_{B}$$ -- Base Score #cvss #notation  #cyber-SA-17">
    <outline text="$$\mu_{Exp}$$ -- Exploitability Subscore #cvss #notation #cyber-SA-17">
        <outline text="$$\mu_{AV}$$ -- attack vector #cvss #notation #cyber-SA-17"/>
        <outline text="$$\mu_{AC}$$ -- attack complexity #cvss #notation #cyber-SA-17"/>
        <outline text="$$\mu_{PR}$$ -- privileges required #cvss #notation #cyber-SA-17"/>
        <outline text="$$\mu_{UI}$$ -- user interaction #cvss #notation #cyber-SA-17"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="$$\mu_{Imp}$$ -- Impact Subscore #cvss #notation  #cyber-SA-17">
        <outline text="$$\mu_{Imp, C}$$ -- confidentiality impact subscore #cvss #notation #cyber-SA-17"/>
        <outline text="$$\mu_{Imp, I}$$ -- integrity impact subscore #cvss #notation #cyber-SA-17"/>
        <outline text="$$\mu_{Imp, A}$$ -- availability impact subscore #cvss #notation #cyber-SA-17"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="$$\mu_{S}$$ -- Scope #cvss #notation"/>
</outline>
<outline text="$$\mu_{Temp}$$ -- Temporal Score #cvss #notation #wfe-ignore-outline ">
    <outline text="$$\mu_{E}$$ -- Exploit Code Maturity #cvss #notation"/>
    <outline text="$$\mu_{RL}$$ -- Remediation Level #cvss #notation"/>
    <outline text="$$\mu_{RC}$$ -- Report Confidence #cvss #notation"/>
</outline>
<outline text="$$\mu_{Env}$$ -- Environmental Score #cvss #notation #wfe-ignore-outline ">
    <outline text="Modified Base Metrics">
        <outline text="$$\mu_{MAV}$$ -- modified attack vector"/>
        <outline text="$$\mu_{MAC}$$ -- modified attack complexity"/>
        <outline text="$$\mu_{MPR}$$ -- modified privileges required"/>
        <outline text="$$\mu_{MUI}$$ -- modified user interaction"/>
        <outline text="$$\mu_{MS}$$ -- modified scope"/>
        <outline text="$$\mu_{MC}$$ -- modified confidentiality"/>
        <outline text="$$\mu_{MI}$$ -- modified integrity"/>
        <outline text="$$\mu_{MA}$$ -- modified availability"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Security Requirements">
        <outline text="$$\mu_{CR}$$ -- confidentiality requirement"/>
        <outline text="$$\mu_{IR}$$ -- integrity requirement"/>
        <outline text="$$\mu_{AR}$$ -- availability requirement"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="$$\mu_{M.Imp}$$ -- Modified Impact"/>
    <outline text="$$\mu_{M.Exp}$$ -- Modified Exploitability"/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="CVSS v2.0 Base Score Equations #slide #CI7130 ">
<outline text="In CVSS v2.0, the equation defining the Base Score is ">
    <outline text="$$\mu_{Base} = k_1 \cdot \mu_{Imp} + k_2 \cdot \mu_{Exp} - k_3$$"/>
</outline>
<outline text="where $$k_1 = 0.71$$, $$k_2 = 0.47$$ and $$k_3 = 1.76$$ (rounded to two decimal places) assuming $$\mu_{Imp} \neq 0$$. "/>
<outline text="The Impact subscore $$\mu_{Imp}$$ describes potential impact that an exploit has on the system:">
    <outline text="$$\mu_{Imp} = k_4 \cdot \mu_{CIA}$$"/>
</outline>
<outline text="where $$k_4 = 10.41$$ and ">
    <outline text="$$\mu_{CIA} = 1 - (1 - \mu_C)(1 - \mu_I)(1 - \mu_A).$$"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Here $$\mu_C$$, $$\mu_I$$ and $$\mu_A$$ are the impacts on the individual security requirements CIA."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="CVSS v3.0 #wfe-ignore-outline ">
<outline text="Uses three Metric Groups:">
    <outline text="Base --  $$\mu_{B}$$ represents the intrinsic and fundamental characteristics of $$v$$ that are independent of time and specific user environments."/>
    <outline text="Temporal -- metrics which reflect the characteristics of the vulnerability $$v$$ that change over time."/>
    <outline text="Environmental -- representing the characteristics of $$v$$ that are unique to the user's environment."/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="CVSS v3.0 Base Score #slide #CI6280 ">
<outline text="&quot;CVSS Base Score = CVSS Impact + CVSS Exploitability&quot;">
    <outline text="The base score $$\mu_{B}$$ represents the intrinsic and fundamental characteristics of $$v$$ that are independent of time and specific user environments."/>
    <outline text="The Impact subscore $$\mu_{Imp}$$ describes potential impact that an exploit has on the system"/>
    <outline text="The Exploitability subscore $$\mu_{Exp}$$ describes the means and ease of exploiting the vulnerability. "/>
</outline>
<outline text="Each of the two sub-metrics contribute in an additive fashion to the final numerical score, ranging from 0 to 10."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="CVSS v3.0 Base Metric Components #slide #CI6280 #wfe-ignore-outline ">
<outline text="Illustration:">
    <outline text="![https://www.dropbox.com/s/jvhg601n4jklq6b/CVSS-metrics-table.png?dl=1](https://www.dropbox.com/s/jvhg601n4jklq6b/CVSS-metrics-table.png?dl=1) #eyo-style:Normal "/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="CVSS v4.0 Updates #slide">
<outline text="More granular"/>
<outline text="Deeper disclosure:">
    <outline text="Temporal metrics: Clearer communication of expected impact over time."/>
    <outline text="Environmental metrics: Enhanced options for tailoring scores to specific contexts."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Streamlined scoring:">
    <outline text="Calculator: Simplified interface for generating scores."/>
    <outline text="Documentation: Improved clarity and guidance for scoring."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Compared to previous versions:">
    <outline text="CVSS v3: More comprehensive, nuanced, and adaptable scoring."/>
    <outline text="CVSS v2: Easier to understand and use, with improved accuracy."/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Mini-Exercise: Understanding CVSS Scores #slide #CI7130 ">
<outline text="Through this Mini-Exercise, you will better understand CVSS by analysing the scoring values for a given vulnerability."/>
<outline text="(a) Find the CVSS v2 score of the famous Heartbleed vulnerability.">
    <outline text="5"/>
</outline>
<outline text="(b) Find also its string representation.">
    <outline text="(AV:N/AC:L/Au:N/C:P/I:N/A:N). "/>
</outline>
<outline text="(c) Briefly sketch the meaning of two components of your choice in this vector notation and judge the credibility of this score.">
    <outline text="For example:">
        <outline text="AV:N -- The access vector is through the network."/>
        <outline text="C:P -- confidentiality is partially impacted upon. "/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="The Score of 5.0 seems somewhat low for this severe vulnerability."/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Limitations #slide ">
<outline text="The main problem with vulnerability scoring is that two different vulnerabilities can have the same score, although they both have individual characteristics."/>
<outline text="Whilst this is impossible to prevent in general, a careful design of the individual scoring functions should at least take this problem into account."/>
<outline text="In the latest version CVSS 3, the scoring of vulnerabilities has improved -- e.g. some vulnerabilities are now scored higher than before."/>
<outline text="We need a transition from a vulnerability-focused approach to a risk-based scoring system."/>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
