                    <outline text="Cryptographic Protocols and Techniques" _note="https://workflowy.com/#/f53f78c6aa79">
                        <outline text="Secret Sharing #h">
                            <outline text="WORKFLOWY" _note="https://workflowy.com/#/d74995cad406"/>
                            <outline text="Shamir's Secret Sharing Scheme #h ">
<outline text="Motivation #slide ">
    <outline text="Cryptography has given us strong encryption algorithms"/>
    <outline text="Symmetric and asymmetric encryption standards are well-established and give reliable ways of protecting our data"/>
    <outline text="However: relying only on encryption has also shortcomings"/>
    <outline text="Main problem: key management and the underlying trust relationship "/>
</outline>
<outline text="Safeguarding a Cryptographic Key #slide  #CI7160 ">
    <outline text="Consider the task of storing a cryptographic key safely, especially in the context of mobile computing"/>
    <outline text="We are facing a &quot;chicken-and-egg&quot; situation (why?)"/>
    <outline text="We need a different, alternative cryptographic technique. ">
        <outline text="![encryption-on-paper-with-key.jpg](https://www.dropbox.com/s/1sfl8794mjk37cp/encryption-on-paper-with-key.jpg?dl=1) #eyo-style:Normal "/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Secret Sharing -- Idea #slide #CI7160 ">
    <outline text="We want to protect sensitive information (the &quot;secret&quot;). "/>
    <outline text="Idea behind secret sharing: divide secret into several pieces (&quot;shares&quot;) and distribute them to recipients (&quot;shareholders&quot;). "/>
    <outline text="Thus we can protect information by distributing it amongst several parties. "/>
    <outline text="Developed in the late 80's, secret sharing is not a new technique, but it is still an active research area and new applications are emerging. "/>
    <outline text="Let's do a jigsaw puzzle!"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Introduction #slide #arman ">
    <outline text="In secret sharing schemes a secret is distributed among a set of users $$\mathcal{P}$$ in such a way that only some sets, the authorised sets, can recover it. "/>
    <outline text="Secret sharing schemes are useful for not trusting a single party e.g. two members of staff required to open a vault. "/>
    <outline text="Similar challenges can arise in other sensitive areas where a secret should be recovered only if certain users, the authorised sets, get together. "/>
</outline>
<outline text="Secret Sharing -- Concept #slide #CI7160 #CI7160 ">
    <outline text="The following terminology is used: given a __secret __$$s$$, a __dealer __will divide it into __shares __and send them to $$n$$ __shareholders __(or__ players__). "/>
    <outline text="We have a ($$t$$,$$n$$)-threshold scheme, if for $$1\le t\le n$$:">
        <outline text="The secret $$s$$ can be divided into $$n$$ shares. "/>
        <outline text="The individual shares do not reveal $$s$$. "/>
        <outline text="If (at least) $$t$$ shares are combined, they can reconstruct $$s$$. "/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="A $$(n,n)$$-threshold scheme is also referred to as __secret splitting__ (similar to RAID 0)."/>
    <outline text="A $$(1,n)$$-threshold scheme represents $$n$$ backups for redundancy (similar to RAID 1)"/>
</outline>
