<outline text="Secret Sharing -- Classical Schemes #slide  ">
    <outline text="The most well-known schemes are:">
        <outline text="Shamir: based on polynomial interpolation"/>
        <outline text="Blakley: solving linear system"/>
        <outline text="Asmuth-Bloom: modular techniques (Chinese remainder theorem)"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="We will present the Shamir scheme more in detail - it is simple and efficient, and yet secure"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Shamir's Secret Sharing Scheme #slide #CI7160 #modified">
    <outline text="Secret sharing schemes are generally using mathematical objects that allow sharing and reconstructing. "/>
    <outline text="The most well-known scheme is Shamir's scheme, based on polynomial interpolation and modular arithmetic."/>
    <outline text="The underlying idea of this scheme is to convert the secret $$s$$ to a polynomial $$f(x)$$ with a suitable degree and coefficients over the integers modulo a suitable prime number $$p$$. ">
        <outline text="The degree of $$f$$ is $$t-1$$. "/>
        <outline text="The secret $$s$$ will be stored in $$f(0)$$ -- this is the constant term of $$f$$. "/>
        <outline text="All other coefficients of $$f$$ are drawn at random. "/>
        <outline text="So, $$f(x)=s+a_1x+a_2x^2+\cdots+a_{t-1}x^{t-1}$$."/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Share Creation and Reconstruction of Secret #slide #CI7160 ">
    <outline text="Distribution of shares works by __evaluating__ $$f$$ modulo $$p$$:">
        <outline text="We share $$n$$ distinct points $$P_i(x_i, f(x_i))$$ (for $$(i=1,\ldots,n$$) amongst the $$n$$ players. "/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Reconstruction of the secret is based on __interpolation__. ">
        <outline text="A polynomial $$f(x)$$ of degree $$t-1$$ is uniquely determined by $$t$$ different points. "/>
        <outline text="Hence a coalition of $$t$$ players can reconstruct $$f$$, using interpolation. "/>
        <outline text="Any set of $$t$$ distinct points will be valid. "/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="This implements all properties required for a $$(t,n)$$ threshold scheme. "/>
    <outline text="It is sufficient to know the constant term $$a_0$$."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Illustration: Shamir's Scheme #slide #CI7160 ">
    <outline text="![ss-shamir-inefficient-illustration.png](https://www.dropbox.com/s/alottc1kdonfk2q/ss-shamir-inefficient-illustration.png?dl=1) #eyo-style:Normal "/>
</outline>
<outline text="Shamir's Scheme: Choice of Evaluation Points #slide #CI7160">
    <outline text="If we are working with the integers modulo $$p$$, then the $$x_i$$ can simply be the values $$x_1=1$$, $$x_2=2$$, $$x_3=3$$..."/>
    <outline text="The $$x_i$$ could also be computed from some unique information related to the players, e.g. using a secure hash function $$H$$, from an ID value: $$x_i = H(ID_i)$$."/>
    <outline text="This point generating algorithm could be made public. "/>
    <outline text="Hence there would be no need to actually send the $$x_i$$."/>
    <outline text="This would reduce the size of the data that needs distributing by 50\%!"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Illustration: Space-Efficient Shamir #slide #CI7160">
    <outline text="![ss-shamir-illustration.png](https://www.dropbox.com/s/gqykalgmfrmgr15/ss-shamir-illustration.png?dl=1) #eyo-style:Normal "/>
</outline>
<outline text="Shamir's Scheme: Discussion #slide ">
    <outline text="Security">
        <outline text="Shamir's scheme is a __perfect__ secret sharing scheme. "/>
        <outline text="This means that no information about the initial secret is revealed to a coalition of less than the threshold number ($$t$$) of players. "/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Space-Requirements">
        <outline text="When done naively, for each share we require twice the size of the secret $$s$$. "/>
        <outline text="This can be reduced to a share size of $$|__s__|$$ e.g. by using a public evaluation point function. "/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Computational Cost">
        <outline text="Polynomial evaluation can be done in the order of $$t$$ arithmetic operations. "/>
        <outline text="The same holds for interpolation. "/>
    </outline>
</outline>
