<outline text="RECONSTRUCTING THE SECRET #wfe-ignore-item ">
    <outline text="Polynomial Interpolation #slide ">
        <outline text="Goal: given $$(x_1, y_1),\ldots, (x_t, y_t)$$, how to explicitly construct a polynomial $$f$$ of degree $$t-1$$, satisfying $$f(x_i) = y_i$$ for all $$i$$?"/>
        <outline text="We define the __Lagrange interpolation polynomial__ $$L_i(x)$$ of degree $$t-1$$ satisfying">
            <outline text="$$L_i(x_j) = 0$$ if $$i\neq j$$,"/>
            <outline text="$$L_i(x_j) = 1$$ otherwise."/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="We can then build the desired polynomial">
            <outline text="$$f(x) = y_1L_1(x) + \cdots + y_tL_t(x)$$."/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="We can state $$L_i(x)$$ explicity:">
            <outline text="$$L_{i}(x)=\prod_{1\le j \le t, i\neq j}\frac{x-x_i}{x_j-x_i}$$"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Polynomial Interpolation -- Example #slide ">
        <outline text="Example: let us fix $$t=3$$ and choose the points">
            <outline text="$$x_1=2$$, "/>
            <outline text="$$x_2=5$$,"/>
            <outline text="$$x_3=-1$$."/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Then:">
            <outline text="$$L_1(x) = \frac{(x-5)(x+1)}{(2-5)(2+1)} = -\frac{1}{9} (x-5)(x+1) = -\frac{1}{9} (x^2-4x-5)$$"/>
            <outline text="$$L_2(x) = \frac{(x-2)(x+1)}{(5-2)(5+1)} = \frac{1}{18} (x-2)(x+1) = \frac{1}{18}(x^2-x-2)$$"/>
            <outline text="$$L_3(x) = \frac{(x-2)(x-5)}{(-1-2)(-1-5)} = \frac{1}{18}(x-2)(x-5) = \frac{1}{18}(x^2-7x+10)$$"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Polynomial Interpolation -- Example (cont.) #slide ">
        <outline text="We can use this to construct a polynomial $$f$$ satisfying">
            <outline text="$$f(2) = -5$$"/>
            <outline text="$$f(5) = 4$$"/>
            <outline text="$$f(-1) = 4$$"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Solution: $$f(x) = -5 L_1(x)+4 L_2(x)+4L_3(x) = [\cdots] = x^2-4x-1$$"/>
        <outline text="Task: verify this!"/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Matrix Version #h">
    <outline text="Principle #slide">
        <outline text="View the evaluation of Shamir polynomial $$f(x_i)$$ as vector multiplication:">
            <outline text="$$f(x_i) = (1, x_i , x_i^2, ..., x_i^{k-1}) \begin{pmatrix}s \\ a_1 \\ a_2 \\ \vdots \\ a_{k-1} \end{pmatrix}$$. "/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Hence, the following matrix equation determines all shares $$(x_i,y_i)=(x_i,f(x_i))$$ for $$i = 1,\ldots, n$$:">
            <outline text="$$\begin{pmatrix} 1 &amp; x_1 &amp; x_1^2 &amp; \cdots &amp; x_1^{k-1} \\ 1 &amp; x_2 &amp; x_2^2 &amp; \cdots &amp; x_2^{k-1} \\ \vdots &amp; \vdots &amp; \vdots &amp; &amp;\vdots \\ 1 &amp; x_n &amp; x_n^2 &amp; \cdots &amp; x_n^{k-1} \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} s \\ a_1 \\ a_2 \\ \vdots \\ a_{k-1} \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} y_1 \\ y_2 \\ \vdots \\ y_{n} \end{pmatrix}$$. "/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Vandermonde Matrix #slide ">
        <outline text="The special matrix in the previous equation is called a __Vandermonde__ matrix:">
            <outline text="$$V(x_1,...,x_n):= \begin{pmatrix} 1 &amp; x_1 &amp; x_1^2 &amp; \cdots &amp; x_1^{k-1} \\ 1 &amp; x_2 &amp; x_2^2 &amp; \cdots &amp; x_2^{k-1} \\ \vdots &amp; \vdots &amp; \vdots &amp; &amp;\vdots \\ 1 &amp; x_n &amp; x_n^2 &amp; \cdots &amp; x_n^{k-1} \end{pmatrix}$$."/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Reconstruction of Secret #slide ">
        <outline text="This is possible if the associated Vandermonde matrix is square and invertible."/>
        <outline text="Choose a coalition $$\{x_i,\ldots,x_{i_k}\}$$ of $$k$$ distinct points. "/>
        <outline text="Then:">
            <outline text="$$\begin{pmatrix} s \\ a_1 \\ a_2 \\ \vdots \\ a_{k-1} \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 1 &amp; x_1 &amp; x_1^2 &amp; \cdots &amp; x_1^{k-1} \\ 1 &amp; x_2 &amp; x_2^2 &amp; \cdots &amp; x_2^{k-1} \\ \vdots &amp; \vdots &amp; \vdots &amp; &amp;\vdots \\ 1 &amp; x_n &amp; x_n^2 &amp; \cdots &amp; x_n^{k-1} \end{pmatrix}^{-1} \begin{pmatrix} y_1 \\ y_2 \\ \vdots \\ \\ y_{k-1} \end{pmatrix}$$. "/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Shamir -- Compact Notation #slide ">
        <outline text="Given $$s$$ secret"/>
        <outline text="Shamir $$(k,n)$$ threshold secret sharing scheme:">
            <outline text="Define $$f(x)=s+\sum_{i=1}^{k-1}a_i x^i$$ where coefficients $$a_i$$ drawn randomly"/>
            <outline text="Choose distinct points $$(x_i,f(x_i))$$"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Reconstruct secret:">
            <outline text="Interpolate $$f$$"/>
            <outline text="$$s=f(0)$$"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Proof of Correctness and Security #h ">
    <outline text="Statement of Theorem #slide ">
        <outline text="Using the information-theoretical concept of entropy, Shamir's secret sharing scheme's correctness and perfect security property can be stated as follows: let $$C$$ be a coalition set of distinct points. Then one has:">
            <outline text="Shamir's scheme is correct: if $$|C|\ge k$$, then $$H(s|C)=0$$."/>
            <outline text="The scheme is a perfect secret sharing scheme: if $$|C|&lt; k$$, then $$H(s|C)=H(s)$$."/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Information Theory #slide ">
        <outline text="Proofs are based on the concept of __entropy__, a notion developed by Shannon \cite{Shannon1948-eb}, as a tool for information theory "/>
        <outline text="The entropy $$H$$ of a random variable $$X$$ is $$H(X)=\sum  p_i\log_{2}(p_i)$$"/>
        <outline text="We require the following random variables:">
            <outline text="$$S$$: the secret"/>
            <outline text="$$F_i$$: the value of $$f(i)$$ (part of $$i$$th share)"/>
            <outline text="$$Q_i$$: the coefficients of Shamir polynomial "/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Entropy Properties #slide ">
        <outline text="The following properties will be used in the proof:" listStyle="arabic">
            <outline text="$$H(X)\ge H(X|Y)$$ #ref:cond"/>
            <outline text="$$H(X,Y)=H(X)+H(Y| X)= H(Y)+H(X|Y)$$"/>
            <outline text="$$0\le H(X) \le \log_2|X|$$"/>
            <outline text="If $$H(Y|Z)=0$$ then $$H(X|Y)\ge H(X|Z)$$ #ref:this "/>
            <outline text="If $$H(Y|Z)=0$$ then $$H(X|Y,Z)=H(X|Z)$$"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Useful Identities #slide ">
        <outline text="We will also need the following entropy identities "/>
        <outline text="They are specific to the construction of the Shamir secret sharing scheme:">
            <outline text="Due to the unique interpolation property of $$f$$, given $$k$$ distinct points, one has: $$H (Q_{0},\ldots ,Q_{k-1} |F_{i_{1}},\ldots ,F_{i_{k}})=0$$."/>
            <outline text="Based on evaluation of $$f$$ we can uniquely determine the shares, hence: $$H (F_{i_{1}},\ldots ,F_{i_{k}}|Q_{0},\ldots ,Q_{k-1} )=0$$."/>
            <outline text="Due to the definition of the Shamir polynomial, we know $$S$$ if we know $$f$$: $$H (S|Q_{0},\ldots ,Q_{k-1})=H (S|S,Q_1,\ldots ,Q_{k-1})=0$$. #ref:shamir "/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Proof: Correctness #slide ">
        <outline text="Applying identity #ref:this with $$Y=Q_{0},\ldots ,Q_{k-1}$$ to the l.h.s. of #ref:shamir yields $$H (S|Q_{0},\ldots ,Q_{k-1}) \ge H (S |F_{i_{1}},\ldots ,F_{i_{k}})$$."/>
        <outline text="Applying #ref:this to this again gives $$H (S |F_{i_{1}},\ldots ,F_{i_{k}})\ge H (S|Q_{0},\ldots ,Q_{k-1})$$."/>
        <outline text="Hence $$H (S|Q_{0},\ldots ,Q_{k-1}) = H (S |F_{i_{1}},\ldots ,F_{i_{k}})$$."/>
        <outline text="But this is 0, and hence $$H (S |F_{i_{1}},\ldots ,F_{i_{k}})=0$$."/>
        <outline text="And then also $$0\le H (S |F_{i_{1}},\ldots ,F_{i_{t}})\le H (S |F_{i_{1}},\ldots ,F_{i_{k}}) =0$$ for $$t&gt;k$$ due to #ref:cond which finishes the proof. "/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Proof: Perfectness #slide">
        <outline text="$$H (S,F_{i_{1}},\ldots ,F_{i_{k-1}})=H(S,Q_{1},\ldots ,Q_{k-1})$$"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="INBOX">
        <outline text="Lemma  ">
            <outline text="$$H (Q_{0},\ldots ,Q_{k-1} |F_0,F_{i_{1}},\ldots ,F_{i_{k-1}})=H(F_0,F_{i_{1}},\ldots ,F_{i_{k-1}})$$"/>
            <outline text="$$H (Q_{0},\ldots ,Q_{k-1} |F_0,F_{i_{1}},\ldots ,F_{i_{k-1}})=H(Q_{0},\ldots ,Q_{k-1})$$"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Proof">
            <outline text="Let $$y=V(x_1,...,x_n) f $$"/>
            <outline text="$$f=V(x_{i_1},...,x_{i_k})^{-1} y$$"/>
            <outline text="Its coefficient vector $$a$$ is $$a = \begin{pmatrix} s \\ a_1 \\ \vdots \\ a_{k-1} \end{pmatrix} = V(0,x_{i_1},...,x_{i_{k-1}})^{-1} \begin{pmatrix} s \\ y_{i} \\ \vdots \\ y_{i_{k-1}} \end{pmatrix}$$."/>
            <outline text="$$a=V(x_{i_1},...,x_{i_k})^{-1} y$$"/>
            <outline text="$$H(f|x)=H(y)$$"/>
            <outline text="$$H(f|y)=H(x)$$ "/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Proof: Overview #slide ">
            <outline text="Let $$C$$ be a coalition set of points."/>
            <outline text="We need to show:">
                <outline text="Correctness: $$H(s|C)=0$$ if $$|C|\ge k$$"/>
                <outline text="Perfect secret sharing scheme: $$H(s|C)=H(s)$$ if $$|C|&lt; k$$"/>
            </outline>
        </outline>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Proof of Correctness and Security (Version 2) #h ">
    <outline text="Due to the unique interpolation property of $$f$$, given $$k$$ distinct points, one has: $$H (Q_{0},\ldots ,Q_{k-1} |F_{i_{1}},\ldots ,F_{i_{k}})=0$$."/>
    <outline text="If $$H(Y|Z)=0$$ then $$H(X|Y)\ge H(X|Z)$$ #ref:this ">
        <outline text="Applying identity #ref:this with $$Y=Q_{0},\ldots ,Q_{k-1}$$ yields $$H (S|Q_{0},\ldots ,Q_{k-1}) \ge H (S |F_{i_{1}},\ldots ,F_{i_{k}})$$.">
            <outline text="Applying #ref:this again gives $$H (S |F_{i_{1}},\ldots ,F_{i_{k}})\ge H (S|Q_{0},\ldots ,Q_{k-1})$$.">
                <outline text="Hence $$H (S|Q_{0},\ldots ,Q_{k-1}) = H (S |F_{i_{1}},\ldots ,F_{i_{k}})$$.">
                    <outline text="But this is 0, and hence $$H (S |F_{i_{1}},\ldots ,F_{i_{k}})=0$$.">
                        <outline text="$$H(X)\ge H(X|Y)$$ #ref:that"/>
                        <outline text="And then also $$0\le H (S |F_{i_{1}},\ldots ,F_{i_{t}})\le H (S |F_{i_{1}},\ldots ,F_{i_{k}}) =0$$ due to #ref:that which finishes the proof. "/>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
            </outline>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Entropy Properties #slide ">
        <outline text="The following properties will be used in the proof:" listStyle="arabic">
            <outline text="$$H(X,Y)=H(X)+H(Y| X)= H(Y)+H(X|Y)$$"/>
            <outline text="$$0\le H(X) \le \log_2|X|$$"/>
            <outline text="If $$H(Y|Z)=0$$ then $$H(X|Y,Z)=H(X|Z)$$"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Useful Identities #slide ">
        <outline text="We will also need the following entropy identities "/>
        <outline text="They are specific to the construction of the Shamir secret sharing scheme:">
            <outline text="Based on evaluation of $$f$$ we can uniquely determine the shares, hence: $$H (F_{i_{1}},\ldots ,F_{i_{k}}|Q_{0},\ldots ,Q_{k-1} )=0$$."/>
            <outline text="Due to the definition of the Shamir polynomial: $$H (S|Q_{0},\ldots ,Q_{k-1})=H (S|S,Q_1,\ldots ,Q_{k-1})=0$$."/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Proof: Correctness #slide "/>
    <outline text="Proof: Perfectness #slide">
        <outline text="Lemma  ">
            <outline text="$$H (Q_{0},\ldots ,Q_{k-1} |F_0,F_{i_{1}},\ldots ,F_{i_{k-1}})=H(F_0,F_{i_{1}},\ldots ,F_{i_{k-1}})$$"/>
            <outline text="$$H (Q_{0},\ldots ,Q_{k-1} |F_0,F_{i_{1}},\ldots ,F_{i_{k-1}})=H(Q_{0},\ldots ,Q_{k-1})$$"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Proof">
        <outline text="Let $$y=V(x_1,...,x_n) f $$"/>
        <outline text="$$f=V(x_{i_1},...,x_{i_k})^{-1} y$$"/>
        <outline text="Its coefficient vector $$a$$ is $$a = \begin{pmatrix} s \\ a_1 \\ \vdots \\ a_{k-1} \end{pmatrix} = V(0,x_{i_1},...,x_{i_{k-1}})^{-1} \begin{pmatrix} s \\ y_{i} \\ \vdots \\ y_{i_{k-1}} \end{pmatrix}$$."/>
        <outline text="$$a=V(x_{i_1},...,x_{i_k})^{-1} y$$"/>
        <outline text="$$H(f|x)=H(y)$$"/>
        <outline text="$$H(f|y)=H(x)$$ "/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="INBOX">
        <outline text="Proof: Overview #slide ">
            <outline text="Let $$C$$ be a coalition set of points."/>
            <outline text="We need to show:">
                <outline text="Correctness: $$H(s|C)=0$$ if $$|C|\ge k$$"/>
                <outline text="Perfect secret sharing scheme: $$H(s|C)=H(s)$$ if $$|C|&lt; k$$"/>
