<outline text="NI FS #wfe-ignore-outline ">
    <outline text="Non-Interactive Fiat-Shamir Heuristic #h ">
        <outline text="Description #slide">
            <outline text="Peggy wants to prove to Victor that she knows a certain value __secret__ $$x$$. "/>
            <outline text="If Victor doesn't know the value then he will not be able to infer or convey what she has."/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Scheme (Modular Exponentiation) #section">
            <outline text="Parameters #slide">
                <outline text="$$g =$$ generator "/>
                <outline text="$$p =$$ prime integer"/>
                <outline text="$$v =$$ Peggy's random integer/private key"/>
                <outline text="$$x =$$ potentially mutual secret"/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Steps Rev #slide" listStyle="arabic">
                <outline text="Both Peggy and Victor compute their own $$y = g^x \bmod{p}$$, $$y_p,y_v$$."/>
                <outline text="Peggy computes the following pair of values $$(r, c)$$ which is sent to Victor">
                    <outline text="$$t = g^v \bmod{p}$$"/>
                    <outline text="$$c = $$ Hash$$(g,y_p,t)$$"/>
                    <outline text="$$r = v - cx \bmod{p-1}$$"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Victor uses $$(r, c)$$ to reconstruct some values using his own $$y$$ which then checks the correctness of $$c$$.">
                    <outline text="$$\hat t = g^r \times y_v^c \pmod{p}$$"/>
                    <outline text="$$\hat c = $$ Hash$$(g,y_v,\hat t)$$"/>
                    <outline text="$$(\hat c = c) \xrightarrow{}$$ **Verified**"/>
                    <outline text="Important Notes:">
                        <outline text="If $$y_p,y_v$$ are the same (they used the same $$x$$ value) then $$c = \hat c$$."/>
                        <outline text="Recall that $$g^r = g^{v - cx}$$ and that $$y^c = (g^x)^c$$."/>
                        <outline text="Victor effectively computes $$g^{v - cx} \times g^{cx} = g^{v-cx+cx}$$"/>
                        <outline text="Therefore $$g^{v-cx+cx} = g^v = t$$ that only Peggy knows the value of $$v$$."/>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
            </outline>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Scheme (Modular Exponentiation) #section">
            <outline text="Parameters #slide">
                <outline text="$$g =$$ generator "/>
                <outline text="$$p =$$ prime integer"/>
                <outline text="$$v =$$ Peggy's random integer/private key"/>
                <outline text="$$x =$$ potentially mutual secret"/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Steps #slide" listStyle="arabic">
                <outline text="Peggy calculates the following:">
                    <outline text="$$y = g^x \bmod p$$"/>
                    <outline text="$$t = g^v \bmod p$$"/>
                    <outline text="$$c = \text{Hash}(g,y,t) \bmod p$$"/>
                    <outline text="$$r = v - cx$$"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Peggy sends $$(r,c)$$ to Victor."/>
                <outline text="Victor challenges Peggy's proof to verify it:">
                    <outline text="$$y = g^x \bmod p$$"/>
                    <outline text="$$t' = (g^r \bmod p)\cdot(y^c \bmod p) \bmod p$$"/>
                    <outline text="$$c' = \text{Hash}(g,y,t')$$"/>
                    <outline text="$$(c' = c) \xrightarrow{} \text{Verified}$$"/>
                </outline>
            </outline>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Reference #slide">
            <outline text="Authors | Jan Stadler Camenisch and Markus"/>
            <outline text="Title   | Proof Systems for General Statements about Discrete Logarithms"/>
            <outline text="Year    | 1997"/>
            <outline text="DOI     | 10.1.1.56.1208"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Non-Interactive Fiat-Shamir Zero-Knowledge Scheme #h">
        <outline text="Note:">
            <outline text="In the non-interaction version, Bob does not choose $$c$$ but creates his own $$t'$$. I also realised that I shouldn't have used $$v$$ twice as once for the random that Alice has and the other for the verification, which should be written as $$t'$$."/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="In this protocol, Alice wants to prove to Bob, as well as to anyone else, that she is identified by the value $$x$$. "/>
        <outline text="Alice and Bob only share a generator $$g$$ and a prime integer $$p$$. ">
            <outline text="$$g = \text{generator}; x = \text{secret}; p = \text{prime}$$ #wfe-ignore-item "/>
            <outline text="Alice starts by calculating some values:">
                <outline text="$$v = \text{random integer}$$"/>
                <outline text="$$y = g^x \bmod{p}$$"/>
                <outline text="$$t = g^v \bmod{p}$$"/>
                <outline text="$$c = \text{Hash}(g,y,t) \bmod{p}$$"/>
                <outline text="$$r = v - c x$$"/>
            </outline>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Alice sends the values $$t$$ and $$r$$ to Bob which are the same values that any other entity needs to verify Alice's identity. "/>
        <outline text="Verification #slide ">
            <outline text="So Bob does the following calculations to verify that Alice's $$x$$ is the same as Bob's $$x$$ value:">
                <outline text="$$y = g^x \bmod{p}$$"/>
                <outline text="$$c = \text{Hash}(g,y,t) \bmod{p}$$"/>
                <outline text="$$t = (g^r \bmod{p}) \times (y^c \bmod{p}) \bmod{p}$$"/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="As shown above, Bob calculates his own $$c$$ value in order to compute his $$t$$. "/>
            <outline text="With this Bob can compare what he calculated to what Alice has sent, so if it's the same then Alice has proven her identity. "/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Interactive Fiat-Shamir Protocol #h #wfe-ignore-outline ">
    <outline text="Description #slide">
        <outline text="Peggy wants to prove to Victor that she knows a certain secret value $$x$$. "/>
        <outline text="If Victor doesn't know the value then he will not be able to infer or convey what she has."/>
        <outline text="Notations:">
            <outline text="$$x =$$ potentially mutual secret"/>
            <outline text="$$g =$$ a generator"/>
            <outline text="$$p =$$ prime number"/>
            <outline text="$$v =$$ Peggy's random integer"/>
            <outline text="$$c =$$ Victor's random integer"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Protocol Steps #slide" listStyle="arabic">
        <outline text="Peggy starts by calculating $$t = g^v \bmod p$$ and sends this to Victor."/>
        <outline text="Meanwhile Victor does $$y = g^x \bmod p$$ and then returns his $$c$$ to Peggy."/>
        <outline text="Peggy calculates $$r = v-cx \bmod p$$ and sends this &quot;proof&quot; $$r$$ to Victor. "/>
        <outline text="Bob does the following to verify Peggy's proof:">
            <outline text="Compute $$t' = g^r \cdot y^c  \bmod p$$. "/>
            <outline text="If $$t = t'$$, the proof is verified. "/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="References #slide">
        <outline text="Authors | Jan Stadler Camenisch and Markus"/>
        <outline text="Title   | Proof Systems for General Statements about Discrete Logarithms"/>
        <outline text="Year    | 1997"/>
        <outline text="DOI     | 10.1.1.56.1208"/>
    </outline>
</outline>
