                    <outline text="Security Architectures #h ">
                        <outline text="how about this for required outputs from each of the first, second and third stages:"/>
                        <outline text="1) Each bank processes every transaction to produce a signal, and share this with an auditor. ">
                            <outline text="From the data contained in the signal, it shall not be possible for any unauthorised entity to infer the 'to' or 'from' bank account, or sort code. For stage 1, the auditor would be unauthorised."/>
                            <outline text="The amount and timestamp data will not be redacted at stage 1, i.e. the auditor is able to infer and use these elements of data about each transaction that it receives, in stage 2."/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="2) The auditor associates a probability of money-laundering to each transaction, and makes this information available to the banks. ">
                            <outline text="Note that the 'to' and 'from' account+sort codes are by necessity redacted. "/>
                            <outline text="For each transaction, the auditor shall either i) disclose this associated data available only to the source bank, or ii) publish to the community of banks. both routes have their security advantages. Hybrid approaches may also be possible."/>
                            <outline text="Note that the auditor may choose to only disclose/publish the transactions for which the probability exceeds a given value, i.e. those intended for inclusion in an SAR. This disclosure/publication activity then becomes in effect a request to reveal bank account+ sort code. "/>
                            <outline text="It may also be possible for the auditor encrypt other aspects of the transaction, including the timestamp, amount,  and the probability of money-laundering. This way, only the source bank will be privy to these elements of data. This is especially relevant if route (ii) is chosen, but could also be useful for (i), i.e. for internal bank security. "/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="3) The auditor and banks work together to produce an SAR for each set of transactions with a sufficiently high probability of money-laundering. ">
                            <outline text="An SAR is defined as a list of transactions."/>
                            <outline text="For each transaction, unless the 'from' bank has authorised the disclosure, the 'from' bank account+sort code is encrypted. Similarly, for each transaction, unless the 'to' bank has authorised the disclosure, the 'to' bank account+sort code is encrypted. "/>
                            <outline text="An interactive workflow to request authorisation (and hence revelation) of plaintext bank account / sort code is suggested "/>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Security Economics #h ">
                        <outline text="Learning Objectives #slide "/>
                        <outline text="Introduction #slide #fix" _note="\begin{frame}{Learning Objectives }&#xA;\end{frame}&#xA;\begin{frame}{Introduction }&#xA;\begin{itemize}&#xA;\item Security Economics or Economics of Security?&#xA;\begin{figure}[t]\includegraphics[width=.75\textwidth]{SecurityEconomicsTrends.png}\centering \end{figure} &#xA;\item \href{https://trends.google.com/trends/explore?date=today\%205-y&amp;q=economics\%20of\%20security,security\%20economics}{Google Trends}&#xA;\item \href{https://www.cybok.org/media/downloads/Security_Economics_KG_v1.0.0.pdf}{CyBOK: Security Economics Knowledge Guide}&#xA;\end{itemize}&#xA;\end{frame}" complete="true">
                            <outline text="Security Economics or Economics of Security ?">
<outline text=" ![Pasted image](https://dynalist.io/u/FwaxcjYzw6bOr3GNZuGU_2ST) "/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="[Google Trends](https://trends.google.com/trends/explore?date=today%205-y&amp;q=economics%20of%20security,security%20economics&amp;hl=en-US)"/>
                            <outline text="[CyBOK: Security Economics Knowledge Guide](https://www.cybok.org/media/downloads/Security_Economics_KG_v1.0.0.pdf)"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Security Economics Domain #slide" complete="true">
                            <outline text="Aim: how can we design effective and cost-efficient security strategies and policies."/>
                            <outline text="Combines economics theory with research in computer science and mathematics (optimisation).">
<outline text="Examines economic factors that drive the security industry.">
    <outline text="(market for security products and services, and the impact of public policies and regulations on security) #wfe-ignore-item #note "/>
</outline>
<outline text="Seeks to understand the trade-offs between the costs of security measures and their benefits. "/>
<outline text="Involves analysing the incentives and strategic decisions of various stakeholders, including attackers, defenders, and end-users."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="As such, it contributes to the security of computer systems and networks. "/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Economics of Security Topics #slide ">
                            <outline text="Financial analysis of security measures,"/>
                            <outline text="The economics of cybercrime,"/>
                            <outline text="Game theory in security."/>
                            <outline text="The market for zero-day vulnerabilities, "/>
                            <outline text="The role of insurance in cybersecurity. "/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Financial analysis of security measures #h ">
                            <outline text="Return on Investment (ROI) and Cost-Benefit Analysis (CBA) #slide" complete="true">
<outline text="Both are financial analysis methods, used to evaluate the financial impact of a proposed investment or project. "/>
<outline text="Key differences between the two:">
    <outline text="ROI is a simpler and more specific metric."/>
    <outline text="It focuses on the return on the investment."/>
    <outline text="CBA takes a broader view of the costs and benefits of the investment. "/>
    <outline text="It attempts to quantify both __tangible__ and __intangible__ (or &quot;soft&quot;) costs and benefits."/>
    <outline text="Usually over a longer period of time. "/>
</outline>
<outline text="They can also be combined."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="ROI -- Definition #slide " complete="true">
<outline text="ROI is a relative measure that calculates the net gain or loss from an investment or spending."/>
<outline text="This provides a measure of the profitability of the investment."/>
<outline text="The deeper meaning of ROI is the measurement of the efficiency of an investment. "/>
<outline text="It takes into account both the benefits gained and the costs incurred, using a mathematic equation."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="ROI -- Calculation #slide " complete="true">
<outline text="Informal equation: ">
    <outline text="$$\text{ROI} = \frac{\text{benefits from investment} - \text{cost of investment}}{\text{cost of investment}}$$"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Formal definition: ">
    <outline text="Denote $$\rho$$ the ROI, $$b$$ and $$c$$ resp. the benefit and costs."/>
    <outline text="Then $$\rho:=\frac{b-c}{c}=\frac{b}{c}-1$$."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Hence, the ROI is calculated by ">
    <outline text="1) Subtracting the initial investment from the expected total return (benefit) on the investment,"/>
    <outline text="2) Dividing this by the initial investment. "/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Investment Utility Function Definition #slide " complete="true">
<outline text="So, values $$\rho &gt; 0$$ indicate that the returns exceed the costs of the investment."/>
<outline text="Any return $$\mu &lt; \rho$$ is a feasible return."/>
<outline text="Another form sometimes used is the investment utility function">
    <outline text="$$u(\lambda):=b-(\lambda+1)c-{b}$$."/>
</outline>
<outline text="One has">
    <outline text="$$\rho+1=\frac{b}{c} \Longrightarrow u(\rho)=b-(\rho+1)c=0$$."/>
</outline>
<outline text="So we have for the investment utility function:">
    <outline text="$$u(\mu) \ge 0$$ if $$\mu$$ is feasible and"/>
    <outline text="the ROI is the maximal feasible value. "/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Single Loss Expectancy (SLE) #slide " complete="true">
<outline text="The Single Loss Expectancy (SLE) is the monetary value expected for a single loss from a threat or risk."/>
<outline text="The formula for SLE is: $$\text{SLE} = \text{AV} \times \text{EF}$$"/>
<outline text="Here:">
    <outline text="the Asset Value (AV) is the estimated value of the asset at risk"/>
    <outline text="the Exposure Factor (EF) is the percentage of the asset value that would be lost if the risk event occurs."/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Annual Loss Expectancy (ALE) #slide " complete="true">
<outline text="The Annual Loss Expectancy (ALE) calculates the total expected loss from a single loss event, repeated throughout the year."/>
<outline text="It can be defined as the product">
    <outline text="$$\text{ALE}$$ = $$\text{SLE} \times \text{ARO}$$."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Here:">
    <outline text="SLE is the monetary value expected from a single occurrence of a risk (see previous definition),"/>
    <outline text="ARO is the number of times a risk is expected to occur in a year."/>
</outline>
<outline text="The ALE for $$n$$ assets can be defined as the sum of the individual ALEs:">
    <outline text="$$\text{ALE} = \sum_{i=1}^{n} \text{SLE}_i \times \text{ARO}_i$$"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Here $$\text{SLE}_i$$ is the Single Loss Expectancy, and $$\text{ARO}_i$$ is the Annual Rate of Occurrence for the $$i$$-th asset."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Mini-Exercise #slide " complete="true">
<outline text="You are the IT security manager of a small company that processes sensitive customer data. The company has recently experienced a security breach that resulted in the loss of 500 customer records. The company's CEO has asked you to provide a report on the breach's potential financial impact and recommend measures to prevent future incidents."/>
<outline text="Each customer record has a value of $50. The company has experienced two similar security breaches in the past three years. Implementing security measures would cost $10,000 annually."/>
<outline text="Tasks:">
    <outline text="0. What are the costs and what are the benefits in this scenario?"/>
    <outline text="1. Calculate the SLE."/>
    <outline text="2. Estimate the ARO."/>
    <outline text="3. Calculate the ALE."/>
    <outline text="4. Calculate the ROI of implementing security measures."/>
    <outline text="5. Plot the investment utility function."/>
    <outline text="6. Recommend suitable security measures."/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Solution #slide ">
<outline text="The Single Loss Expectancy (SLE) of the security breach can be determined by estimating the cost of the loss that could result from a single incident: SLE = $50 x 500 = $25,000."/>
<outline text="The Annualized Rate of Occurrence (ARO) of a security breach can be estimated by determining how often similar security breaches have occurred in the past: ARO = 2 / 3 = 0.67."/>
<outline text="The Annual Loss Expectancy (ALE) can be calculated by multiplying the SLE by the ARO: ALE = $25,000 x 0.67 = $16,750."/>
<outline text="To calculate the ROI of implementing security measures, divide the potential cost savings (ALE) by the cost of the security measures: ROI = ($16,750 - $10,000) / $10,000 = 0.675 or 67.5%."/>
<outline text="Based on the ROI, it is recommended to implement the security measures as they would result in a positive return on investment. The company can consider measures such as enhancing access controls, implementing intrusion detection and prevention systems, and providing security awareness training to employees."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Research Insight -- MAEVA Framework #h " _note="https://workflowy.com/#/91df9de63f8f" complete="true"/>
                            <outline text="Research Extensions: Multi-Returns of Multi-Security Investments #h #novel ">
<outline text="Motivation: Securing Logical Assets #slide " complete="true">
    <outline text="We would like to apply the previous ideas to more complex assets."/>
    <outline text="A logical asset is a system, composed of several sub-systems. "/>
    <outline text="We examine a system $$a$$ with $$m&gt;1$$ components $$a_1, \ldots, a_m$$."/>
    <outline text="Also, we might want to implement several security investments (controls/security policies)."/>
    <outline text="Denote $$n&gt;1$$ the number of these different types of security investments $$I_1, \ldots, I_m$$."/>
    <outline text="In the model, $$b_i$$ will be defined as the asset value of $$a_i$$ and $$c_i$$ as the costs for applying $$I_j$$ for $$i=1,\ldots,m$$ and $$j=1,\ldots,n$$."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Examples -- Illustration #slide " complete="true">
    <outline text="![Pasted image](https://dynalist.io/u/JRG-aJKxGNwECAUg7ItaUOtu) #eyo-style:Normal "/>
</outline>
<outline text="Security Investments for System 1 #slide " complete="true">
    <outline text="Example for System 1: asset $$a$$ is a network with $$a_1$$ a firewall and $$a_2$$ an end-device (PC)"/>
    <outline text="Assumption: there are no internal threats in the system."/>
    <outline text="Security inter-dependencies:">
        <outline text="If $$a_1$$ is secure, the overall system $$a$$ is secure (whether $$a_2$$ is secure or not, as it will not be compromised internally and is protected externally through $$a_1$$)."/>
        <outline text="If $$a_1$$ is not secure,  then $$a$$ is secure, as long as $$a_2$$ is secure."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="We want to study the overall security achieved by the following security investments:">
        <outline text="$$I_1$$: Harden the firewall"/>
        <outline text="$$I_2$$: Patch the PC"/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Security Investments for System 2 #slide " complete="true">
    <outline text="Example for System 2: a network consisting of two connected PCs $$a_1$$ and $$a_2$$."/>
    <outline text="They have different vulnerabilities and different asset values."/>
    <outline text="Security inter-dependencies:">
        <outline text="The system is secure, if both $$a_1$$ and $$a_2$$ are secure."/>
        <outline text="But both assets are independent in terms of their security."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Study the security achieved by the following investments:">
        <outline text="$$I_1$$: Patch the PC $$a_1$$"/>
        <outline text="$$I_2$$: Patch the PC $$a_2$$"/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Multi-Asset Returns of (Single) Investment (M-ROI) #slide  #econ #security #VNM ">
    <outline text="Let us consider an extension of the ROI concept to $$m$$ multiple assets, secured by the same investment."/>
    <outline text="Example for $$m=2$$: ">
        <outline text="Utility function for investment securing two assets:">
            <outline text="$$u(\lambda)= \begin{pmatrix} b_1 \\ b_2 \\  \end{pmatrix}-(\lambda+1)\begin{pmatrix} c_1 \\ c_2 \\ \end{pmatrix}\ge 0$$."/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="This vector function does in general not have a value $$\rho$$ satisfying $$u(\rho)=\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\  \end{pmatrix}$$, so it is difficult to define ROI that way."/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="M-ROI Approach #slide ">
    <outline text="Motivation: we could add the ROIs of the individual asset investments, but only if they are independent (see ALE for multiple assets)"/>
    <outline text="Weighted asset selection vector $$x^\top = (x_1,x_2)$$ allows for distribution of allocated intensity:">
        <outline text="Denote $$\rho:=ROI(a_1,a_2)$$."/>
        <outline text="Assume $$x^\top u(\rho)\ge 0$$ and solve for $$\rho$$."/>
        <outline text="We require">
            <outline text="$$x^\top u(\rho)=x^\top\begin{pmatrix} b_1-c_1-\rho c_1 \\ b_2-c_2-\rho c_2 \end{pmatrix}\ge 0$$."/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="This yields ">
            <outline text="$$ROI(a_1,a_2)=\rho \le \frac{x_1(b_1-c_1)+x_2(b_2-c_2)}{x_1c_1+x_2c_2}= \frac{x_1(b_1-c_1)}{x_1c_1+x_2c_2}+\frac{x_2(b_2-c_2)}{x_1c_1+x_2c_2}$$"/>
            <outline text="$$\le \frac{b_1-c_1}{c_1}+\frac{b_2-c_2}{c_2}=ROI(a_1)+ROI(a_2)$$."/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Hence we could define ">
        <outline text="$$\rho:=\max \lambda$$  s.th. $$\exist x_1,x_2:x^\top u(\lambda)\ge 0$$."/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Return of Multi-Investments (ROI-M) #slide ">
    <outline text="This is an extension to $$n$$ multiple security investments made for the single asset."/>
    <outline text="Example for $$n=2$$: ">
        <outline text="Utility function for two investments, acting as overlapping controls">
            <outline text="$$u(\lambda)= \begin{pmatrix} b_1 &amp; b_2 \\  \end{pmatrix}-(\lambda+1)\begin{pmatrix} c_1 &amp; c_2 \\ \end{pmatrix}$$."/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="ROI-M Approach #slide ">
    <outline text="There is a different parameters to optimise now:">
        <outline text="Weighted security control (&quot;layered defense'') selection vector $$y = \begin{pmatrix} y_1 \\ y_2 \\  \end{pmatrix}$$."/>
        <outline text="Minimise $$\lambda$$ over $$u(\lambda)y$$, the assignment of invested capital."/>
        <outline text="Why? Consider the attacker's mind!"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Economics context:">
        <outline text="Investment returns are produced goods."/>
        <outline text="The production creates costs."/>
        <outline text="These should be minimised."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Interpretation for security domain:">
        <outline text="Security investments can be done in several ways."/>
        <outline text="The attacker wants them to be as ineffective as possible, potentially for a single (or small number of) assets."/>
        <outline text="This creates maximal damage for the defending organisation."/>
        <outline text="Hence the minimiser function can predict incoming attacks (principle of easiest attack)."/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Multi-Asset Returns of Multi-Investments (M-ROI-M) #slide ">
    <outline text="Combine both extensions to model $$n$$ multiple investments made for each of the $$m$$ assets."/>
    <outline text="There are two parameters to optimise now:">
        <outline text="Maximise $$\lambda$$ over selection of covered assets"/>
        <outline text="Minimise $$\lambda$$ over assignment of security controls"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="One can show that these values are so-called equilibrium value of the Von Neumann economical growth model."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Generic M-ROI-M Model ($$m=2, n=2$$) #slide " complete="true">
    <outline text="Asset selection vector $$x^\top = (x_1,x_2)$$."/>
    <outline text="Layered-defense vector (&quot;security policy'') $$y = \begin{pmatrix} y_1 \\ y_2 \\ \end{pmatrix}$$."/>
    <outline text="Matrix ROI for asset consisting of two inter-dependent assets: ">
        <outline text="$$U(\lambda)= \lambda\begin{pmatrix} c_{11} &amp; c_{12}\\ c_{21} &amp; c_{22} \\ \end{pmatrix}-\begin{pmatrix} b_{11}-c_{11} &amp; b_{12}-c_{12}\\ b_{21}-c_{21} &amp; b_{22}-c_{22} \\ \end{pmatrix} =: \lambda C -B$$."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Definition of upper and lower ROI:">
        <outline text="$$\rho^+:=\max \lambda$$  s.th. $$\exist x:\,x^\top U(\lambda)\ge 0$$."/>
        <outline text="$$\rho^-:=\min \lambda$$  s.th. $$\exist y:\,U(\lambda)y\ge 0$$."/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Example 1 Revisited #slide " complete="true">
    <outline text="Security Investments:">
        <outline text="If we use $$I_1$$ (harden firewall) then: ">
            <outline text="$$b=b_1 + b_2$$,"/>
            <outline text="$$c=c_1$$."/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="If we use $$I_2$$ (patch PC) then: ">
            <outline text="$$b=b_2$$,"/>
            <outline text="$$c=c_2$$."/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="This is M-ROI-M Model with $$m=2, n=2$$, and">
        <outline text="$$U(\lambda)= \lambda\begin{pmatrix} c_{1} &amp; c_{1}\\ c_{2} &amp; c_{2} \\ \end{pmatrix}-\begin{pmatrix} b_{11}-c_{1} &amp; b_{12}-c_{1}\\ b_{21}-c_{2} &amp; b_{2}-c_{2} \\ \end{pmatrix}$$."/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Example 2 Revisited #slide " complete="true">
    <outline text="If we patch the PC $$a_1$$ then:">
        <outline text="$$b=b_1$$,"/>
        <outline text="$$c=c_1$$."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="If we patch the PC $$a_2$$ then">
        <outline text="$$b=b_2$$,"/>
        <outline text="$$c=c_2$$."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="If we patch both PCs $$a_1, a_2$$ then">
        <outline text="$$b=b_1+b_2$$,"/>
        <outline text="$$c=c_1+c_2$$."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="This is M-ROI-M Model with $$m=2, n=2$$, and two independent assets:">
        <outline text="$$U(\lambda)= \lambda\begin{pmatrix} c_1 &amp; 0\\ 0 &amp; c_2 \\ \end{pmatrix}-  \begin{pmatrix} b_1-c_1 &amp; 0\\ 0 &amp; b_2-c_2 \\  \end{pmatrix}=(\lambda+1)\begin{pmatrix} c_1 &amp; 0\\ 0 &amp; c_2 \\ \end{pmatrix}-  \begin{pmatrix} b_1 &amp; 0\\ 0 &amp; b_2\\  \end{pmatrix}$$."/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="INBOX #wfe-ignore-outline ">
    <outline text="[Discussion #slide ]">
        <outline text="Compare $$\rho=\frac{b-c}{c}=\frac{b}{c}-1\Longleftrightarrow b-(1+\rho)c=0$$ with $$\det(C^{-1}B-\rho I)=0 \Longleftrightarrow \det(B-(1+\rho)C)=0$$"/>
        <outline text="This is the scalar version of the VNM"/>
        <outline text="Applicable if the matrix $$C^{-1}B$$ has the Frobenius-Perron property."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="[Example: $$m=1, n=2$$ #slide ]">
        <outline text="ROI for two assets: $$u(\lambda)= \lambda\begin{pmatrix} c_1 \\ c_2 \\ \end{pmatrix}-  \begin{pmatrix} b_1-c_1 \\ b_2-c_2 \\  \end{pmatrix}$$."/>
        <outline text="Investment vector $$y = \begin{pmatrix} y_1 \\ y_2 \\ \end{pmatrix}$$."/>
        <outline text="Solve for $$\lambda$$ in $$y^\top u(\lambda)&gt;0$$ yields $$\lambda &gt; \frac{y_1(b_1-c_1)+y_2(b_2-c_2)}{y_1c_1+y_2c_2}$$ $$\forall y_1,y_2$$."/>
        <outline text="Hence we could define $$\rho:=$$."/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="ARCHIVE #wfe-ignore-outline ">
    <outline text="So here $$m=2, n=2$$. Logical system asset $$a$$ has two independent assets "/>
    <outline text="System $$a$$ is secure if both $$a_1$$ and $$a_2$$ are."/>
    <outline text="Example: two networked PCs ($$a_1$$ and $$a_2$$) with software vulnerabilities $$v_1$$ and $$v_2$$ and asset values $$d_1$$ and $$d_2$$."/>
    <outline text="Overall asset value: $$d=d_1+d_2$$."/>
</outline>
<outline text="KNOWLEDGE #hh #wfe-ignore-item " _note="https://dynalist.io/d/gcskC8EanDTKsGE-U8yP7HPC#z=ohsaWy3Sa71R3O3OB6Ez8Dwn"/>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="INBOX #wfe-ignore-outline ">
                            <outline text="Utility functions">
<outline text="Utility functions play a crucial role in decision-making and economics."/>
<outline text="They represent the preferences and satisfaction levels of individuals."/>
<outline text="Used in decision theory, utility functions help make choices by maximizing expected satisfaction."/>
<outline text="Definition: A utility function assigns a numerical value to the perceived satisfaction or well-being derived from different choices or outcomes."/>
<outline text="Key Components:"/>
<outline text="Preferences:">
    <outline text="Utility functions capture individual preferences and desires."/>
    <outline text="Preferences may vary among individuals, leading to diverse utility functions."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Decision-Making:"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Slide Title: Leveraging Utility Design in Cybersecurity">
<outline text="1. Adaptive Risk Management:">
    <outline text="Utility design allows for adaptive risk management by assigning numerical values to potential threats."/>
    <outline text="Helps prioritize cybersecurity efforts based on the potential impact and likelihood of different risks."/>
</outline>
<outline text="2. Resource Allocation Optimization:">
    <outline text="Utility functions aid in optimizing resource allocation by quantifying the utility of different security measures."/>
    <outline text="Enables organizations to invest resources where they provide the highest cybersecurity utility."/>
</outline>
<outline text="3. User Behavior Analysis:">
    <outline text="Utility design assists in analyzing user behavior by quantifying the utility users derive from certain actions."/>
    <outline text="Enhances the ability to detect anomalies and potential security breaches through deviations in user behavior."/>
</outline>
<outline text="4. Decision Support for Incident Response:">
    <outline text="Utility functions facilitate decision-making during incident response by quantifying the potential impact of different response strategies."/>
    <outline text="Supports rapid and effective decision-making in the face of cybersecurity incidents."/>
</outline>
<outline text="5. Cost-Benefit Analysis:">
    <outline text="Utility design allows for cost-benefit analysis in cybersecurity investments."/>
    <outline text="Helps organizations evaluate the trade-offs between the cost of security measures and the utility gained from mitigating potential risks."/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="The Economics of Cybercrime #h #eyo-style:Section ">
                            <outline text="Introduction #slide "/>
                            <outline text="The Model #slide ">
<outline text="Source: \cite{Anderson2013-nq}"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Defender Cost #slide ">
<outline text="When an asset is attacked, there is damage/harm/loss, resulting in a cost"/>
<outline text="It might cost time and money to defend/repair an asset"/>
<outline text="There could also be other hidden costs"/>
<outline text="We will present a cost model, inspired by Anderson's taxonomy \cite{Anderson2013-nq} on the cost of cybercrime "/>
<outline text="Approach: scaling up the notion of a &quot;system&quot;: ">
    <outline text="Society becomes organisation"/>
    <outline text="People asset turns into a generic asset of organisation"/>
    <outline text="Use of computers in society is mapped into business operations"/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Defender Cost Framework #slide ">
<outline text="We would like to quantify both tangible and intangible costs"/>
<outline text="Can distinguish between __direct __and__ indirect loss__ as well as __defence cost__">
    <outline text="Direct losses:">
        <outline text="Replacing or repairing an asset"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Indirect  losses:">
        <outline text="Loss of business"/>
        <outline text="Loss of reputation"/>
        <outline text="Fines"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Defence cost: develop, deploy and maintain defence mechanisms"/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Defender Benefit #slide ">
<outline text="We usually get some &quot;operational benefit&quot; from a digital asset">
    <outline text="This could be revenues (in a business organisation)"/>
    <outline text="Individuals get benefits for their leisure activities, e.g. improved communications and information sharing"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Question: how can we quantify this?"/>
<outline text="It might be reasonable to assume that this is proportional to the asset value"/>
<outline text="Could then be used for the cost-benefit analysis"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Example -- Phishing #slide ">
<outline text="Direct losses">
    <outline text="criminal revenue"/>
    <outline text="time and effort to reset account credentials"/>
    <outline text="secondary costs of overdrawn accounts (deferred purchases) lost attention and bandwidth caused by spam messages"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Indirect losses">
    <outline text="loss of trust in online banking"/>
    <outline text="lost opportunity for banks to communicate via email efforts to clean-up PCs infected with malware"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Defense costs">
    <outline text="security products (spam filters, antivirus)"/>
    <outline text="services for consumers (training) &amp; industry (take-down) fraud detection, tracking, and recuperation efforts"/>
    <outline text="law enforcement"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Criminal revenue">
    <outline text="sum of the money withdrawn from victim accounts"/>
    <outline text="revenue to spammer for sending phishing mails"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Attacker #slide #wfe-ignore-outline ">
    <outline text="A cybercrime is committed if $$b_M + b_P - c_A - c_M p_ap_c&gt;0$$ where:">
        <outline text="$$b_M$$: The monetary benefits of committing the crime"/>
        <outline text="$$b_P$$: The psychological benefits of committing the crime"/>
        <outline text="$$c_A$$: Costs of attacking the system"/>
        <outline text="$$c_M$$: Monetary (or other) punishment costs "/>
        <outline text="$$p_a$$: The probability of arrest"/>
        <outline text="$$p_c$$: The probability of conviction"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="The product term $$c_M p_ap_c$$ is also called the expected penalty effect."/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Assets #slide #wfe-ignore-outline ">
<outline text="Reputation, esteem"/>
<outline text="Effort"/>
<outline text="Income"/>
<outline text="Revenues"/>
<outline text="Profit"/>
<outline text="Tangible/intangible"/>
<outline text="Value"/>
<outline text=""/>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
