                    <outline text="Security Management #h ">
                        <outline text="MATURE FRAMEWORKS">
                            <outline text="OCTAVE (Operationally Critical Threat, Asset and Vulnerability Evaluation)" colorLabel="4">
<outline text="Overview">
    <outline text="OCTAVE -- a well-documented, open security risk assessment methodology."/>
    <outline text="Set of tools, techniques and methods for risk-based information security strategic assessment and planning"/>
    <outline text="Developed by Christopher Alberts at Carnegie Mellon University (CMU)"/>
    <outline text="Published by Software Engineering Institute (SEI) at CMU in 1999"/>
    <outline text="More information is available at the [CERT website](http://www.cert.org/octave/)"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Characteristics">
    <outline text="Philosophy/Vision">
        <outline text="Focuses on strategy"/>
        <outline text="Take into account the organisations needs"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Risk Assessment:">
        <outline text="Top-down approach"/>
        <outline text="Threat-per-asset based"/>
        <outline text="Qualitative approach"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Implementation:">
        <outline text="Flexible: Can be customized"/>
        <outline text="Self-directed: led by organisations employee"/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Variants">
    <outline text="OCTAVE -- suitable for large organisations ( 300 employees)">
        <outline text="Phase 1: Build asset-based threat profiles ">
            <outline text="Process 1: Determine critical assets and how they are currently protected "/>
            <outline text="Process 2: Identify security requirements for each critical asset. "/>
            <outline text="Process 3: Identify organisational vulnerabilities within existing practices "/>
            <outline text="Process 4: Create a Threat Profile for each critical asset ">
                <outline text="Asset (what is at risk)">
                    <outline text="The (critical) asset that is potentially affected by the threat "/>
                    <outline text="Remember the asset categories: ">
                        <outline text="Data "/>
                        <outline text="Software "/>
                        <outline text="Hardware "/>
                        <outline text="People "/>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Actor (origin of the threat)">
                    <outline text="OCTAVE distinguishes between the actors &quot;nature&quot; and &quot;human&quot; "/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Motive (reason for the attack) ">
                    <outline text="Attackers might be classified according to his/her motive: ">
                        <outline text="Amateurs "/>
                        <outline text="Script Kiddies"/>
                        <outline text="Geeks"/>
                        <outline text="White Hat (Ethical) Hackers "/>
                        <outline text="Grey Hat Hackers "/>
                        <outline text="Black Hat Hackers (Computer Criminals) "/>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Access (how the asset is reached)">
                    <outline text="An attack vector is a path or means by which the attacker can gain access to an asset "/>
                    <outline text="Attack vectors enable the exploitation of system vulnerabilities, including the human element. "/>
                    <outline text="Examples: ">
                        <outline text="A web interface with an XSS vulnerability  "/>
                        <outline text="An employee with a weak password "/>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Outcome (damage likely to be caused)">
                    <outline text="Outcome is one of the following: disclosure, modification, loss/destruction, interruption, or other "/>
                    <outline text="It is measured by the impact on the organisation -- the overall cost of losing an asset "/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Mini-Exercises: Threat Profile ">
                    <outline text="For this exercise, you will review the latest developments concerning the ENISA (EU/Brexit InfoSec) vulnerability and create a threat profile of the most critical asset, relevant in this scenario."/>
                    <outline text="Reminder: a threat profile consists of the following attributes:">
                        <outline text="Asset (e.g. customer data, pc,)"/>
                        <outline text="Access (e.g. private/public network, web page)"/>
                        <outline text="Actor (Source of threat)"/>
                        <outline text="Internal (e.g. staff), External (e.g. hacker)"/>
                        <outline text="Motive (accidental, deliberate)"/>
                        <outline text="Outcome (Impact of asset e.g. data loss)"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Solutions">
