<outline text="Data in transit between a EU country and the UK.">
    <outline text="criminal records"/>
    <outline text="traveller information"/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Access:">
<outline text="COMPLICATED!"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Actor:">
<outline text="Another member country of the EU"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Motive (accidental, deliberate):">
<outline text="accidential"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Outcome (disclosure, modification, loss/destruction, interruption, or other):">
<outline text="disclosure"/>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Threat 2: interception of confidential data/info by attacker external to the EU-internal"/>
                        <outline text="Threat 3"/>
                        <outline text=":"/>
                        <outline text=":"/>
                        <outline text=":"/>
                        <outline text=":"/>
                        <outline text=":"/>
                        <outline text="Threat 1407"/>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
            </outline>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Phase 2: Identify infrastructure vulnerabilities ">
            <outline text="Process 5: Identify network access paths and IT components related to critical assets "/>
            <outline text="Process 6: Evaluate identified IT components "/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Phase 3: Develop security strategy and mitigation plans ">
            <outline text="Process 7: Conduct risk analysis ">
                <outline text="Goal: to identify and evaluate the impact of threats to critical assets "/>
                <outline text="OCTAVE forms a risk profile by expanding the threat profile by two additional attributes:">
                    <outline text="Impact description -- &quot;The disclosure of the sensitive documents mean that our competitors know our trade secrets and might be able to come out with a competitive new product.&quot;"/>
                    <outline text="Impact value -- usually chosen from {low, medium, high}, looking at impact areas such as:">
                        <outline text="Reputation/customer confidence"/>
                        <outline text="Life/health of customer"/>
                        <outline text="Fines/Legal penalties"/>
                        <outline text="Financial"/>
                        <outline text="etc"/>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Mini-Exercises: Risk Profile ">
                    <outline text="Consider the threat profile from the previous exercise and complete it to a risk profile. ">
                        <outline text="Impact description:">
                            <outline text="Act of terrorism, committed in the EU with one nationality, and travelling back to UK with another nationality-passport and hence he/she is not arrested at the border."/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Impact value:">
                            <outline text="Potentially high."/>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Criticism: this approach is quite rudimentary and does not fully implement a risk analysis as we have introduced earlier. "/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Process 8: Develop protection strategy and mitigation plan ">
                <outline text="Information generated by Phases 1 and 2 are analysed to:">
                    <outline text="Identify risks to critical assets - prioritise"/>
                    <outline text="Develop protection strategies"/>
                    <outline text="Develop mitigation plans"/>
                    <outline text="Propose next steps"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Will need Senior Management approval"/>
            </outline>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="OCTAVE-S -- organisations  300 employees">
        <outline text="Developed in 2003 in response to needs of smaller organisations"/>
        <outline text="Meets same OCTAVE criteria but is adapted to more limited means and unique constraints of small organizations">
            <outline text="Small organisation with a simple hierarchical structure"/>
            <outline text="Small interdisciplinary analysis team (3-5 employees)"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Uses more streamlined processes and different worksheets, but produces the same type of results"/>
        <outline text="Includes a limited exploration of the computing infrastructure during Phase 2"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="OCTAVE Allegro -- focuses on information assets">
        <outline text="What is OCTAVE Allegro?">
            <outline text="Developed in 2007 due to the increased need to protect data"/>
            <outline text="Derived from earlier OCTAVE and OCTAVE-S methodologies."/>
            <outline text="Unlike previous OCTAVE approaches, it focuses on information assets:">
                <outline text="Where they are stored, transported, and processed"/>
                <outline text="How they are used"/>
                <outline text="How they are exposed to threats, vulnerabilities, and disruptions as a result"/>
            </outline>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Consists of eight steps organized into four phases:">
            <outline text="Develop risk measurement criteria consistent with the organization's mission, goal objectives, and critical success factors."/>
            <outline text="Create a profile of each critical information asset that establishes clear boundaries for the asset, identifies its security requirements, and identifies all of its __containers__."/>
            <outline text="Identify threats to each information asset in the context of its containers."/>
            <outline text="Identify and analyse risks to information assets and begin to develop mitigation approaches."/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Strengths">
    <outline text="Well-documented through published academic papers and freely available resources"/>
    <outline text="Flexible as organisations may choose to implement portions that they find appropriate"/>
    <outline text="Comprehensive and thorough"/>
    <outline text="Strategic as it focuses on important and relevant risks"/>
    <outline text="Cheap as it is self-led"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Shortcomings">
    <outline text="Needs extensive preparation and is complex when done correctly"/>
    <outline text="Qualitative methodology means that OCTAVE does not allow for the mathematical modelling of risks"/>
    <outline text="Risk Analysis is simplistic as done on a single asset and does not use any mathematical model"/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="STRIDE and DREAD -- a (web) application security risk analysis framework, developed for Microsoft's threat modelling framework" colorLabel="3">
<outline text="STRIDE and DREAD are threat classification models originally designed for web application security.">
    <outline text="Developed by Microsoft in 2005"/>
    <outline text="Now also recommended by OWASP"/>
    <outline text="Is top-down: focuses on threats (threat/risk modelling)"/>
    <outline text="A simple approach"/>
    <outline text="An iterative process"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Illustration">
    <outline text="![](https://i-msdn.sec.s-msft.com/dynimg/IC101260.gif)"/>
    <outline text="STRIDE is part of the bigger picture of threat modelling."/>
</outline>
<outline text="The STRIDE mnemonic conveniently covers most relevant threats to CIA.">
    <outline text="![](https://www.dropbox.com/s/5gnjyxyp95j87po/STRIDE.jpg?dl=1)"/>
</outline>
<outline text="DREAD is a mnemonic that can be used for impact-assessing activity.">
    <outline text="**D**amage -- how bad would an attack be?"/>
    <outline text="**R**eproducibility -- how easy is it to reproduce the attack?"/>
    <outline text="**E**xploitability -- how much work is it to launch the attack?"/>
    <outline text="**A**ffected users -- how many people will be impacted?"/>
    <outline text="**D**iscoverability -- how easy is it to discover the threat?"/>
</outline>
<outline text="STRIDE proceeds in 4 steps.">
    <outline text="Step 1. Create a list including all known threats, mapped against their impact."/>
    <outline text="Step 2. Rank threats by criticality (impact) and likelihood.">
        <outline text="For each threat, assign two numbers $$c$$ and $$l$$:">
            <outline text="$$c$$ -- criticality (10 is most severe)"/>
            <outline text="$$l$$ -- likelihood (10 is least likely to occur)"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Calculate overall risk as $$R = c/l$$."/>
        <outline text="DREAD (and its successor alternatives) can be used to decide on criticality value $$c$$.">
            <outline text="When a given threat is assessed using DREAD, each category is given a rating. ">
                <outline text="Rating scales running from 0 to 10 are common -- for example, 10 for high, 5 for medium, 1 for low and 0 for none. "/>
                <outline text="The sum of all ratings for a given exploit can be used to prioritize among different exploits."/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="It was previously used at Microsoft and currently used by OpenStack and many other corporations but it was discovered that the ratings are not very consistent and subject to debate. "/>
            <outline text="It was out of use at Microsoft by 2008."/>
            <outline text="Discoverability Debate -- some security experts feel that including the &quot;Discoverability&quot; element as the last &quot;D&quot; rewards Security through Obscurity."/>
            <outline text="Some organizations have either moved to a DREAD-D &quot;DREAD minus D&quot; scale (which omits Discoverability) or always assume that Discoverability is at its maximum rating."/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Step 3. Select a mitigation technique or technology for each threat"/>
    <outline text="Step 4. Start again (Step 1) as the project evolves"/>
</outline>
<outline text="The main advantage of STRIDE is its simplicity and effectiveness.">
    <outline text="STRIDE was originally designed for building secure web applications, whereas OCTAVE targets (information) security of an organisation."/>
    <outline text="Both frameworks are top-down, but the OCTAVE has a more formal approach for identifying critical assets and their vulnerabilities."/>
    <outline text="In OCTAVE, threat profiling is very generic, whereas the STRIDE acronym helps to identify relevant threat categories."/>
    <outline text="OCTAVE also lacks specific guidelines for risk analysis, STRIDE has developed the DREAD categorisation for threat outcomes."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Mini-Exercise">
    <outline text="Choose a threat in a application-related area. "/>
    <outline text="Compare and contrast its OCTAVE threat and risk profiles and its STRIDE/DREAD classification."/>
    <outline text="Threat: Premature roll-out (deployment) of software with a security vulnerability.">
        <outline text="OCTAVE:">
            <outline text="Build threat profile....">
                <outline text="Actor"/>
                <outline text="Motive">
                    <outline text="Negligence, Greed, Revenge"/>
                </outline>
            </outline>
        </outline>
        <outline text="STRIDE">
            <outline text="This threat is escaping the technology-focussed mnemonic, which does not cover the area of policies and procedures!"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
</outline>
