    <outline text="Pencil Eigenvalues -- Definition #slide ">
        <outline text="The concept of eigenvalues can be generalised to regular matrix pencils as follows: ">
            <outline text="Consider the pairs $$(\beta,\alpha) \in \bar{K}\times\bar{K}$$ such that there exist $$0\neq y \in {\bar{K}}^n$$ verifying $$\beta Ay = \alpha By$$."/>
            <outline text="Define the equivalence relation">
                <outline text="$$(\beta_1,\alpha_1) \sim (\beta_2,\alpha_2)\quad\Longleftrightarrow\quad \beta_1\alpha_2 -  \beta_2\alpha_1 = 0$$."/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="We define the __spectrum__ $$\rho(A,B)$$ as $$(\bar{K}\times\bar{K})/\sim$$, the set of equivalence classes of $$\sim$$."/>
            <outline text="This is the set of above pairs $$(\beta,\alpha)$$ modulo the equivalence relation $$\sim$$."/>
            <outline text="The eigenvalues of the regular matrix pencil $$A-\lambda B$$ will be identified with the elements of $$\rho(A,B)$$."/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Finite and Infinite Eigenvalues #slide ">
        <outline text="The values">
            <outline text="$$\left\{ \left. \lambda = \frac{\alpha}{\beta} \;\right|\;[(\beta, \alpha)] \in \rho(A,B), \beta \neq 0 \right\}$$"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="are the __finite eigenvalues__ of the matrix pencil $$A-\lambda B$$."/>
        <outline text="If $$[(0, 1)] \in \rho(A,B)$$, it is a representative of the __eigenvalue at infinity__. "/>
        <outline text="The finite eigenvalues can be identified with the roots of $$f(\lambda) = \det(A-\lambda B)$$."/>
        <outline text="The algebraic multiplicity of a finite eigenvalue is its multiplicity as a root of $$f$$."/>
        <outline text="The integer $$d=n-\deg(P)$$ is the multiplicity of the eigenvalue at infinity."/>
        <outline text="If $$B=I$$, the finite eigenvalues are identified with the eigenvalues of $$A$$ in the usual sense. "/>
        <outline text="In this case and more generally if $$\det B \neq 0$$, the multiplicity of the eigenvalue at infinity is zero."/>
        <outline text="Notations: depending on context, we will identify "/>
