<outline text="Learning Objectives #slide ">
    <outline text="Understand the definition of integers and their representation using a number system"/>
    <outline text="Be familiar with the structure of univariate polynomials over the integers"/>
    <outline text="Appreciate the motivation behind introducing boolean numbers"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Numbers #eyo-style:Subsection  #h ">
    <outline text="Integers and Other Numbers #slide #maths-engage ">
        <outline text="Almost most natural mathematical object"/>
        <outline text="Numbers such as -333, -1, 0, 10, 2000,..."/>
        <outline text="Mathematical symbol: $$Z$$"/>
        <outline text="Union of positive and negative numbers, including 0"/>
        <outline text="Good for computer arithmetic, if not too big"/>
        <outline text="Other Numbers">
            <outline text="Rational Numbers (Fractions)"/>
            <outline text="Irrational Numbers"/>
            <outline text="Real Numbers"/>
            <outline text="Complex Numbers "/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Number Systems #slide #maths-engage">
        <outline text="Number system: a scheme to represent integers (or rationals) using digits"/>
        <outline text="Traditionally humans have used the decimal system"/>
        <outline text="Writing $$d$$ in a number system with basis $$b$$ means computing \[ d_{(b)} = d_{k}b^k + \ldots + d_{1}b + d_0 \quad (d_{i} \in \{0\ldots b-1\}) \]"/>
        <outline text="Here $$b$$ is the __basis __and the $$d_i$$ the __digits__"/>
        <outline text="Decimal system: $$b = 10$$"/>
        <outline text="Binary: $$b = 2$$, hexadecimal: $$b = 16$$, ternary: $$b = 3$$"/>
        <outline text="Can also represent fractions, using negative powers of $$b$$"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Mini-Exercise  #wfe-count:ex #slide #maths-engage">
        <outline text="Convert $$1010110_{2}$$ into decimal notation."/>
        <outline text="Write the integer 12 as a decimal, binary and ternary number."/>
        <outline text="Convert $$0.011_{2}$$ into decimal notation."/>
        <outline text="Write $$\frac{5}{8}$$ as a binary (optional: ternary) number."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Solutions: #slide #maths-engage #solution " complete="true">
        <outline text="$$101 0110_{(2) }= 1\cdot 2^6+1\cdot 2^4+1\cdot 2^2+1\cdot 2^1= 64+16+4+2= 86_{(10) }$$"/>
        <outline text="$$12= 12_{(10) }$$ (decimal number)"/>
        <outline text="$$12=9+3=1\cdot 3^2+1\cdot 3^1+ 0\cdot 3^0= 110_{(3) }$$ (ternary number) "/>
        <outline text="$$12 =8+4=1\cdot 2^3+1\cdot 2^2+0\cdot 2^1 +0\cdot 2^0= 1100 _{(2) }$$ (binary number)"/>
        <outline text="$$0.011_{(2) }=1\cdot 2^{-2}+1\cdot 2^{-3}=\frac{1}{4}+\frac{1}{8}=\frac{3}{8}_{(10) }$$"/>
        <outline text="$$\frac{5}{8}=\frac{3}{8}+\frac{2}{8}= (\frac{1}{4}+\frac{1}{8}) +\frac{1}{4}=\frac{1}{8}+\frac{1}{2}=0.101_{(2) }$$">
            <outline text="![mini-exercise-1.png](https://www.dropbox.com/s/a66nv0xf8hxli2v/maths-mini-1.png?dl=1) #eyo-style:Normal #solution #wfe-ignore-item "/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Polynomials #eyo-style:Subsection  #h ">
    <outline text="Polynomials #slide #maths-engage">
        <outline text="Notation: $$f(x)   = \textstyle\sum_{i=0}^{d} a_i x^i\textstyle\in Z[x]$$">
            <outline text="$$d =\deg f$$ is the __degree__ of $$f$$"/>
            <outline text="$$a_i$$ are the __coefficients__"/>
            <outline text="$$Z[x]$$: the __ring__ of __univariate__ polynomials with coefficients in the integers"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Example: $$f(x)=10x^2-5x+1$$ -- what is the degree of $$f$$ ? What are its coefficients?"/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Boolean Numbers #eyo-style:Subsection  #h ">
    <outline text="Booleans -- Working with Zeros and Ones #slide #maths-engage">
        <outline text="Fundamental truth values __false __and __true__ could be represented by integers: 0 and 1 "/>
        <outline text="Benefits:">
            <outline text="Logical reasoning, used to describe real-life scenarios or for mathematical proofs, can be done numerically"/>
            <outline text="Very efficient with computers which use binary numbers internally"/>
            <outline text="Reason: easy to represent digit value of 0 or 1 in hardware"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
</outline>
