<outline text="Integer Arithmetic #slide #maths-engage">
    <outline text="We again consider integer numbers"/>
    <outline text="We can perform __addition__, __subtraction__, __multiplication __and __division with remainder__"/>
    <outline text="Examples for division with remainder:">
        <outline text="10:5 = 2 since 10 = 2*5 + 0 (remainder 0)"/>
        <outline text="19:2 = 9 since 19 = 9*2 + 1 (remainder 1)"/>
        <outline text="23:5 = 4 since 23 = 4*5 + 3 (remainder 3)"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="We say that $$a$$ is divisible by $$b$$ if the division of $$a$$ by $$b$$ gives remainder 0"/>
    <outline text="In the above example, 10 is divisible by 5"/>
</outline>
<outline text="The Modulo Operation #eyo-style:Subsection  #h ">
    <outline text="The Modulo Operation -- Definition #slide #maths-engage">
        <outline text="Introducing $$a \bmod n$$: the modulo operation is defined as remainder of division of $$a$$ by $$n$$."/>
        <outline text="Example calculations:">
            <outline text="$$19 \bmod 5 = 4$$"/>
            <outline text="$$10 \bmod 5 = 0$$"/>
            <outline text="$$19 \bmod 2 = 1$$"/>
            <outline text="$$23 \bmod 5 = 3$$"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Real world scenario: we know that 25h is the same as 1h -- the clock is counted modulo 24!"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="The Modulo Operation -- Notations #slide #maths-engage">
        <outline text="Unfortunately, over time mathematicians have adopted different notations"/>
        <outline text="__Functional notation__: $$b=\bmod(a,n)$$"/>
        <outline text="Example: The input $$a=15$$ and $$n=4$$ gives the output $$b=3$$"/>
        <outline text="__Equational notation__: $$a \equiv b \pmod{n}$$ means $$a \bmod n = b \bmod n$$"/>
        <outline text="__Lazy mathematician's notation__: simply write $$a \equiv b $$ $$(n)$$"/>
        <outline text="Examples:">
            <outline text="$$15\equiv 11 \pmod{4}$$"/>
            <outline text="$$4 \equiv 19 \equiv 24 \equiv -1$$ $$(5)$$"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="The Modulo Operation -- Properties #slide #maths-engage">
        <outline text="You can use the Calculator in Windows to evaluate the mod function"/>
        <outline text="Small numbers can be done without a tool"/>
        <outline text="Additional Properties:">
            <outline text="$$a \bmod n$$ is always smaller than $$n$$"/>
            <outline text="$$a \bmod n=a$$ if $$a &amp;lt; n$$"/>
            <outline text="$$a+k\cdot n \bmod n\equiv a \bmod n$$ (useful if $$a$$ is negative)"/>
            <outline text="$$a \bmod n\equiv b \bmod n$$ is equivalent to saying $$n$$ divides $$a - b$$ (Mathematician's preferred definition)"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Mini-Exercise  #wfe-count:ex #slide #maths-engage">
        <outline text="Compute">
            <outline text="$$17 \mod 5$$"/>
            <outline text="$$343 \mod 2$$"/>
            <outline text="$$0 \mod 77$$"/>
            <outline text="$$97 \mod 98$$"/>
            <outline text="$$98 \mod 97$$"/>
            <outline text="$$-4 \mod 6$$"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Solutions: #slide #maths-engage " complete="true">
        <outline text="$$17 \mod 5 = 2$$ \label{firstone}"/>
        <outline text="$$343 \mod 2 = 1$$"/>
        <outline text="$$0 \mod 77 = 0$$"/>
        <outline text="$$97 \mod 98 = 97$$"/>
        <outline text="$$98 \mod 97 = 1$$"/>
        <outline text="$$-4 \mod 6 = 2$$"/>
        <outline text="Alternative notations for \ref{firstone}:">
            <outline text="$$17 \mod 5 \equiv 2$$"/>
            <outline text="$$17 \equiv 2 \; \mod 5$$"/>
            <outline text="$$17 \equiv 2 \; (5)$$"/>
            <outline text="$$17 \equiv 2 \equiv 12 \; (5)$$"/>
            <outline text="$$\mod(17,5) = 2$$"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Modular Arithmetic #eyo-style:Subsection  #h ">
    <outline text="Modular Arithmetic #slide #maths-engage">
        <outline text="We can perform addition, subtraction and multiplication modulo $$n$$"/>
        <outline text="This confines results to range $$[0..n-1]$$ -- there is no &quot;overflow&quot;"/>
        <outline text="Notation: $$a+b \bmod n$$ means $$(a+b) \bmod n$$"/>
        <outline text="Similar for $$-$$ and $$\cdot$$, also use exponentiation (power raising)"/>
        <outline text="Examples:">
            <outline text="$$7 + 5 = 2 \bmod 10$$"/>
            <outline text="Reason: $$7 + 5 = 12\;\;$$ and $$\;\;12 \bmod 10 = 2$$"/>
            <outline text="$$7\cdot 5 = 5 \bmod 10$$"/>
            <outline text="Reason: $$7 \cdot 5 = 35 \;\;$$ and $$\;\;35 \bmod 10 = 5$$"/>
            <outline text="$$7^5 = 16807 = 7 \bmod 10$$"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Associativity of Modular Arithmetic #slide #maths-engage">
        <outline text="An operation is __associative__, if brackets can be grouped freely (intermediate results can be computed in any order)"/>
        <outline text="It is easy to see that normal addition, multiplication and exponentiation are associative: e.g. $$(1+3) + 4 = 1 + (3+4) = 8$$"/>
        <outline text="This is correct for modular arithmetic as well!"/>
        <outline text="Example: we want to compute $$(2^5)^2 \bmod 30$$.">
            <outline text="\begin{eqnarray*}(2^5 \bmod 30)^2 \bmod 30 &amp; = &amp; (32 \bmod 30)^2 \bmod 30 \\ &amp; = &amp; 2^2 \bmod 30 \\ &amp; = &amp; 4. \end{eqnarray*} #eyo-style:Normal "/>
            <outline text="On the other hand, check that $$(2^5)^2 = 1024 = 4 \bmod 30$$."/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Remark: this is used in the proof of correctness for the RSA algorithm"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Mini-Exercise  #wfe-count:ex #slide #maths-engage">
        <outline text="Compute:">
            <outline text="$$5+7$$ mod $$10$$"/>
            <outline text="$$1+1$$ mod $$2$$"/>
            <outline text="$$1-1$$ mod $$2$$"/>
            <outline text="$$4\cdot 7$$ mod $$27$$"/>
            <outline text="$$14^7 \bmod 13$$"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Solutions: #slide #maths-engage " complete="true">
        <outline text="$$5+7$$ mod $$10$$ $$= 12 \mod 10 = 2$$"/>
        <outline text="$$1+1$$ mod $$2$$ $$= 2 \mod 2 = 0$$"/>
        <outline text="$$1-1$$ mod $$2$$ $$= 0 \mod 2 = 0$$"/>
        <outline text="$$4\cdot 7$$ mod $$27$$ $$= 28 \mod 27 = 1$$"/>
        <outline text="$$14^7 \bmod 13=(14\bmod 13)^7= 1^7 \mod 13 = 1$$"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Modular Arithmetic Tables #slide #maths-engage">
