<outline text="Computing the Greatest Common Divisor #eyo-style:Subsection  #h ">
    <outline text="Greatest Common Divisor #slide #maths-engage">
        <outline text="Definition: given two integers $$a$$ and $$b$$, their __greatest common divisor__ $$\gcd(a, b)$$ is the greatest integer dividing both $$a$$ and $$b$$."/>
        <outline text="Example: $$a = 28, \; b = 24 \Rightarrow \gcd(28, 24) = 4$$."/>
        <outline text="The gcd can be computed e.g. using prime factor decomposition: let $$a = p_1^{\alpha_1} \cdots p_n^{\alpha_n}$$ and $$b = p_1^{\beta_1} \cdots p_n^{\beta_n}$$ with $$\alpha_i, \beta_i\ge 0, p_i$$ prime."/>
        <outline text="It follows that then $$\gcd(a,b) = \prod p_i^{\min(\alpha_i,\beta_i)}$$."/>
        <outline text="We say that $$a$$ and $$b$$ are __co-prime__ if $$\gcd(a,b) = 1$$."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="The Euclidean Algorithm #slide #maths-engage ">
        <outline text="The __Euclidean Algorithm__ (EA) computes the greatest common divisor of two numbers."/>
        <outline text="Based on following __recursive__ identity:\[\gcd(a,b) = \gcd(b, a \bmod b)\]and $$\gcd(a, 0) = a$$ (__base case__). #fix "/>
        <outline text="We explain this using an example -- compute $$\gcd(80,45)$$:">
            <outline text="$$80: \color{orange}{45}  = 1$$ and $$80 - 1* \color{orange}{45}  =  \color{blue}{35}$$"/>
            <outline text="$$\color{orange}{45} : \color{blue}{35} = 1$$ and $$\color{orange}{45} - 1* \color{blue}{35} = \color{green}{10}$$"/>
            <outline text="$$\color{blue}{35}:\color{green}{10} = 3$$ and $$\color{blue}{35} - 3* \color{green}{10} =\color{red}{5}$$"/>
            <outline text="$$\color{green}{10} : \color{red}{5} = 2$$ and $$\color{green}{10} - 2* \color{red}{5} = \color{yellow}{0}\Rightarrow$$ algorithm terminates!"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Solution: $$\gcd(80, 45) = \color{red}{5}$$"/>
        <outline text="Reason: $$\gcd(80, 45)=\gcd(45, 35)=\cdots =\gcd(5, 0)=5$$."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Mini-Exercise  #wfe-count:ex #slide #maths-engage">
        <outline text="(a) Compute the $$\gcd$$ of $$75$$ and $$28$$, using">
            <outline text="(i) Prime factor decomposition,"/>
            <outline text="(ii) The Euclidean algorithm."/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="(b) Find the greatest common divisor $$g$$ of $$799$$ and $$987$$."/>
        <outline text="(c) Optional: Find integers $$x$$ and $$y$$ such that $$799x + 987y = g$$."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Solutions: #slide #maths-engage ">
