</outline>
<outline text="Computing the Modular Inverse #eyo-style:Subsection  #h ">
    <outline text="Modular Inverse #slide #maths-engage ">
        <outline text="Let $$a$$, $$n$$ be integers. The __inverse __of $$a$$ modulo $$n$$ is an integer $$x$$ such that $$a\cdot x \equiv 1 \bmod n$$."/>
        <outline text="Of course, then also $$x\cdot a \equiv 1 \bmod n$$."/>
        <outline text="We also write $$a^{-1} \bmod n$$ for the inverse."/>
        <outline text="Example:">
            <outline text="$$a = 3$$, $$n = 20$$."/>
            <outline text="The inverse of $$a$$ modulo $$20$$ is $$x = 7$$ since $$3\cdot 7 = 21 \equiv 1 \bmod 20$$."/>
            <outline text="Of course, also $$7\cdot 3 \equiv 1 \bmod 20$$."/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Note: the inverse does not always exist. In fact, the inverse of $$a$$ exists $$\Longleftrightarrow \gcd(a,n)=1$$."/>
        <outline text="Importance for cryptography: computing RSA keys."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="The Extended Euclidean Algorithm #slide #maths-engage ">
        <outline text="How can inverse $$a^{-1}\bmod n$$ be computed?">
            <outline text="From multiplication table"/>
            <outline text="Try and error"/>
            <outline text="Extended Euclidean Algorithm"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Using the extended version of Euclidean Algorithm (EEA):">
            <outline text="This computes $$u, v$$ such that $$ua + vb = \gcd(a, b)$$."/>
            <outline text="If $$\gcd(a, b)=1$$: computes $$u$$ as modular inverse of $$a$$ mod $$b$$"/>
            <outline text="Proof: $$ua = 1-vb$$ so $$ua \equiv 1 \mod b$$"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Example: ">
            <outline text="$$a = 3$$, $$b=20$$. "/>
            <outline text="EEA computes $$u=7$$, $$v=-1$$ with $$7 \cdot 3 - 1 \cdot 20 = 1$$"/>
            <outline text="Hence: $$3^{-1} \equiv 7 \bmod{20}$$"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="The Extended Euclidean Algorithm -- Example #slide #maths-engage">
        <outline text="Example: Compute modular inverse of $$29 \bmod 41$$"/>
        <outline text="Step 1 (Euclidean Algorithm):">
            <outline text="$$41:29 = 1$$ and $$41 \color{red}{- 1} * 29 = 12$$"/>
            <outline text="$$29:12 = 2$$ and $$29 \color{orange}{- 2} * 12 = 5$$"/>
            <outline text="$$12:5 = 2$$ and $$12 \color{blue}{- 2} *5 = 2$$"/>
            <outline text="$$5:2 = 2$$ and $$5 \color{green}{- 2} * 2 = 1$$"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Step 2 (Extended Euclidean Algorithm) -- redo EA operations on input (0, 1):">
            <outline text="$$0\color{red}{-1}*1 = -1$$"/>
            <outline text="$$1\color{orange}{-2}*(-1) = 3$$"/>
            <outline text="$$-1\color{blue}{-2}*3 = -7$$"/>
            <outline text="$$3\color{green}{-2}*(-7) = 17$$"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Solution: $$29^{-1} \bmod 41 = 17$$. Exercise: verify this!"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Mini-Exercise  #wfe-count:ex #slide #maths-engage">
        <outline text="(a) Compute the modular inverse of 28 mod 75."/>
        <outline text="(b) Solve the following linear equations:">
            <outline text="(i) $$8x \equiv 1$$ (mod 13)"/>
            <outline text="(ii) $$6x \equiv 11$$ (mod 29)"/>
            <outline text="(iii) $$8x \equiv 7$$ (mod 11)"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Solutions: #slide #maths-engage ">
        <outline text="![mini-exercise-9.png](https://www.dropbox.com/s/u6w3flmirszw43n/mini-exercise-9.png?dl=1) #eyo-style:Normal #solution"/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Summary #slide ">
