                            <outline text="Number Theory #CI7100_LO1 #slide ">
<outline text="Number theory studies properties of the integers."/>
<outline text="Founded by famous mathematicians such as Fermat, Gauss and Euler."/>
<outline text="&quot;Mathematics is the queen of the sciences, and number theory is the queen of mathematics&quot; (Gauss)."/>
<outline text="Surprisingly difficult to prove even simple mathematical properties."/>
<outline text="Believed to be without serious applications, before the invention of public key cryptography."/>
<outline text="Our main interest: use of computational number theory for the RSA algorithm."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Prime Numbers #slide #maths-engage">
<outline text="Definition: __a prime number is any integer &gt; 1 that is divisible only by itself and 1.__"/>
<outline text="Examples: $$2, 3, 5, 7, 11, 47, 1997, \ldots$$"/>
<outline text="It is easy to see that there is an infinite number of prime numbers. #blue "/>
<outline text="Computers can decide relatively efficiently whether a given number is a prime number."/>
<outline text="Integers that are not primes can be decomposed into smaller integers -- for example: $$12 = 4 \cdot 3$$"/>
<outline text="__Factorisation __of an integer: writing a given integer as product of prime numbers.">
    <outline text="Every non-zero integer can be written __uniquely__ (up to sign) as product of prime numbers"/>
    <outline text="Example: $$10 = 2\cdot 5,\;\; 12 = 2\cdot 2\cdot 3,\;\; 19 = 19$$"/>
</outline>
<outline text="The problem of prime factorisation turns out to be a computationally very difficult problem."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Mini-Exercise  #wfe-count:ex #slide #maths-engage">
<outline text="Decompose into prime factors:">
    <outline text="33"/>
    <outline text="45"/>
    <outline text="1001"/>
    <outline text="2020"/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Solutions: #slide #maths-engage #solution " complete="true">
<outline text="$$33=3\cdot 11$$"/>
<outline text="$$45=3^2\cdot 5$$"/>
<outline text="$$1001=7\cdot 11\cdot 13$$"/>
<outline text="$$2020=2^2\cdot 5 \cdot 101$$"/>
<outline text="#wfe-ignore-outline ">
    <outline text="![mini-exercise-2.png](https://www.dropbox.com/s/6xxi6i69yls148b/mini-exercise-2.png?dl=1) #eyo-style:Normal "/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Euler's Function #slide #maths">
<outline text="Euler's function $$\phi(n)$$ plays an important role in computational number theory"/>
<outline text="Many properties and theorems relating to integers can be stated, involving this function."/>
<outline text="Our main interest: use for the proof of correctness of the RSA algorithm."/>
<outline text="For $$n &gt; 1$$, $$\phi(n)$$ is the number of integers $$k \in \{ 1,\ldots, n-1 \}$$ that are co-prime to $$n$$"/>
<outline text="So, formally: ">
    <outline text="$$ \phi(n) := \;\mid \{ k \in \{ 1,.., n-1 \} : \gcd(k, n) = 1 \} \mid. $$ #eyo-style:Normal "/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Mini-Exercise  #wfe-count:ex #slide #maths">
<outline text="Compute $$\phi(15)$$. Tip: you need to successively examine all of the integers $$1, 2, \ldots, 14$$."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Fermat's Little Theorem and Euler's Theorem #slide #maths">
<outline text="These two related theorems state properties of repeated multiplication, when using modular arithmetic."/>
<outline text="Fermat's Little Theorem: __if $$p$$ is prime and $$p \nmid a$$, then $$a^{p-1} \equiv 1 \: (\bmod p)$$__."/>
<outline text="Application in cryptography:">
    <outline text="Primality testing"/>
    <outline text="Integer factorisation"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Euler's Theorem: __if $$\gcd(a,n) = 1$$ then $$a^{\phi(n)} \equiv 1 \: (\bmod n)$$__."/>
<outline text="Applications in cryptography:">
    <outline text="RSA algorithm"/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Mini-Exercise  #wfe-count:ex #slide #maths" listStyle="arabic">
<outline text="Verify Euler's Theorem for $$n=15$$ and $$a=2$$."/>
<outline text="How are Euler's and Fermat's Theorem related? Hint: what is $$\phi(p)$$ for $$p$$ prime?"/>
<outline text="Prove that for $$p$$, $$q$$ prime and $$p \nmid a$$, $$q \nmid a$$, one has $$ a^{(p-1)(q-1)} \equiv 1 \pmod {pq}. $$ Hint: Use Euler's theorem and the fact that $$\phi(nm) = \phi(n) \phi(m)$$."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Solutions: Verify Euler's Theorem #slide" complete="true">
<outline text="Euler's Theorem states that if $$\gcd(a,n) = 1$$ then $$a^{\phi(n)} \equiv 1 \: (\bmod n)$$.  "/>
<outline text="Here, with $$n=15$$ and $$a=2$$, $$\gcd(2,15) = 1$$, as they have no larger common divisors.  "/>
<outline text="We saw in the solution to Mini-Exercise 11 that $$\phi(15) = 8$$.  "/>
<outline text="Now  $$2^8 = 256$$ and $$256 = 17 \times 15 + 1$$, so $$2^{\phi(15)} \equiv 1 \: (\bmod 15)$$ and Euler's Theorem is verified for these two values."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Solutions: Euler's Theorem and Fermat's Theorem #slide" complete="true">
<outline text="Consider integers $$a, p$$ with $$p$$ prime and $$p \nmid a$$.  "/>
<outline text="Then by Fermat's Little Theorem, $$a^{p-1} \equiv 1 \: (\bmod p)$$.  "/>
<outline text="Because $$p$$ is prime and $$p \nmid a$$ it must also be the case that $$\gcd(a,p) = 1$$.      What is $$\phi(p)$$?  Because for every positive integer $$m &lt; p$$, $$\gcd(m,p) = 1$$, we must have $$\phi(p) = p - 1$$.  "/>
<outline text="Substituting $$\phi(p)$$ for $$p - 1$$ in the expression in Fermat's Little Theorem gives us $$a^{\phi(p)} \equiv 1 \: (\bmod p)$$, which is the expression in Euler's Theorem.  % EP bug"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Solutions: cont. #slide" complete="true">
<outline text="For $$p$$, $$q$$ prime and $$p \nmid a$$, $$q \nmid a$$,  $$ a^{(p-1)(q-1)} \equiv 1 \pmod {pq}$$"/>
<outline text="Recall from the last answer, we had $$\phi(p) = p-1$$."/>
<outline text="So we can rewrite $$ a^{(p-1)(q-1)} = a^{\phi(p)\phi(q)} = a^{\phi(pq)}$$ using the hint."/>
<outline text="Now $$\gcd(a, pq) = 1$$ because $$p \nmid a$$ and $$q \nmid a$$, so by Euler's Theorem, $$a^{\phi(pq)} \equiv 1 \pmod {pq}$$ as required."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Summary #slide ">
<outline text="Understand the importance of (computational) number theory for cryptography, and the RSA algorithm in particular."/>
<outline text="Know the definition of a prime number and differentiate between the computational tasks of prime factorisation/primality testing."/>
<outline text="Comprehend the definition of  Euler's Function."/>
<outline text="Be familiar with Fermat's Little Theorem and Euler's Theorem, and their use for cryptography."/>
                            </outline>
