                        <outline text="Bayesian Games #h ">
                            <outline text="Motivation #slide ">
<outline text="Incomplete information about the strategies and payoffs"/>
<outline text="In particular, one player has incomplete information about the other player."/>
<outline text="Can be modelled by introducing Nature (a random value -- signal) as a player in the game "/>
<outline text="This converts a game of incomplete information to a game of imperfect information"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Notations #slide ">
<outline text="$$N$$ -- State of Nature #GT #bayes"/>
<outline text="$$A_i \in (A \times T)$$ -- action set of $$P_i$$, specified for specific types #GT #bayes "/>
<outline text="$$a_i \in  (A \times T)$$ -- a specific action of $$P_i$$, specified for specific types #GT #bayes "/>
<outline text="$$\theta_i \in \Theta$$ -- type of player $$P_i$$ (as a function of $$N$$) #GT #bayes "/>
<outline text="$$p_i$$ -- probability distribution (&quot;beliefs&quot;) over $$N$$, for the specific player $$P_i$$ #GT #bayes "/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Overview #slide ">
<outline text="Non-Bayesian game: strategy profile is a NE iff every strategy in that profile is a best response to every other strategy"/>
<outline text="Our game: find Bayesian Nash Equilibria (BNE) "/>
<outline text="Bayesian Games: Players maximise their expected payoffs"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Basic Concepts #slide ">
<outline text="Bayesian are methods in probability and statistics named after Thomas Bayes. These methods include Bayesian Games which provides a new way for analysing incomplete information games. In such games, there is a certain belief with a known probability distribution"/>
<outline text="John Harsanyi developed a new theory for analysing games: Bayesian Games">
    <outline text="&quot;developing the highly innovative analysis of games of incomplete information, so-called Bayesian games&quot;"/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Bayesian game consists of: #slide " _note="@book{Osborne1994,&#xA;  title={A course in game theory},&#xA;  author={Osborne, Martin J and Rubinstein, Ariel},&#xA;  year={1994},&#xA;  publisher={MIT press}&#xA;}">
<outline text="finite set N (the set of players)">
    <outline text="each player has his own set of actions"/>
    <outline text="each player has a finite set of signals and a signal function"/>
    <outline text="each player has a prior belief"/>
    <outline text="each player has a preference relation"/>
</outline>
<outline text="finite set set of $$\Omega$$ (the set of states)"/>
<outline text="Bayesian Games (Games of Incomplete information) represents players' uncertainties about the game player" _note="@book{Shoham2009,&#xA;  title={Multiagent systems: Algorithmic, game-theoretic, and logical foundations},&#xA;  author={Shoham, Yoav and Leyton-Brown, Kevin},&#xA;  year={2009},&#xA;  publisher={Cambridge University Press}&#xA;}"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Bayesian Game -- Definition #slide">
<outline text="A Bayesian game can be represented as a tuple $$(N, A,\Theta, p, u)$$ where:">
    <outline text="$$N$$ is a set of agents"/>
    <outline text="$$A = A_1 \times\cdots \times A_n$$ where $$A_i$$ is the set of actions available to player $$i$$"/>
    <outline text="$$\Theta = \Theta_1 \times\cdots \times \Theta_n$$ where $$\Theta_i$$ is the type space of player $$i$$"/>
    <outline text="$$p : \Theta \rightarrow [0, 1]$$ is a common prior over types"/>
    <outline text="$$u = (u_1, \cdots , u_n)$$, where $$u_i : A \times \Theta \rightarrow \R$$ is the utility function for player $$i$$"/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Two-Player Bayesian Game -- Definition #slide">
<outline text="A Two-Player Bayesian game can be represented as $$G(A,B, \Theta, p)$$ where:">
    <outline text="$$\Theta$$ is the type space of the first player"/>
    <outline text="$$A = A_1 \times\cdots \times A_n$$ where $$A_i$$ is the set of actions available to player $$i$$"/>
    <outline text="$$u = (u_1, \cdots , u_n)$$, where $$u_i : A \times \Theta \rightarrow \R$$ is the utility function for player $$i$$"/>
    <outline text="$$p : \Theta \rightarrow [0, 1]$$ is a common prior over types"/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Harsanyi-Transformation #slide ">
<outline text="John Harsanyi developed a theory for analysing Bayesian Games. "/>
<outline text="Idea: convert game with uncertainty over strategies (types) into game with payoff uncertainty. "/>
<outline text="Assume knowledge of probability distribution for types. "/>
<outline text="This transforms a game of incomplete information into one of imperfect information. "/>
<outline text="This can then solved with standard techniques. "/>
<outline text="Disadvantage: the resulting game is of bigger size and hence more difficult to analyse."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Bayesian Nash Equilibrium (BNE) Types #slide ">
<outline text="__Pooling Equilibrium__: if the first player's best response is independent of any type. It remains the same, regardless of his belief in the type of Player 2."/>
<outline text="__Separating Equilibrium__: if best response is different, depending on the type."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="References #slide ">
<outline text="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_game"/>
                            </outline>
