                            <outline text="Basic Concepts and Terminologies #h">
<outline text="Bimatrix Game #slide #notation ">
    <outline text="$$A$$ and $$B$$ -- real matrices of dimension $$m\times n$$. "/>
    <outline text="A bimatrix game is a two-person, non-zero sum finite game $$G=(X,Y,A,B)$$ where ">
        <outline text="$$X$$ and $$Y$$ are the sets of strategies for the different players, #paper:order-2-barrier #paper:adv-learning "/>
        <outline text="$$A:X\times Y \mapsto \mathbb{R}$$ is the payoff function for Player 1,  #paper:order-2-barrier #paper:adv-learning "/>
        <outline text="$$B:X\times Y \mapsto \mathbb{R}$$ is the payoff function for Player 2.  #paper:order-2-barrier #paper:adv-learning "/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="The first (row) player plays a row action #paper:order-2-barrier #paper:adv-learning "/>
    <outline text="The second (column) player plays a column action #paper:order-2-barrier #paper:adv-learning "/>
</outline>
<outline text="Strategies #slide #CYENS #notation ">
    <outline text="$$x, y$$ -- strategies">
        <outline text="pure strategies #paper:order-2-barrier #paper:adv-learning "/>
        <outline text="mixed strategies (probability vectors $$x,y \in {\mathbb R}^n$$ with $$0\le x_i\le 1$$, $$\sum_i x_i=1$$ and $$0\le y_i\le 1$$, $$\sum_i y_i=1$$) #paper:order-2-barrier #paper:adv-learning "/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="$$s=(x, y)$$ --  __strategy profile__, groups strategies of each player together. #paper:order-2-barrier "/>
    <outline text="Given a bimatrix game with payoff matrices $$A$$ and $$B$$, a __mixed strategy__ for Player 1 (the row player) is a real vector $$x$$ satisfying $$0\le x_i\le 1$$, with $$\sum x_i = 1$$. "/>
    <outline text="A mixed strategy for Player 2 (the column player) is a real vector $$y$$ satisfying the same properties. "/>
    <outline text="A __completely mixed strategy__ has all vector entries strictly greater than zero. "/>
    <outline text="The corresponding payoffs to Player 1 and Player 2 are $$^t{\!}xAy$$ and $$^t{\!}xBy$$ respectively. "/>
</outline>
<outline text="Best Response #slide ">
    <outline text="$$\mathcal{BR}(y)$$ -- the set of __best responses__ to a strategy $$y$$ (the set of all strategies $$x$$ of Player 1 maximizing his expected payoff $$x^\top Ay$$)."/>
    <outline text="Similarly a best response to $$x$$ is a strategy $$y\in \mathcal{BR}(x)$$ of Player 2 that maximizing her expected payoff $$x^\top By$$. "/>
    <outline text="#definition">
        <outline text="A Player 2 strategy $$y^*$$ is a __Nash equilibrium best response__ to a Player 1 strategy $$x$$ (denoted $$y^* \in \mathcal{BR}(x)$$ in the sequel) is a strategy $$y^*$$ satisfying $$ xBy^* \ge    xBy$$ for all other Player 2 strategy $$y$$."/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Nash Equilibrium Strategies #slide #CYENS #notation ">
    <outline text="#definition ">
        <outline text="A __Nash Equilibrium strategy__ $$(x^*,y^*)$$ satisfies: ">
            <outline text="$$ x^*Ay^* \ge  xAy^* \quad\forall x$$"/>
            <outline text="$$ x^*By^* \ge    x^*By\quad\forall y$$"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="A Nash equilibrium strategy is hence a strategy pair $$(x^*,y^*)$$ of mutual best responses: $$ x^* \in \mathcal{BR}(y^*) $$ and $$ y^* \in \mathcal{BR}(x^*) $$."/>
    <outline text=" $$x^*,y^*$$ -- __Nash Equilibrium strategies__ of the game satisfying  ">
        <outline text="$$ x^*Ay^* \ge  xAy^* \;\;\forall x,\quad x^*By^* \ge    x^*By\;\;\forall y$$. #wfe-style:Equation #paper:order-2-barrier #paper:adv-learning "/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="$$s^*=(x^*,y^*)$$ -- __Nash Equilibrium strategy profile __ "/>
</outline>
<outline text="Game Values #slide #notation ">
    <outline text="$$v=(v_A,v_B)$$ -- a (not necessarily unique) equilibrium value pair of a bimatrix game #paper:order-2-barrier #paper:adv-learning "/>
</outline>
<outline text="Nash Equilibrium Types #slide ">
    <outline text="NE strategies may be pure or mixed, and the corresponding NE is referred to as a pure or mixed NE. #paper:order-2-barrier #paper:adv-learning "/>
    <outline text="If all components of a strategy vector are non-negative, it is called a weakly completely mixed strategy. #paper:order-2-barrier"/>
    <outline text="If all components of a strategy vectors are strictly positive, it is called a strictly completely mixed strategy. #paper:order-2-barrier"/>
    <outline text="Depending on the type of completely mixed strategies involved in a NE, one has a __strict__ NE. Otherwise, the NE is __non-strict__."/>
    <outline text="Depending on the type of completely mixed strategies involved in a NE, one has a __strict__ NE. Otherwise, the NE is __non-strict__."/>
    <outline text="CHECK"/>
</outline>
<outline text="A Best Response Lemma #h ">
    <outline text="A Best Response Lemma #slide #CYENS ">
        <outline text="#lemma:best-response ">
            <outline text="If Player 1's mixed strategy $$x^*$$ is a best response to the (mixed) strategy $$y$$ of the other player, then, for each pure strategy $$e_i$$ such that $$x_i &gt; 0$$, it must be the case that $$e_i$$ is itself a best response.  In particular, the payoff $$e_i Ay$$ must be the same for all such strategies."/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Note: an analogous lemma can be stated for Player 2, $$y^*$$ and $$x$$."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Proof (I) #slide #CYENS ">
        <outline text="Recap: due to $$x^* \in \mathcal{BR}(y^*)$$ we have $${}^t \!x^*Ay^*=v_{A}$$ and $${}^t \!xAy^*\le v_{A}$$ for all $$x$$. "/>
        <outline text="Let us write $${}^t \!x^*= (x^*_{1},\ldots ,x^*_{i},\ldots ,x^*_{n})$$ and assume $$x^*_{i}\neq 0$$."/>
        <outline text="Furthermore, denote $${}^t \!e_{i}= (\underbrace{0,\ldots ,0}_{i-1}, 1, 0,\ldots , 0)$$."/>
        <outline text="It is clear that $${}^t \!e_{i}Ay^*\le v_{A}$$."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Proof (II) #slide #CYENS ">
        <outline text="Now assume $${}^t \!e_{i}Ay^*&lt; v_{A}$$, minimal for all pure strategies. "/>
        <outline text="Find $$j\neq i$$, $$x_{j}^*\neq 0$$ (such $$j$$ exists since $$x^*$$ is not pure) and define">
            <outline text="$${}^t \!\hat{x}={}^t \!x^*-x_i^* {\;}^t\! e_i+x_i^* {\;}^t\! e_j=(x^*_{1},\ldots ,0,\ldots ,x^*_{j}+x^*_{i},\ldots ,x^*_{n})$$."/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="This is a mixed strategy as all components of strategy vector still add up to one."/>
        <outline text="It follows">
            <outline text="$$^t\!\hat{x}Ay^*={}^t\!x^*Ay^*+x_{i}^*\overbrace{(^t\!e_{j}Ay^*-{}^t\!e_{i}Ay^*)}^{&gt;0}&gt;\,{}^t\! x^*Ay^*$$"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="which is a contradiction. Hence we must have $${}^t \!e_{i}Ay^*= v_{A}$$. "/>
        <outline text="An additional consequence is $${}^t \!x^*Ay^*\le v_{A}{}^t\!e$$. "/>
        <outline text="Furthermore, since $${}^t \!e_{i}A$$ is the $$i$$th row of $$A$$,">
            <outline text="$$Ay^*= v_{A}e$$. "/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Strategical Equivalence #h ">
<outline text="Motivation #slide ">
    <outline text="Sometimes, two different games have the same strategic constraints "/>
    <outline text="This might not be directly obvious from the payoff functions "/>
    <outline text="But it can be seen from the relationship that exists between the two game matrices"/>
    <outline text="This means that the Nash solution strategies coincide"/>
    <outline text="But not necessarily the values"/>
    <outline text="This is formalised with the concept of strategic equivalence"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Notations #slide ">
    <outline text="Let $$\mathcal{B}(I)$$ denote the set of payoff matrices with equal columns"/>
    <outline text="This means a row $$R_i$$ has the only entry $$\alpha_i$$"/>
    <outline text="This means $$S\in \mathcal{B}(I)\Longleftrightarrow S={\rm diag}(\alpha_1,\ldots,\alpha_m)\cdot E$$. "/>
    <outline text="Similarly denote $$\mathcal{B}(J)$$ for matrices of equal rows. "/>
    <outline text="This means matrices of the form $$T=E\cdot {\rm diag}(\beta_1,\ldots,\beta_m)$$"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Strategical Equivalence -- Definition #slide ">
    <outline text="#definition:strategic-equivalent ">
        <outline text="The games $$(A, B)$$ and $$(C,D)$$ are __strategically equivalent__ iff" listStyle="arabic">
            <outline text="$$ \exists \lambda &gt; 0 $$ such that $$C- \lambda A  \in \mathcal{B}(J) $$ or $$A$$ and $$C$$ are equivalently trival, and"/>
            <outline text="$$ \exists \mu&gt; 0 $$ such that $$D- \mu B  \in \mathcal{B}(I) $$ or $$B$$ and $$D$$ are equivalently trival."/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="This means $$C=\lambda A+E\cdot {\rm diag}(\beta_1,\ldots,\beta_m)$$ and $$D=\mu B+ {\rm diag}(\alpha_1,\ldots,\alpha_m)\cdot E$$. "/>
</outline>
<outline text="NE Theorem #slide ">
    <outline text="Assume the games $$G=G(A,B)$$ and $$\tilde{G}=G(\tilde{A},\tilde{B})$$ are strategically equivalent. Then any strategy profile $$s$$ is a Nash Equilibrium profile for $$G$$, iff it is one for $$\tilde{G}$$. "/>
</outline>
<outline text="Proof #slide ">
    <outline text="One shows that best responses for any strategy coincide for both games. "/>
    <outline text="Let $$x^*\in {\mathcal{BR}}_G(y)$$ be a best response for $$y$$ in the game $$G$$. "/>
    <outline text="Hence $$x^*Ay\ge xAy$$ for all strategies $$x$$. "/>
    <outline text="But then">
        <outline text="$$x^*\tilde{A}y=x^*Ay+(\alpha_1,\alpha_2)y\ge xAy+(\alpha_1,\alpha_2)y=x\tilde{A}y\quad \forall x$$."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Thus $$x^*\in {\mathcal{BR}}_{\tilde{G}(y)}$$. "/>
    <outline text="Similarly for $$y^*\in {\mathcal{BR}}_G(x)$$."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Strategical Equivalence for 2x2 Games #slide ">
    <outline text="The games $$G(A,B)$$ and $$\tilde{G}(\tilde{A},\tilde{B})$$ are said to be __strategically equivalent__ iff there exist real numbers $$\alpha_1, \alpha_2, \beta_1, \beta_2, \mu&gt;0, \sigma&gt;0$$ such that">
        <outline text="$$\tilde{A}=\mu {A}+\begin{pmatrix}  \alpha_1&amp; \alpha_2\\\alpha_1 &amp; \alpha_2 \\  \end{pmatrix}$$ and $$\tilde{B}=\sigma{B}+\begin{pmatrix}  \beta_1&amp; \beta_1\\\beta_2 &amp; \beta_2 \\  \end{pmatrix}$$.">
            <outline text="$$\Longleftrightarrow$$ $$A-\mu \tilde{A}=\begin{pmatrix}  \alpha_1&amp; \alpha_2\\\alpha_1 &amp; \alpha_2 \\  \end{pmatrix}$$ and $$B-\sigma\tilde{B}=\begin{pmatrix}  \beta_1&amp; \beta_1\\\beta_2 &amp; \beta_2 \\  \end{pmatrix}$$ "/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Strategical Equivalence Transformation #slide ">
    <outline text="For non-trivial games this means $$G \mapsto \tilde{G}$$ where">
        <outline text="$$\tilde{A}=\sigma A+E\; {\rm diag}(\beta_1,\ldots,\beta_m)$$ and"/>
        <outline text="$$\tilde{B}=\mu B+ {\rm diag}(\alpha_1,\ldots,\alpha_m)\; E$$. "/>
    </outline>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Algorithms for Solving Bimatrix Games #h">
<outline text="Introduction #slide ">
    <outline text="A large body of research investigating the design of algorithms for solving bimatrix games exists. "/>
    <outline text="Most methods are based on linear techniques, an overview of such approaches is given e.g. in \cite{@Stengel2002}. "/>
</outline>
<outline text="Solving 2x2 Generic Bimatrix Games #h">
    <outline text="Definition of Generic Game #slide #CYENS">
        <outline text="Consider the following generic bimatrix game in strategic normal form:">
            <outline text="$$\begin{array}{c|c|c}  &amp;l &amp;r \\ \hline u &amp; a_{1}, a_{2} &amp; b_{1}, b_{2} \\  \hline d &amp;c_{1}, c_{2}&amp; d_1,d_2  \end{array}$$"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="To check the existence of a completely mixed-strategy equilibrium, we use a fundamental theorem due to Nash."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Best Response to (Row) Player 1 #slide #CYENS">
        <outline text="Suppose the row player plays $$u$$ with probability $$\alpha$$ and $$d$$ with probability $$1-\alpha$$."/>
        <outline text="He uses a mixed strategy $$\sigma=\alpha u+(1-\alpha)d$$."/>
        <outline text="Then, if the column player uses both $$l$$ and $$r$$ in the mixed equilibrium best response, we have seen (Best Response Lemma) that they must both have the same payoff $$v_B$$."/>
        <outline text="The payoff to $$l$$ against $$\sigma$$ is $$\alpha{a_2}+(1-\alpha)c_{2}$$, and the payoff to $$r$$ against $$\sigma$$ is $$\alpha b_{2}+(1-\alpha)d_2$$. "/>
        <outline text="Equating these two, we find $$\alpha=\dfrac{d_2-c_2}{d_2-b_2+a_2-c_2}$$."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Best Response to (Column) Player 2 #slide #CYENS ">
        <outline text="This follows sthe same reasoning, assuming the column player uses the strategy $$\tau=\beta l +(1-\beta)r$$ (that is, plays $$l$$ with probability $$\beta$$). "/>
        <outline text="Then, if the row player uses both $$u$$ and $$d$$, they must both have the same payoff against $$\beta$$. "/>
        <outline text="The payoff to $$u$$ against $$\beta$$ is $$\beta a_{1} +(1-\sigma)b_{1}$$, and the payoff to $$d$$ against $$\sigma$$ is $$\beta c_{1}+ (1 -\beta)d_1$$. "/>
        <outline text="Eventually we find ">
            <outline text="$$\beta=\dfrac{d_1-b_1}{d_1-b_1+a_1-c_1}.$$"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Discussion #slide #CYENS  ">
        <outline text="For this to make sense, the denominator must be nonzero, and the right-hand side must lie between zero and one. "/>
        <outline text="Note that the __column__ players strategy is determined by the requirement that __row__ players two strategies be equal."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="References">
        <outline text="[https://oyc.yale.edu/sites/default/files/mixed_strategies_handout_0_0.pdf](https://oyc.yale.edu/sites/default/files/mixed_strategies_handout_0_0.pdf)"/>
    </outline>
</outline>
