                        <outline text="Matrix Games #h " _note="#slide #h #hh ">
                            <outline text="Basic Concepts and Terminologies #h  ">
<outline text="Notations and Definitions #slide">
    <outline text="$$A$$ -- square, real matrix of dimension $$n$$"/>
    <outline text="$$x, y$$ -- strategies, can be:">
        <outline text="pure strategies"/>
        <outline text="mixed strategies (probability vectors $$x,y \in {\mathbb R}^n$$ with entries summing up to 1: $$0\le x_i\le 1$$, $$\sum_i x_i=1$$ and $$0\le y_i\le 1$$, $$\sum_i y_i=1$$)"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="$$v=v(A)$$ -- the unique value of the game"/>
    <outline text=" $$x^*,y^*$$ -- optimal solutions of the game">
        <outline text="$$x^*Ay^*=v$$"/>
        <outline text="$$xAy^* \le v^- \;\forall x$$"/>
        <outline text="$$x^* Ay \ge v^+ \;\forall y$$ "/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Let $$x$$ be an optimal strategy for Player 1. "/>
    <outline text="Then any $$i$$ for which $$x_i=0$$ is called an inactive strategy. "/>
</outline>
<outline text="Matrix Games #slide">
    <outline text="These are two-person, zero-sum finite games $$G=(X,Y,A)$$ where ">
        <outline text="$$X$$ and $$Y$$ are the sets of strategies for the different players "/>
        <outline text="$$A:X\times Y \mapsto {\mathbb R}$$ is the payoff function. "/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="We use a matrix to represent the payoff function"/>
    <outline text="The first (row) player plays a row action "/>
    <outline text="The second (column) player plays a column action"/>
    <outline text="Zero-sum game: one player wins what the other player loses"/>
</outline>
<outline text="VALUE AND OPTIMAL SOLUTIONS #hh ">
    <outline text="MINIMAX AND MAXIMIN #hh ">
        <outline text="Lower and Upper Value #slide #definition #deconstruct:equilibrium ">
            <outline text="We denote ">
                <outline text="$$v^{-}(A):=\max_x \min_y xAy$$ the __lower value__ of the matrix game $$G(A)$$. "/>
                <outline text="$$v^{+}(A):= \min_y \max_x xAy $$ the __upper value__ of the game. "/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Using elementary mathematics, it can be seen that $$v^{-} \le v^{+}$$."/>
            <outline text="Min-max Theorem (due to von Neumann): ">
                <outline text="In the setting of a matrix game, these two values can be seen to be the same: $$v^- = {v^+}$$."/>
                <outline text="Proof: non-trivial. "/>
            </outline>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Value and Optimal Solutions #slide #deconstruct:equilibrium ">
            <outline text="We can hence define the __value__ of the game uniquely by $$v(A):=\max_x \min_y xAy = \min_y \max_x xAy $$."/>
            <outline text="Any strategy $$x^*, y^*$$ satisfying $$x^*Ay^* = v$$ is called __optimal__. "/>
            <outline text="There may be several such $$x^*, y^*$$."/>
            <outline text="They are a __mutual best response__ pairs."/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="BILINEAR #hh ">
        <outline text="Specialisation of Nash Equilibrium Concept #slide">
            <outline text="Often, NE are not mentioned in the context of zero-sum games."/>
            <outline text="We say that $$(x^*, y^*)$$ is a NE strategy profile iff">
                <outline text="$$\forall x: \; xAy^* \le x^*Ay^* = v^-$$ "/>
                <outline text="$$\forall y: \; x^* Ay \ge x^*Ay^* = v^+$$ "/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Note that one can show for zero-sum games that any combination of different optimal strategies yields an equilibrium strategy. "/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="BR #hh ">
        <outline text="Best Response #slide">
            <outline text="Any player will want to maximise their payoff, which means ">
                <outline text="maximising $$xA$$ if $$x$$ is Player 1's strategy,"/>
                <outline text="minimising $$Ay$$ if $$y$$ is Player 2's strategy. "/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="With their best response, a player will want to maximise what she gets from the other player's move.">
                <outline text="The best response for Player 1 is to assume maximum damage caused by the other player, and then to try mitigating this as much as possible: $$ \max_x \min_y xAy =: v^{-}$$. "/>
                <outline text="The best response for Player 2 is to assume Player 1 seeks maximum gain, and then to limit this as much as possible: $$\min_y \max_x xAy =: v^{+}$$."/>
            </outline>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Equalizer  Formulation Using Best Responses #slide "/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="SLACK-BASED #hh ">
        <outline text="Principle of Indifference (Player 1) #slide ">
            <outline text="The following can be seen as a result of the Best Response Lemma for bimatrix games:"/>
            <outline text="Lemma. #lemma ">
                <outline text="If $$x^*$$ is an optimal solution for Player 1 and $$x^*_{i}&gt;0$$ (i.e. $$i$$ is an active strategy), then every optimal solution $$y^*$$ for Player 2 satisfies" colorLabel="3"/>
                <outline text="$$(\underbrace{0,\ldots,0}_{i-1},1,\underbrace{0,\ldots,0}_{n-i-1}) Ay^*=\text{row}_{i}(A)y^* = v^-$$." colorLabel="3"/>
                <outline text="For any other index $$k$$ with $$x_k^*=0$$ one has $$\text{row}_{k}(A)y^* &lt; v^-$$." colorLabel="3"/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Hence we have $$Ay^*=v^-e-b$$ where $$b\ge 0$$."/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Principle of Indifference (Player 2) #slide ">
            <outline text="A similar statement holds for an optimal solution $$y^*$$ for Player 2. "/>
            <outline text="Lemma. #lemma ">
                <outline text="If $$y^*$$ is an optimal solution for Player 2 and $$y_{i}&gt;0$$ (i.e. $$j$$ is an active strategy), then every optimal solution $$x^*$$ for Player 1 satisfies" colorLabel="3"/>
                <outline text="$$x^*A(\underbrace{0,\ldots,0}_{j-1},1,\underbrace{0,\ldots,0}_{m-j-1}) =x^*\text{col}_{j}(A) = v^+$$." colorLabel="3"/>
                <outline text="For any other index $$k$$ with $$x_k^*=0$$ one has $$x^*\text{col}_{k}(A) &gt; v^+$$." colorLabel="3"/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Hence we have $$x^*A=v^+e+b$$ where $$b\ge 0$$."/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Value -- Discrete Definition #slide ">
            <outline text="Starting with $$v^-(A):=\max_x \min_y xAy$$ we use the Principle of Indifference: $$v^-(A):=\max_x x\text{col}_{i}(A)$$"/>
            <outline text="Similar for $$ \min_y \max_x xAy $$."/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
</outline>
