<outline text="Simple type of a dynamic Bayesian game. "/>
<outline text="It is a game with two players, called the sender and the receiver: ">
    <outline text="The sender can have one of several types. The sender's type $$t$$, determines the payoff function of the sender. It is the private information of the sender - it is not known to the receiver."/>
    <outline text="The receiver has only a single type, so by the assumption of common priors, their payoff function is known to both players."/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Game Play #slide ">
<outline text="The game has two steps:">
    <outline text="The sender plays in the first step. They can play one of several actions, which are called __messages__. The set of possible messages is $$\mathcal M = \{m_1, m_2, m_3,\ldots, m_j\}$$."/>
    <outline text="The receiver plays in the second step, after viewing the sender's message. The set of possible actions is $$\mathcal A= \{a_1, a_2, a_3,\ldots, a_j\}$$."/>
</outline>
<outline text="The two players receive payoffs dependent on the sender's type, the message chosen by the sender and the action chosen by the receiver"/>
                            </outline>
