                            <outline text="Overview #h "/>
                            <outline text="Small Taxonomy #slide ">
<outline text="Stochastic Game: transition function depends on the history "/>
<outline text="Stochastic Games #slide ">
    <outline text="A dynamic game that involves probabilistic transitions through several states of the system"/>
    <outline text="Has a start state: players choose actions and receive a payoff that depends on the current state of the game"/>
    <outline text="Then the game transitions into a new state, with a probability based upon players actions and the current state"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Finite Stochastic Games #slide ">
    <outline text="In these games, there are a finite number of players and a finite number of states. "/>
    <outline text="The outcome of the game depends on the actions taken by the players and the probability of transitioning from one state to another."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Continuous Stochastic Games #slide ">
    <outline text="In these games, the state space is continuous, "/>
    <outline text="and the outcome of the game depends on the actions taken by the players and the probability of transitioning from one state to another."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Markov Decision Processes (MDPs) #slide ">
    <outline text="MDPs can be seen as a special case of stochastic games"/>
    <outline text="There is only one player, "/>
    <outline text="Outcome of the game depends only on:">
        <outline text="the player's actions "/>
        <outline text="the probability of transitioning from one state to another."/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Partially Observable Markov Decision Processes (POMDPs) #slide ">
    <outline text="POMDPs are a more general form of MDPs"/>
    <outline text="The state of the game is not directly observable"/>
    <outline text="However it can be inferred from the observations made by the player."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Markov Games #slide ">
    <outline text="Linear Markov Game: transition function depends only on the current state "/>
    <outline text="Extend the concept of Markov decision processes (MDPs) to the multiplayer setting"/>
    <outline text="Multiple agents interact with each other in a shared environment"/>
    <outline text="Actions affect not only the immediate reward but also the state of the environment, which influences future rewards."/>
    <outline text="New state does not depend on previous history though"/>
    <outline text="Competitive Game: 2 player Zero Sum Markov Game"/>
</outline>
<outline text="States #slide ">
    <outline text="Like in an MDP, the state of a Markov game satisfies the Markov property, meaning that the current state captures all relevant information about the past history of the game. However, in a Markov game, each agent's action affects not only the immediate reward but also the transition function, which determines the probability distribution over the next state given the current state and joint actions of all agents."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Bayesian Games #slide ">
    <outline text="In Bayesian games, the players have incomplete information about the state of the game, "/>
    <outline text="and the state of the game is determined by a random variable."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Evolutionary Games #slide ">
    <outline text="In these games, the players are not rational decision-makers, but instead follow simple rules that determine their behavior. "/>
    <outline text="The outcome of the game is determined by the frequency of each player's behavior in the population."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Repeated Games #slide ">
    <outline text="In these games, the players interact repeatedly over time"/>
    <outline text="The outcome of the game depends on the history of previous interactions."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Stochastic Differential Games #slide ">
    <outline text="These games are a more general form of stochastic games in which the state space evolves continuously over time, "/>
    <outline text="and the outcome of the game depends on the players' actions and the stochastic differential equations that govern the evolution of the state space."/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Notations -- GameSec #slide ">
<outline text="We assume A dynamic game states of which changes over time "/>
<outline text="A game different in each state "/>
<outline text="Simultaneous actions of players A function describes the dynamic evolution of the system w.r.t the simultaneous plays and the state "/>
<outline text="When the evolution function is random it is a stochastic game. "/>
                            </outline>
