<outline text="SHAPLEY STOPPING GAME">
    <outline text="Model Motivation #slide ">
        <outline text="First description of stochastic game in seminal paper"/>
        <outline text="Stochastic Repeated Matrix Game "/>
        <outline text="Maps:">
            <outline text="Payoff map $$G: \mathcal{P} \times  \mathcal{S} \rightarrow \R$$ is the same irrespective of current state"/>
            <outline text="State transition map $$T: \mathcal{P} \times  \mathcal{S} \times S \rightarrow {S}$$ depends linearly on chosen strategy and given state, hence a bilinear map"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Description #slide ">
        <outline text="The same game $$G$$ proceeds in steps according to transition probabilities $$0\le s_{ij}\le 1$$"/>
        <outline text="If row player choose a strategy $$i$$ and column player chooses $$j$$, then ">
            <outline text="the game stops with probability $$s_{ij}$$"/>
            <outline text="the game continues with probability $$1-s_{ij}$$"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="The state transition function is linearly depending on both players' strategies "/>
        <outline text="Hence it is a function bilinear in the strategies"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="States and Transitions #slide ">
        <outline text="There are two states: play and stop."/>
        <outline text="One is transient, the other absorbing."/>
        <outline text="Transition matrix $$P$$ is encoding map ">
            <outline text="$$T: \mathcal{X}\times S \times \mathcal{Y} \rightarrow S$$, $$(x^\top,s,y) \mapsto T(x^\top,s,y):=x^\top Py$$."/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Strategic State Transition Diagram #slide ">
        <outline text="![Pasted image](https://dynalist.io/u/U5kmS8j_Y7NSIxSgU5Qh6an5) "/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Stage Games #slide "/>
    <outline text="Payoffs #slide  "/>
    <outline text="Playing the Game #slide ">
        <outline text="Define $$s=\min_{i,j} s_{ij}$$"/>
        <outline text="Hence, probability that game does not stop after $$t$$ steps is $$P(\text{&quot;More than t steps&quot;})\le (1-s)^t$$"/>
        <outline text="So game finishes in finite number of steps"/>
        <outline text="Payoffs accumulate throughout game"/>
        <outline text="Defining the bound $$M=\max | a_{ij} |$$ we find a bound for the expected payoff as">
            <outline text="$$M + (1-s)M + (1-s)^2M + \cdots = M/s$$."/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Stationary Solutions #slide ">
        <outline text="Assume we play the same strategy $$(x^\top, y)$$ and repeat with probability $$p=x^\top P y$$"/>
        <outline text="The probability that the state after $$k$$ iterations is still &quot;play&quot; is $$p^k$$"/>
        <outline text="The probability that the game stops in the $$k$$th iteration is $$p^{k-1}(1-p)$$"/>
        <outline text="The overall payoff is $$u=\sum_i x^\top A yp^i$$"/>
        <outline text="$$v=\sum_i x^\top P^i y$$"/>
        <outline text="The strategy leading to this is $$(x^\top P^k, P^ky)$$"/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="MARKOV GAME">
