<outline text="TWO-STAGE REPEATED GAME">
    <outline text="Repeated Games #h ">
        <outline text="Maps:">
            <outline text="Payoff map $$G: \mathcal{P} \times  \mathcal{S} \times S  \rightarrow \R$$"/>
            <outline text="State transition map $$T: \mathcal{P} \times  \mathcal{S} \times S \rightarrow {S}$$"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Definition #slide ">
            <outline text="An [extensive form game](https://en.wikipedia.org/api/rest_v1/page/mobile-html/Extensive_form_game) that consists of a number of repetitions of some base game (called a stage game). "/>
            <outline text="The stage game is usually one of the well-studied [2-person games](https://en.wikipedia.org/api/rest_v1/page/mobile-html/List_of_games_in_game_theory). "/>
            <outline text="Repeated games capture the idea that a player will have to take into account the impact of his or her current action on the future actions of other players; this impact is sometimes called his or her reputation.  "/>
            <outline text="Single stage game or single shot game are names for non-repeated games."/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Repeated Games #h ">
            <outline text="Stochastic Games #slide ">
                <outline text="We now look at repeatedly playing these games $$G_1$$ and $$G_2$$. "/>
                <outline text="We will define some stopping conditions to prevent an infinite duration. "/>
                <outline text="This yields __stochastic games__, as introduced by (Shapley, 1953). "/>
                <outline text="Let us focus on repeating $$G_1$$ first. "/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="The Stochastic Game  $$G^*_1$$ #slide">
                <outline text="Consider the stopping matrix $$S=\begin{pmatrix} 1&amp; s\\ s &amp;1  \\  \end{pmatrix}$$ where $$0&lt;s &lt; 1$$. "/>
                <outline text="There will be a finite sequence $$i=1,\ldots,N$$ of the __stage-game__ $$G^*_1$$. "/>
                <outline text="The players decide on their strategies $$x_i$$ and $$y_i$$"/>
                <outline text="The payoffs of each stage are added"/>
                <outline text="After a stage, the game stops if:">
                    <outline text="The system can trust a cooperative Wizard"/>
                    <outline text="The system detects a non-cooperative Wizard"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Otherwise, it continues with probability $$1-s$$"/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Game Analysis -- Questions #slide ">
                <outline text="What are the NEs?"/>
                <outline text="As a parameter of $$s$$?"/>
                <outline text="Good values for $$s$$?"/>
                <outline text="How do we interpret mixed strategies?"/>
                <outline text="Run simulation -- mixed strategies."/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Previous Work #slide ">
                <outline text="Shapley has shown that in the case of a matrix game (zero-sum, $$B=-A$$), there is a unique value $$v$$."/>
                <outline text="One can obtain this from a rational form $$v := \min_x \max_y \frac{xAy}{xSy}$$."/>
                <outline text="(Von Neumann, 1937) and (Loomis, 1946) have first shown the existence and uniqueness of this value."/>
                <outline text="(Thompson &amp; al) connect linear algebra concepts to the structure of optimal solutions."/>
                <outline text="More recent work? On bimatrix (non-zero sum) case?"/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Our Approach #slide ">
                <outline text="Following Thompson, we consider the matrix pencil $$P(\lambda)=A-\lambda S$$."/>
                <outline text="Concepts: generalised characteristic polynomial, eigenvalues and eigenvectors."/>
                <outline text="A fundamental result is due to Thompson et al.">
                    <outline text="https://dynalist.io/d/LEdIn-fQiooRnQn8D-7fFHVC#z=YSp1OMYk8Zhb6qGinGLbhdKe #wfe-ignore-item"/>
                </outline>
            </outline>
        </outline>
    </outline>
