                    <outline text="Security Games #h " _note="https://workflowy.com/#/929e463e968d&#xA;#GT #ch2 #small #big #decision #h #sg-field">
                        <outline text="Introduction #slide #IARIA">
                            <outline text="Security games model interaction between players:">
<outline text="attacker(s)"/>
<outline text="defender(s)"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="They assume that players are:">
<outline text="rational"/>
<outline text="non-cooperative "/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="All players seek to maximise their payoff (utility) functions."/>
                            <outline text="Our context: two-player, non-zero-sum complete information games."/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Notations and Definitions #slide ">
                            <outline text="Players">
<outline text="$$\mathcal{P} = \{\mathcal{A}, \mathcal{D}\}$$ where">
    <outline text="$$\mathcal{A}$$ -- attacker #notation"/>
    <outline text="$$\mathcal{D}$$ -- defender #notation"/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Strategies">
<outline text="$${\mathcal S}_\mathcal{A}$$ -- strategy set/space of attacker #GT "/>
<outline text="$${\mathcal S}_\mathcal{D}$$ -- strategy set/space of defender #GT "/>
<outline text="$$s_\mathcal{A} \in {\mathcal S}_\mathcal{A}$$ -- strategy of attacker (pure or mixed)"/>
<outline text="$$s_\mathcal{D} \in {\mathcal S}_\mathcal{D}$$ -- strategy of defender (pure or mixed)"/>
<outline text="$$s = (s_\mathcal{A}, s_\mathcal{D})$$ where $$s_\mathcal{A} \in {\mathcal S}_\mathcal{A}$$ and $$s_\mathcal{D} \in {\mathcal S}_\mathcal{D}$$: strategy profile where strategies are chosen from strategy spaces"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Utility Functions">
<outline text="$$u_\mathcal{A}$$ -- attacker's utility function #notation "/>
<outline text="$$u_\mathcal{D}$$ -- defender's utility function #notation "/>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Complete Information Security Games #slide #IARIA ">
                            <outline text="Introduction #slide #IARIA ">
<outline text="Complete information security games assume mutual knowledge of strategies, by both the attacker and defender. "/>
<outline text="In real-world scenarios, this could correspond to a situation where the attacker might be able to gain some knowledge. "/>
<outline text="For example, through:">
    <outline text="insider information"/>
    <outline text="information leakage"/>
    <outline text="reconnaissance"/>
</outline>
<outline text="The defender might be aware of potential attackers and their motivation through security assessment and risk analysis. "/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Massive 2-Player Complete Information Security Games #h ">
<outline text="Motivation #slide " complete="true">
    <outline text="Game-theoretic models that are motivated by real-world scenarios." complete="true"/>
    <outline text="Constraints in defense budget can be taken into account."/>
    <outline text="Big security games are usually non-zero-sum games."/>
    <outline text="Typically, they have 2 players but a large number of actions."/>
    <outline text="A compact notation helps with efficiently storing and solving the game."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Notations #slide " complete="true">
    <outline text="Let us fix some notations:">
        <outline text="$${\mathcal T} = \{t_1,\ldots,t_n\}$$ -- set of __targets__ (assets under attack),"/>
        <outline text="$${\mathcal R} = \{r_1,\ldots,r_m\}$$ -- set of __resources__, covering $$m \leq n$$ targets (implementing controls),"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Example: Case Study 1">
        <outline text="$$\{t_1,\ldots,t_n\}$$ -- targeted YouTube channels ($$n=31,000,000$$),"/>
        <outline text="$$\{r_1,\ldots,r_m\}$$ -- YouTube employees ($$m \ll n$$)."/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Strategies -- Attacker #slide " complete="true">
    <outline text="The attacker can choose between __pure__ or __mixed__ strategies.">
        <outline text="Pure strategy space:">
            <outline text="$$s_A= {\mathcal T}$$ -- the set of targets,"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Mixed strategy space:">
            <outline text="$$s_A= \{(q_1,q_2,\ldots q_n )\}$$ where $$0 \le q_j \le 1 $$ and $$\sum q_j=1 $$ represents the probability of attacking target $$t_i$$. "/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Example: Case Study 1">
        <outline text="The attacker can choose random YouTube channels as his targets, using an automated script. This implements a mixed strategy."/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Strategies -- Defender #slide " complete="true">
    <outline text="$${\mathcal S}$$ -- set of __feasible schedules__, representing specific allocations of resources to cover targets (respecting a finite budget constraint)."/>
    <outline text="There are $$d={n \choose m}$$ such feasible schedules."/>
    <outline text="Pure strategy:">
        <outline text="This is a feasible schedule $$s_D \in {\mathcal S}$$, covering $$m$$ out of $$n$$ targets."/>
        <outline text="Notation: $$s = \langle i_1,i_2,\ldots i_n \rangle$$  ($$i_j \in \{0, 1\}$$, $$\sum i_j = m$$).">
            <outline text="$$s \subset {\mathcal T}$$ ($$|s| = m$$) -- set notation  #wfe-ignore-item "/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Mixed strategy:">
        <outline text="$$s_D = ( p_1,p_2,\ldots p_d )$$ where $$0 \le p_j \le 1$$ are probabilities of using a feasible schedule."/>
        <outline text="This induces a __coverage vector__ $$c = \langle c_{1},\ldots, c_{n} \rangle$$, expressing the probability of protection for each of the targets."/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Utilities #slide " complete="true">
    <outline text="Compact notations: utility per use/attack of $$t_i$$">
        <outline text="$$u_D^c(t_i)$$ -- defender's utility when target $$t_i$$ is covered by at least one resource,"/>
        <outline text="$$u_D^u(t_i)$$ -- defender's utility for uncovered target $$t_i$$,"/>
        <outline text="$$u_A^c(t_i)$$ -- attacker's utility for a covered target $$t_i$$,"/>
        <outline text="$$u_A^u(t_i)$$ -- attacker's utility, when $$t_i$$ is uncovered."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="$$u_D^c(t_i) - u_D^u(t_i) = 0$$ if $$t_i$$ is not attacked."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Assumptions/Properties #slide" complete="true">
    <outline text="Applying resources to a target benefits the defender and hurts the attacker:">
        <outline text="$$\Delta u_D(t_i) := u_D^c(t_i) - u_D^u(t_i) &gt; 0$$ -- the defender's utility reduction due to loss of coverage on attack,"/>
        <outline text="$$\Delta u_A(t_i) :=  u_A^u(t_i)-u_A^c(t_i) &gt; 0$$ -- the attacker's utility gain when attacked target not covered."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="These assumptions are realistic, for the considered scenario."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Example: Case Study 1 #slide " complete="true">
    <outline text="YouTube Game in sparse notation:" _note="\begin{table}[]&#xA;\begin{tabular}{l|ll|ll|ll|ll|}&#xA;\cline{2-9}&#xA; &amp; \multicolumn{2}{c|}{$t_{1}$} &amp; \multicolumn{2}{c|}{$t_{2}$} &amp; \multicolumn{2}{c|}{$t_{3}$} &amp; \multicolumn{2}{c|}{$t_{4}$} \\ \cline{2-9} &#xA; &amp; c &amp; u &amp; c &amp; u &amp; c &amp; u &amp; c &amp; u \\ \hline&#xA;\multicolumn{1}{|l|}{D} &amp; \multicolumn{1}{l|}{7} &amp; 3 &amp; \multicolumn{1}{l|}{5} &amp; 1 &amp; \multicolumn{1}{l|}{4} &amp; 3 &amp; \multicolumn{1}{l|}{3} &amp; 0\\ \hline&#xA;\multicolumn{1}{|l|}{A} &amp; \multicolumn{1}{l|}{0} &amp; 1 &amp; \multicolumn{1}{l|}{1} &amp; 4 &amp; \multicolumn{1}{l|}{0} &amp; 5 &amp; \multicolumn{1}{l|}{2} &amp; 3 \\ \hline&#xA;\end{tabular}&#xA;\end{table}"/>
    <outline text="Using bimatrix game notation, we have:">
        <outline text="$$A=\begin{pmatrix} 7 &amp; 1 &amp; 3 &amp; 0 \\ 3&amp; 5 &amp; 3 &amp; 0 \\ 3&amp; 1 &amp; 4 &amp; 0 \\ 3&amp; 1 &amp; 3 &amp; 3 \\ \end{pmatrix}$$, $$B=\begin{pmatrix} 0 &amp; 4 &amp; 5 &amp; 3 \\ 1&amp; 1 &amp; 5 &amp; 3 \\ 1 &amp;  4&amp; 0 &amp; 3 \\ 1&amp; 4 &amp; 5 &amp; 2 \\ \end{pmatrix}$$ #eyo-style:Normal "/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Example (continued) #slide ">
    <outline text="The unique NE solution $$(x^*, y^*) $$ to this game is: $$x^*= (0, 0.39, 0.43, 0.17)$$ and $$y^*= (0, 0.16, 0.63, 0.21 )$$."/>
    <outline text="The corresponding expected payoffs are 2.68 and 2.83."/>
    <outline text="These are coverage vectors, from which suitable feasible schedules can be computed."/>
</outline>
