                            <outline text="Goal: Identify trade-offs between objectives."/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Pareto Optimality (Multi-Criteria Optimisation) #slide">
                            <outline text="Definition: A solution is Pareto optimal if no other feasible solution improves one objective without worsening at least one other."/>
                            <outline text="Formal (minimisation case): Let $$f: X "/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Visualising the Pareto Front #slide">
                            <outline text="The Pareto front consists of all Pareto optimal solutions in objective space."/>
                            <outline text="Represents the best trade-offs between competing objectives."/>
                            <outline text="Often visualised in 2D with dominated points below the curve."/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Partial Orders and Pareto Dominance #slide">
                            <outline text="Pareto dominance defines a partial order on $$\mathbb{R}^k$$: $$u \prec v \iff (\forall i,\ u_i \leq v_i) \land (\exists j,\ u_j &lt; v_j)$$"/>
                            <outline text="This relation is:">
<outline text="Reflexive"/>
<outline text="Antisymmetric"/>
<outline text="Transitive"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Pareto optimal points are the maximal elements under this partial order."/>
                        </outline>
