                    <outline text="Linear Programming #h" _note="#simplex ">
                        <outline text="Introduction #slide "/>
                        <outline text="LP Standard Canonical Form #slide ">
                            <outline text="A standard form of the LP is to choose $$y_1,\ldots,y$$, to maximize">
<outline text="$$ c_1y_1 + \cdots + c_ny$$, "/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="subject to the constraints">
<outline text="$$a_{11}y_1 + \cdots + a_{1n}y_n \le b_1$$"/>
<outline text="  $$\vdots$$"/>
<outline text="$$a_{m1}y_1 + \cdots + a_{mn}y_n \le b_m$$"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="and $$b_i\ge 0$$, $$y_j \ge 0$$ for $$ i = 1,\ldots,m$$ and $$ j = 1,\ldots,n$$."/>
                            <outline text="In compact notation this is:">
<outline text="MAX $$c^T y$$  ST $$Ay\le b$$ and $$y\ge 0$$. "/>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="LP Augmented Canonical Form #slide #simplex:augmented ">
                            <outline text="Idea: convert the system of inequality constraints into a system of equations, subject to some positivity conditions."/>
                            <outline text="The __augmented canonical__ form of the LP is: ">
<outline text="Find $$y_1,\ldots,y_n$$ to maximise">
    <outline text="$$z= c_1y_1 + \cdots + c_ny+d$$"/>
</outline>
<outline text="subject to the constraints">
    <outline text="$$a_{11}y_1 + \cdots + a_{1n}y_n + {\hat{y}}_1= b_1$$,"/>
    <outline text="  $$\vdots$$"/>
    <outline text="$$a_{m1}y_1 + \cdots + a_{mn}y_n+ {\hat{y}}_{m}= b_m$$"/>
</outline>
<outline text="where $$y_j \ge 0$$ for $$ j = 1,\ldots,n$$ and $${\hat{y}}_j \ge 0$$ for $$ j = 1,\ldots,m$$."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="The $$\hat{y}_j$$ are called the __slack variables__ or __basic solutions__. "/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="The Revised Simplex Method #h">
                            <outline text="Using Matrix Notation #slide ">
<outline text="The augmented/canonical form contains a linear system which can be expressed using matrices:">
    <outline text="$$\max z := c^\top x+d:$$">
        <outline text="$$ Ax+\hat{x}=b \,\land \, z-c^\top x=d \Longleftrightarrow $$"/>
        <outline text="$$\begin{pmatrix}  0&amp; A&amp;I\\  1 &amp; -c^\top&amp;0\\ \end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}  z\\ x  \\  \hat{x}  \\   \end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix}   b  \\ d  \\ \end{pmatrix}$$. "/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Here, $$x$$ contains the __non-basic solutions__ and $$\hat{x}$$ the __basic solutions__."/>
<outline text="A __feasible solution__ is any solution $$\begin{pmatrix} x \\ \hat{x}\end{pmatrix}$$, satisfying the constraints."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Main Idea #slide ">
<outline text="Denote the system during a step of iteration $$k$$ as:">
    <outline text="$$\begin{pmatrix}  0&amp; {A}_{{k}}&amp;I\\  1 &amp; -{c}^\top_{{k}}&amp;0\\ \end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix} z\\ x_{{k}} \\  \hat{x}_{{k}}  \\  \end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix} {b}_{{k}}  \\  {d}_{{k}} \\  \end{pmatrix}$$."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Successive left-multiplication with matrix $$R_{{k+1}}$$ implements row-operations, increasing the value of $$z$$:">
    <outline text="$$\begin{pmatrix}  0&amp; {A}_{{k+1}}&amp;I\\  1 &amp; -{c}^\top_{{k+1}}&amp;0\\ \end{pmatrix}=R_{{k}}\begin{pmatrix}  0&amp; {A}_{{k}}&amp;I\\  1 &amp; -{c}^\top_{{k}}&amp;0\\ \end{pmatrix}$$,"/>
    <outline text="$$\begin{pmatrix} {b}_{{k+1}}  \\  {d}_{{k+1}} \\  \end{pmatrix}=P_{{k}}\begin{pmatrix} {b}_{{k}}  \\  {d}_{{k}} \\  \end{pmatrix}$$."/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Initialisation and Termination #slide #simplex:exit ">
<outline text="We start with $$b_0=b, d_0=0$$ and put $$x_{0} =0$$ and $$\hat{x}_{0}=b_0$$, satisfying the lower block-row. #simplex:init"/>
<outline text="Iterations terminate once the row-vector $$-{c}^\top_{k}$$ is nonnegative. "/>
<outline text="Reason:">
    <outline text="Maximising $$z_k= {d}^\top_{k}+{c}^\top_{k} x_k$$ and $${c}^\top_{k} \leqq 0$$ is solved by $$x_k=0$$. "/>
</outline>
<outline text="Hence:">
    <outline text="$$z= {d}_k$$ is the optimal value."/>
    <outline text="$$(x,\hat{x})=(0,\hat{x}_{{k}})$$ is a feasible solution for the augmented system"/>
    <outline text="CORRECT THIS:, hence of the original LP.  "/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Pivot-Step #slide #simplex:pivot ">
<outline text="In this step, subject to some assumptions, fix a row index $$i$$ and column index $$j$$. "/>
<outline text="Denote the $$j$$th column of a matrix $$A$$ as $$\text{col}(A,j)$$."/>
<outline text="Assume we can form $$R$$ non-singular such that $$R \;\text{col}(A,j) =  e_i $$."/>
<outline text="Multiplying the entire system of linear equations by $$R$$ on the left allows swapping the non-basic variable $$x_j$$ and basic variable $$\hat{x}_i$$."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Determining $$i$$ and $$j$$ #slide ">
<outline text="In this step, a suitable row index $$i$$ and column index $$j$$ need to be found. "/>
<outline text="The previous operation increases $$z$$, provided the $$i$$th entry of the vector $$R\tilde{b}$$ is greater than zero. "/>
<outline text="This is equivalent to stating ">
    <outline text="$$\exist i: b/a_{ij} &gt; 0$$"/>
</outline>
<outline text="We then chose $$i := \argmax_i \{ b/a_{ij} \}$$."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="New System #slide ">
<outline text="After a Pivot-Step, the new system is"/>
