<outline text="Original Economics Definition #slide #teaching #research" complete="true">
    <outline text="In the original context of mathematical economics \cite{Neumann1945-ab}:">
        <outline text="Definition of Von Neumann __balanced growth path__: $$(\alpha,x)$$ such that $$\alpha$$ is maximal subject to $$x^\top(B-\alpha A) \ge 0$$.">
            <outline text="$$\alpha$$: expansion factor"/>
            <outline text="$$x$$: intensity vector"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Definition of Von Neumann __price problem__: $$(\beta,p)$$ such that $$\beta$$ is minimal subject to $$(B-\alpha A)p \le 0$$.">
            <outline text="$$\beta$$: interest factor"/>
            <outline text="$$p$$: price vector"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="One makes the following assumption: $$A+B&gt;0$$."/>
    <outline text="The result is then, that at least one such solution exist, and that it holds $$0&lt;\beta\le \alpha$$."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Min-Max Definition #slide ">
    <outline text="In Game-theoretic context \cite{}:"/>
    <outline text="$$(\alpha,x)$$ such that $$\alpha$$ is maximal subject to $$(A-\alpha B)x \ge 0$$."/>
    <outline text="$$(\beta,p)$$ such that $$\beta$$ is minimal subject to $$p(A-\alpha B) \le 0$$."/>
    <outline text="Assumption: $$A+B&gt;0$$."/>
    <outline text="Results:">
        <outline text="Solutions exist."/>
        <outline text="It holds $$0&lt;\beta\le \alpha$$."/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Generalised Definition #slide ">
    <outline text="A triplet $$(x, y,\lambda)$$, with $$x\geqq0$$, $$y\geqq 0$$, $$\lambda &gt; 0$$, is a __generalised equilibrium solution__ for the von Neumann technology VNM($$A, B$$) if it satisfies the following system:">
        <outline text="$$x^\top A \geqq \lambda x^\top B$$,"/>
        <outline text="$$Ay \leqq \lambda By$$."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="So we do not need $$x^\top Ay&gt; 0$$. "/>
</outline>
<outline text="Active Sub-pencil Definition #slide ">
    <outline text="Thompson et al \cite{Thompson1971-or} show that "/>
    <outline text="This generalises results by Shapley, see also Karlin's book, for game theory"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Equality Definition #slide ">
    <outline text="A quadruplet $$(x, y, , )$$, $$x\geqq 0$$, $$y \geqq 0$$, $$\alpha \neq 0$$, $$\beta \neq 0$$ is an __equilibrium solution__ for the von Neumann model VN$$(B, A)$$ if it satisfies the following system:">
        <outline text="$$ x^\top A  \ge  \alpha x^\top B$$,"/>
        <outline text="$$ x^\top A y= \alpha  x^\top By$$,"/>
        <outline text="$$ Ay \le \beta By$$,"/>
        <outline text="$$ x^\top Ay = x^\top \beta By $$,"/>
        <outline text="$$x^\top Ay &gt; 0$$."/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Pencil Notation #slide ">
    <outline text="We can re-write the above inequalities using matrix pencil notation:">
        <outline text="$$ x^\top (A  - \alpha B)\ge 0$$,"/>
        <outline text="$$ x^\top (A - \alpha  B)y = 0$$,"/>
        <outline text="$$ (A  -\beta B)y\le 0 $$,"/>
        <outline text="$$ x^\top (A - \beta B)y = 0$$,"/>
        <outline text="$$x^\top Ay &gt; 0$$."/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Simplification #slide ">
    <outline text="Lemma: If $$(\bar{x}, \bar{y}, \bar{\alpha} ,\bar{\beta})$$ is an equilibrium solution, then $$\bar{\alpha}=\bar{\beta}&gt;0$$."/>
    <outline text="Proof:">
        <outline text="$$0&lt;\bar{x}^\top A\bar{y}= \alpha\bar{x}^\top B\bar{y}=\beta\bar{x}^\top B\bar{y}$$"/>
        <outline text=" ![Pasted image](https://dynalist.io/u/KY41W0xBeMdX3mvJ9H06H-cj) "/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Simplified Definition #slide ">
