<outline text="Suitability for Model: Digital Productivity as a Circular Economy #h ">
    <outline text="Introduction #slide ">
        <outline text="Circular economy:">
            <outline text="Focuses on minimizing waste and maximizing resource reuse within a closed-loop system."/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Digital productivity:">
            <outline text="Refers to the effective use of digital tools, platforms, and processes to create value."/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Digital productivity exhibits traits of a circular economy #slide ">
        <outline text="Reuse of digital resources:">
            <outline text="Digital tools, software, and platforms can be reused indefinitely without degradation."/>
            <outline text="Example: Open-source software reused and adapted across industries."/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Knowledge as a renewable resource:">
            <outline text="Knowledge work outputs (e.g., reports, analyses) can be reused as inputs for future projects."/>
            <outline text="Example: Insights from one project informing strategic decisions for others."/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Low marginal cost of replication:">
            <outline text="Digital goods (e.g., software, data, reports) can be duplicated at almost zero cost."/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Conclusion #slide ">
        <outline text="Digital productivity can be partially seen as a circular economy:">
            <outline text="Strengths:">
                <outline text="The reuse and low-cost replication of digital resources align with circular principles."/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Limitations:">
                <outline text="Energy use and hardware waste are significant barriers to full circularity."/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Future direction:">
                <outline text="Emphasizing green computing and sustainable digital practices can help bridge the gap."/>
            </outline>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Challenges in achieving circularity ">
            <outline text="Digital waste:">
                <outline text="Obsolete hardware, e-waste, and outdated systems contribute to resource inefficiency."/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Energy consumption:">
                <outline text="Data centers and cloud computing require significant energy, impacting sustainability."/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Security and obsolescence:">
                <outline text="Older digital systems may become vulnerable, limiting their long-term reusability."/>
            </outline>
        </outline>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Von Neumann Growth Model for Knowledge Work Scenario #h ">
    <outline text="Goal #slide ">
        <outline text="To apply the VNM to a digital productivity scenario where knowledge workers are assigned to projects, working on tasks. "/>
        <outline text="The goal is to maximise productivity output based on a suitable assignment of intensities, while minimising the required salaries."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Model Definition #slide ">
        <outline text="Input matrix: represents the amount of each task required to produce a unit of project output">
            <outline text="Each row accumulates the extent to which a specific task is required for the various projects"/>
            <outline text="Each column specifies the involved tasks for a specific project"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Output matrix: represents the goods (tasks) produced by each project:"/>
        <outline text="Intensity and Price Levels: Worker Allocations and Costs">
            <outline text="$$w=(w_1,w_2)$$ where $$w_1, w_2$$ are the time and effort (productivity or depth level) allocated to the projects 1 and 2. "/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Equilibrium Solutions #slide "/>
    <outline text="Benefits #slide "/>
    <outline text="Example #h ">
        <outline text="Model Setup -- Technological Production #slide ">
            <outline text="Sectors: knowledge work projects (matrix columns)">
                <outline text="Project 1: Focuses on strategic planning."/>
                <outline text="Project 2 (matrix rows): Focuses on operational research."/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Goods: knowledge work tasks">
                <outline text="Task 1: Report Writing (e.g., creating strategic or operational reports)."/>
                <outline text="Task 2: Data Analysis (e.g., processing data for decision-making)."/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Intensity vector: allocated efforts/workers">
                <outline text="This is  $$w=(w_1,w_2)$$ where $$w_1, w_2$$ are the time and effort (productivity or depth level) allocated to the projects 1 and 2. "/>
            </outline>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Input Matrix #slide " complete="true">
            <outline text="Consider the following matrix:">
                <outline text="$$A = \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; 1 \\ 1 &amp; 3 \end{bmatrix}.$$"/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Project 1 requires 2 units of Report Writing and 1 unit of Data Analysis."/>
            <outline text="Project 2 requires 1 unit of Report Writing and 3 units of Data Analysis."/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Output Matrix #slide " complete="true">
            <outline text="Consider the following matrix:">
                <outline text="$$B = \begin{bmatrix} 4 &amp; 1 \\ 2 &amp; 3 \end{bmatrix}.$$"/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Project 1 produces 4 units of Report Writing and 2 units of Data Analysis."/>
            <outline text="Project 2 produces 1 unit of Report Writing and 3 units of Data Analysis."/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Growth Condition #slide ">
            <outline text="The growth inequality">
                <outline text="$$(1 + g) x^\top A  \leq x^\top B$$"/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="where $$g&gt;0$$ and $$ x = \begin{bmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \end{bmatrix} $$ represents the production levels of Project 1 and Project 2."/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Solve for Growth Rate #slide ">
            <outline text="Expand the growth inequality into two conditions:"/>
            <outline text="1. For Project 1:">
                <outline text="$$            (1 + g)(2x_1 + x_2) \leq 3x_1 + x_2.$$"/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="2. For Project 2:">
                <outline text="$$            (1 + g)(x_1 + 2x_2) \leq x_1 + 3x_2.$$"/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Solving these yields:"/>
            <outline text="$$        g^* = 0.5 \quad \text{(50\% maximum growth rate)}.$$"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Equilibrium Production Levels #slide ">
            <outline text="At the maximum growth rate $$ g^* $$, equilibrium production levels satisfy:"/>
            <outline text="$$        x_1 = 2 \quad \text{(output from Project 1)}, \quad x_2 = 1 \quad \text{(output from Project 2)}.$$"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Model Setup -- Economical Pricing #slide ">
            <outline text="Dual price vector:">
                <outline text="$$        p = \begin{bmatrix} p_1 \\ p_2 \end{bmatrix},$$"/>
                <outline text="where $$ p_1 $$ is the value per unit of Report Writing and $$ p_2 $$ is the value per unit of Data Analysis."/>
            </outline>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Interpretation #slide ">
            <outline text="Inputs ($$ A $$): Project 1 relies more on Report Writing, while Project 2 relies more on Data Analysis."/>
            <outline text="Outputs ($$ B $$):Project 1 emphasizes producing reports; Project 2 emphasizes producing data insights."/>
            <outline text="Maximum Growth Rate ($$ g^* $$):">
                <outline text="The tasks can grow at a maximum rate of 50\%, given the balance of inputs and outputs."/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Equilibrium Values:">
                <outline text="Project Outputs: Project 1 should produce twice as much as Project 2."/>
                <outline text="Task Values: Report Writing is valued twice as much as Data Analysis."/>
            </outline>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Discussion #slide "/>
    <outline text="INBOX #ignore-outline ">
        <outline text="Solving:">
            <outline text="$$        p^T B = (1 + g^*) p^T A,$$"/>
            <outline text="yields:"/>
            <outline text="$$        p_1 = 2, \quad p_2 = 1 \quad \text{(equilibrium task values)}.$$"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
</outline>
