<outline text="Example: A 2x2 Highly Interconnected System #slide #teaching ">
    <outline text="Model Parameters:">
        <outline text="Input matrix $$ A $$: Represents resources required for production."/>
        <outline text="Output matrix $$ B $$: Represents resources produced by production."/>
        <outline text="Let">
            <outline text="$$        A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 1 \\ 1 &amp; 1 \end{bmatrix}, \quad         B = \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; 1 \\ 1 &amp; 2 \end{bmatrix}.$$"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Interpretation:">
        <outline text="Input Matrix $$ A $$:">
            <outline text="Every unit of output from any sector requires 1 unit of every input."/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Output Matrix $$ B $$:">
            <outline text="Sector 1 produces 2 units of Good 1 and 1 unit of Good 2."/>
            <outline text="Sector 2 produces 1 unit of Good 1 and 2 units of Good 2."/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Example: Independent System #slide #teaching">
    <outline text="A matrix AA with all entries equal to 1 reflects a system of **uniform interdependence and balanced resource usage**, "/>
    <outline text="which has strong symmetry but also potential vulnerabilities if outputs fail to exceed inputs."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Production Model #slide #teaching "/>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="WATER RESOURCE MANAGEMENT  #hh"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="INBOX #ignore-outline ">
                        <outline text="Implications of A=[1111]A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 1 \\ 1 &amp; 1 \end{bmatrix}:"/>
                        <outline text="1. Uniform Dependence Across Goods and Sectors:">
                            <outline text="Each sector consumes **one unit of each good** to produce one unit of output."/>
                            <outline text="For instance: ">
<outline text="In the LAN-DMZ network security example: ">
    <outline text="The LAN requires **1 Firewall with Router** and **1 PC Workstation** to produce its security benefits."/>
    <outline text="The DMZ requires **1 File Server** and **1 Router with Internet Access** for its security benefits.2. Balanced Input Structure:"/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="No good is more or less critical than others; all goods are consumed in equal amounts for production."/>
                            <outline text="This creates a symmetrical dependency where every sector equally relies on all the goods.3. Strong Coupling of Sectors:"/>
                            <outline text="The sectors are tightly integrated, as each one depends equally on the outputs of all sectors (since all goods are required in equal proportions)."/>
                            <outline text="For example, in a broader economic model, this could reflect industries where every sector needs contributions from all others in a balanced way (e.g., a perfectly interconnected supply chain).Effect on Growth Dynamics"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="The growth inequality is:"/>
                        <outline text="(1+g)AxBx.(1 + g) A x \leq B x.1. Input Consumption:"/>
                        <outline text="With AA having all ones, the input required by the system is:"/>
                        <outline text="Ax=[x1+x2x1+x2].A x = \begin{bmatrix} x_1 + x_2 \\ x_1 + x_2 \end{bmatrix}.Here, each sector requires the sum of the outputs from all sectors to operate."/>
                        <outline text="2. Growth Rate Condition:"/>
                        <outline text="For the system to grow, the outputs BxB x must sufficiently exceed the inputs AxA x. If BB has larger entries (e.g., B=[2112]B = \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; 1 \\ 1 &amp; 2 \end{bmatrix}), the system can sustain growth because the outputs per unit of input exceed the inputs required for production."/>
                        <outline text="3. Limiting Behavior:"/>
                        <outline text="If BB is also a matrix with all ones (e.g., B=[1111]B = \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 1 \\ 1 &amp; 1 \end{bmatrix}), the system cannot grow (g=0g = 0). This is because the outputs produced exactly match the inputs required, leaving no surplus for expansion."/>
                        <outline text="Interpretation in Real-World Contexts"/>
                        <outline text="1. Network Security (LAN and DMZ Example):"/>
                        <outline text="If AA has all ones:">
                            <outline text="Both the LAN and DMZ require equal contributions from all networked appliances to produce security benefits."/>
                            <outline text="The system is highly interdependent; improving or maintaining one sectors security depends equally on the contributions from the other.2. General Economics:"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="If all industries consume equal amounts of all goods for production, it may indicate:">
                            <outline text="A highly interconnected, **egalitarian economy**, where no industry dominates."/>
                            <outline text="However, it might also signify a **fragile system**, as disruptions in any sector propagate equally across all others.Key Insight:"/>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
